m}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |title=The 16th Annual ACTRA Awards in Toronto Nominees |url=https://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/the-16th-annual-actra-awards-in-toronto-nominees-669015333.html |website=www.newswire.ca |accessdate=20 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|4855517}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* {{Instagram}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liu, Simu}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Chinese emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Harbin]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian television writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male actors of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian male actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Short description|Canadian actor}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Simu Liu\n| image              = Simu Liu by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| caption            = Liu at [[San Diego Comic-Con]] in 2019\n| native_name        =\n| native_name_lang   = \n| pronunciation      = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1989|4|19|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Harbin]], [[Heilongjiang]], China\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (enter DEATH date then BIRTH date (e.g., ...|1908|31|8|1967|28|2}} use both this parameter and |birth_date to display the person's date of birth, date of death, and age at death) -->\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| body_discovered    = \n| resting_place      = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| burial_place       = <!-- may be used instead of resting_place and resting_place_coordinates (displays \"Burial place\" as label) -->\n| burial_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality        = Canadian\n| home_town          = [[Mississauga]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| residence          = [[Toronto]], Ontario, Canada<br />[[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Actor, writer, [[stuntman]]\n| years_active       = 2012\u2013present\n| spouse             = <!-- Use article title or common name -->\n| partner            = <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| children           = \n| parents            = <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n| mother             = <!-- may be used (optionally with father parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| father             = <!-- may be used (optionally with mother parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| relatives          = \n| family             = \n| callsign           = \n| awards             = \n| website            = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module             = {{Chinese |child = yes|t=\u5289\u601d\u6155|s=\u5218\u601d\u6155|p=Li\u00fa S\u012bm\u00f9|bpmf=\u310c\u3127\u3121\u02ca \u3119 \u3107\u3128\u02cb|j=Lau4 Si1 Mou6}}\n}}\n'''Simu Liu''' ({{zh|s=\u5218\u601d\u6155}}; born April 19, 1989) is a Canadian actor, writer and stuntman. He is best known for the role of Jung in the [[CBC Television]] sitcom ''[[Kim's Convenience (TV series)|Kim's Convenience]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kim's Convenience \u2013 CBC Media Centre|url=http://www.cbc.ca/mediacentre/program/kims-convenience|publisher=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=July 29, 2016}}</ref> He will portray the [[superhero]] [[Shang-Chi]] in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]], beginning with the film ''[[Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings]]'' (2021). He is set to become the first [[Asian people|Asian]] actor to lead a [[Marvel Studios]] film.\n\nHe received nominations at the [[ACTRA Award]]s and [[Canadian Screen Awards]] for his work in ''[[Blood and Water (TV series)|Blood and Water]]''.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|title=Simu Liu \u2013 Academy.ca|url=http://www.academy.ca/2017/simu-liu/|website=Academy.ca|accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nLiu was born in [[Harbin]], and immigrated to Canada at the age of five. He was raised in [[Erin Mills]], an area of [[Mississauga, Ontario]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Clay|first1=Chris|title=Mississauga-raised actor stars in Kim's Convenience, lands role in NBC's Taken|url=http://www.mississauga.com/whatson-story/6932846-mississauga-raised-actor-stars-in-kim-s-convenience-lands-role-in-nbc-s-taken/|accessdate=December 21, 2016|work=Mississauga News|date=October 27, 2016|location=Mississauga ON}}</ref> He attended [[University of Toronto Schools]] for high school. For post-secondary, Simu studied 2 years at [[University of Western Ontario]] and 2 years studying finance and accounting at the [[Ivey Business School]]. He worked as an accountant at [[Deloitte]] but was eventually laid off.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://kollaboration.org/podcast/kollabcast-episode-144-simus-convenience-w-simu-liu/|title=KollabCast Episode 144 \u2013 Simu's Convenience w/ Simu Liu|website=Kollaboration|access-date=2 November 2017}}</ref> He decided to explore other career options before deciding to pursue a career as an actor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://virtual.torontosun.com/doc/Toronto-Sun-Homes/toronto_sun_homes-1213/2015121001/4.html#4|title=Simu Liu for Toronto Sun|website=Toronto Sun|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161202171620/http://virtual.torontosun.com/doc/Toronto-Sun-Homes/toronto_sun_homes-1213/2015121001/4.html#4|archive-date=2016-12-02|url-status=dead|last1=Cornblum|first1=Marcy|access-date=December 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nLiu first got his start working as an [[Extra (acting)|extra]] on [[Guillermo del Toro]]'s ''[[Pacific Rim (film)|Pacific Rim]]''.<ref name=\":0\" /> His early onscreen credits include ''[[Nikita (TV series)|Nikita]]'' (2012) and ''[[Beauty & the Beast (2012 TV series)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' (2014). In 2015, he was a member of the ''[[Heroes Reborn (miniseries)|Heroes Reborn]]'' [[stunt]] team, appearing in three episodes as a [[stunt double]]. He next appeared as a series regular in the [[OMNI Television]] crime drama series ''[[Blood and Water (TV series)|Blood and Water]]'' (2015\u20132016), for which he received [[ACTRA Award|ACTRA]] and [[Canadian Screen Awards|Canadian Screen Award]] nominations in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.academy.ca/2017/simu-liu/|title=Simu Liu {{!}} Best Performance by an Actor in a Featured Supporting Role in a Dramatic Program {{!}} Canadian Screen Awards|date=January 8, 2017|work=Academy.ca|access-date=6 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/television/kims-convenience-wins-two-actra-awards/article34144736/|title=Kim's Convenience scores two prizes at ACTRA Awards|last=Service|first=Wire|date=February 27, 2017|access-date=6 July 2017}}</ref>[[File:SLiuRedCarpet.jpg|thumb|Liu in 2016|alt=|left|282x282px]]In 2016, Liu was cast as the ex-[[Central Intelligence Agency|CIA]] analyst Faaron, loosely modeled on real-life ex-analyst [[Rodney Faraon]], in the [[NBC]] prequel series ''[[Taken (2017 TV series)|Taken]]'' based on the [[Taken (franchise)|film franchise]] starring [[Liam Neeson]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mississauga.com/whatson-story/6932846-mississauga-raised-actor-stars-in-kim-s-convenience-lands-role-in-nbc-s-taken/|title=Mississauga-raised actor stars in Kim's Convenience, lands role in NBC's Taken {{!}} Mississauga.com|last=Clay|first=Chris|date=October 27, 2016|website=Mississauga.com|access-date=6 July 2017}}</ref> He also plays Jung in the [[CBC Television|CBC]] [[Kim's Convenience (TV series)|television adaptation]] of the hit Canadian play ''[[Kim's Convenience (play)|Kim's Convenience]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.macleans.ca/culture/television/kims-convenience-a-tv-first-that-doesnt-buckle-under-the-pressure/|title=Kim's Convenience: A TV first that doesn't buckle under the pressure \u2013 Macleans.ca|date=October 10, 2016|work=Maclean's|access-date=6 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nLater that year, Liu joined the cast of the hit [[BBC]]-[[Space (Canadian TV channel)|Space]] series ''[[Orphan Black]]'' for its fifth and final season<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/orphan-black-tatiana-maslany-final-season-5-cast-1201899944/|title=\u2018Orphan Black\u2019 Reveals Sneak Peek, Sets Cast for Fifth and Final Season|website=Variety|last1=Kelley|first1=Seth|accessdate=December 2, 2016}}</ref> and was nominated for a [[Dora Mavor Moore Award]] in the Outstanding Ensemble category alongside his castmates in the [[Factory Theatre]] remount of the play ''Banana Boys''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/arts/theatre-and-performance/article30201346.ece/BINARY/DORA+2016+NOMINEES+GRID.pdf|title=2016 DORA MAVOR MOORE AWARDS NOMINEES||publisher=[[Toronto Alliance for the Performing Arts]]|accessdate=October 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Liu joined the cast of the second season of [[Slasher (TV series)|''Slasher'']] as well as the [[City (TV network)|CityTV]] miniseries ''[[Bad Blood (TV series)|Bad Blood]]'', both as recurring characters.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shaftesbury.ca/slasher-wraps-production-on-season-2/|title=Shaftesbury {{!}} Slasher wraps production on Season 2|website=shaftesbury.ca|access-date=2 October 2017}}</ref> The following year, he appeared in the science fiction television series ''[[The Expanse (TV series)|The Expanse]]'' and the YouTube series ''[[Wong Fu Productions|Yappie]]''.\n\nIn early 2019, it was announced that Liu would be joining the cast of ABC's ''[[Fresh Off the Boat]]'' as a guest star.<ref>{{cite web |title='Kim's Convenience' Actor Simu Liu Will Guest Star On 'Fresh Off The Boat' |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2019/02/13/simu-liu-fresh-off-the-boat_a_23668071/ |website=HuffPost |accessdate=February 26, 2019}}</ref> He ended up starring as a noodle vendor named Willie in the 100th episode of the series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/fresh-off-the-boat-first-look-kims-convenience-star-simu-liu-drops-by-100th-episode-exclusive|title='Fresh Off the Boat': 'Kim's Convenience's' Simu Liu Drops by 100th|website=Entertainment Tonight|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-04}}</ref>\n\nAt [[San Diego Comic-Con|Comic-Con 2019]], it was announced that he has been cast as the [[Marvel Comics]] superhero [[Shang-Chi]] in the upcoming film ''[[Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings]]'', set in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]].  ''Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings'' will be Marvel's first [[Asian people|Asian]]-led film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/07/21/entertainment/simu-liu-marvel-shang-chi/index.html|title=Marvel's latest leading man Simu Liu will soon be a 'household name'|author=Sandra Gonzalez|website=CNN|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-49070232|title=Marvel Phase 4: A new era for diversity in Hollywood?|first=Neil|last=Smith|date=July 22, 2019|website=BBC}}</ref>  Liu had previously petitioned for the role on [[Twitter]] back in December 2018 when the movie was revealed to be in development.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/shang-chi-star-simu-liu-asked-marvel-about-playing-shan-1836603273|title=Shang-Chi star Simu Liu asked Marvel about playing Shang-Chi on Twitter 8 months ago|first=Gabe|last=Worgaftik|website=AV Club|date=July 22, 2019}}</ref>  Before his casting, Liu expressed interest in playing either [[Sunfire (comics)|Sunfire]] or [[Namor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9UEaUvr78L0|title=20 Questions With Simu Liu: Skincare, Korean BBQ, And Power Rangers &#124; NBC Asian America|via=www.youtube.com|publisher=NBC News|format=Video}}</ref>\n\nAside from his work performing onscreen, Liu is also a writer and filmmaker. Liu participated in the writing room for ''Blood and Water,'' during which he helped break the story for the show and wrote an episode for its second season.<ref name=\":1\" /> He also wrote an online piece for ''[[Maclean's]]'' magazine in December 2017 detailing his experiences growing up in an immigrant family. The article was later published in the magazine's January 2018 issue.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.macleans.ca/opinion/a-chinese-canadian-to-his-parents-privately-i-yearned-for-your-love/|title=A Chinese-Canadian to his parents: 'Privately, I yearned for your love' \u2013 Macleans.ca|date=December 4, 2017|work=Maclean's|access-date=8 December 2017}}</ref> As a filmmaker Liu has written, directed and produced short films which have screened and won awards in festivals across the US and Canada. His most recent short film ''Meeting Mommy,'' which he wrote and produced with [[Tina Jung]], was released in February 2018 on the [[Wong Fu Productions]] Youtube channel. The film amassed over 250,000 views in its first week.<ref>{{Citation|last=Wong Fu Productions|title=Meeting Mommy|date=February 28, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uI5_G-Hiu8U|accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe is currently developing long-form projects under his 4:12 Entertainment banner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weareresonate.com/2019/05/interview-kims-convenience-star-simu-liu-answers-your-questions/|title=INTERVIEW: Kim's Convenience star Simu Liu answers YOUR questions|last=Chew|first=Cohan|date=2019-05-23|website=Resonate|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Kollaboration SF Community Spotlight: Simu Liu|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jIxzdRZT_Pc|language=en|access-date=2020-01-17}}</ref>  \n\n== Accolades ==\nLiu was nominated for a [[Canadian Screen Awards|Canadian Screen Award]] and an [[ACTRA Award]] in 2017 for his work in ''[[Blood and Water (TV series)|Blood and Water]]''.<ref name=\":1\" /> He, along with his ''Kim's Convenience'' castmates, won the ACTRA Award for Outstanding Ensemble in 2017. Liu and his castmates were subsequently nominated for the same award in 2018 and 2019. ''Kim's Convenience'' also went on to win the award for Best Comedy Series at the [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Comedy Series|2018 Canadian Screen Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Vlessing|first1=Etan|title=Canadian Screen Awards: 'Alias Grace,' 'Maudie,' 'Anne With an E' Dominate|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/canadian-screen-awards-netflixs-alias-grace-anne-an-e-dominate-1093656|website=The Hollywood Reporter|accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n\nLiu was named one of [[Hello! (magazine)|''Hello!'']]'s 50 Most Beautiful Canadians and 25 Hottest Bachelors in 2017 and 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Canada's Most Beautiful 2017: See who made the list!|url=https://ca.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/gallery/02017050835609/canada-s-most-beautiful-2017-full-list/25/|website=Hello! Canada|accessdate=March 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Canada's 25 Hottest Bachelors of 2017|url=https://ca.hellomagazine.com/2017-canada-s-25-hottest-bachelors/gallery/02017102539519/canadas-hottest-bachelors-2017/18|website=Hello! Canada|accessdate=March 20, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Canada's Most Beautiful 2018: See who made the list! |date=June 25, 2018 |url=https://ca.hellomagazine.com/celebrities/gallery/02018062045801/canadas-most-beautiful-2018-full-list/10/ |website=Hello! Canada |accessdate=February 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Director\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Pacific Rim (film)|Pacific Rim]]''\n| Extra\n| [[Guillermo del Toro]]\n| First film debut\n|-\n| 2021\n| ''[[Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings]]''\n| [[Shang-Chi]]\n| [[Destin Daniel Cretton]]\n| Filming\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year \n! Title \n! Role \n! Notes\n|-\n| 2012 \n| ''[[Nikita (TV series)|Nikita]]'' \n| [[Hong Kong Police]] Constable (Desk Cop)\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2013 \n| ''[[Warehouse 13]]'' \n| Bartender\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Played (TV series)|Played]]'' \n| Gunman\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Mayday (Canadian TV series)|Mayday]]'' \n| Narita Air Traffic Controller\n|\n|-\n| 2014 \n| ''[[Beauty & the Beast (2012 TV series)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' \n| EMT\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2015 \n| ''[[Blood and Water (TV series)|Blood and Water]]'' \n| Paul Xie \n| Main role\n|-\n| ''[[Heroes Reborn (miniseries)|Heroes Reborn]]'' \n| Stunt Performer \n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| ''[[Make It Pop]]!'' \n| Randy\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2016 \n| ''[[Taken (2017 TV series)|Taken]]''\n| Faaron\n| Recurring role (season 1); 10 episodes\n|-\n| 2016\u2013present\n| ''[[Kim's Convenience (TV series)|Kim's Convenience]]''\n| Jung Kim\n| Main role\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2017\n| ''[[Orphan Black]]''\n| Mr. Mitchell \n| \n|-\n| [[Slasher (TV series)|''Slasher: Guilty Party'']]\n| Luke \n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| [[Bad Blood (TV series)|''Bad Blood'']] \n| Guy \n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2018 \n| [[The Expanse (TV series)|''The Expanse'']]\n| Lt. Paolo Mayer \n| 1 episodes\n|-\n| [[Wong Fu Productions#Yappie|''Yappie'']]\n| Tom\n| Main role\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[Fresh Off the Boat]]''\n| Willie\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''[[Awkwafina Is Nora from Queens]]''\n| Garbage Boy\n| Episode: \"Grandma & Chill\"\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Nominated work\n! Award\n! Category\n! Result\n! Ref\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2017\n| rowspan=\"2\"|''[[Blood and Water (TV series)|Blood and Water]]''\n| [[ACTRA Awards]]\n| Outstanding Performance \u2013 Male\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |last1=Davis |first1=Erin |title=Move Over, Oscars: Canada\u2019s Finest Talent Inspired at the ACTRA Awards |url=https://torontoguardian.com/2017/02/canadas-finest-talent-inspired-at-the-actra-awards/ |website=Toronto Guardian |accessdate=20 September 2019 |language=en-CA |date=28 February 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Canadian Screen Award]]\n| Best Supporting Actor in a Dramatic Program or Series\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |title=Kim's Convenience star Simu Liu thanks his immigrant parents for his Canadian life |url=https://www.cbc.ca/2017/whatsyourstory/kim-s-convenience-star-simu-liu-thanks-his-immigrant-parents-for-his-canadian-life-1.4007124 |website=CBC |accessdate=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Kim's Convenience]]''\n| ACTRA Awards 2017\n| Outstanding Performance \u2013 Ensemble\n| {{won}}\n| <ref name=CBC>{{cite web |title=Simu Liu, new Marvel superhero & Kim's Convenience star, writing a memoir |url=https://www.cbc.ca/books/simu-liu-new-marvel-superhero-kim-s-convenience-star-writing-a-memoir-1.5245067 |website=CBC |accessdate=20 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Kim's Convenience''\n| ACTRA Awards 2018\n| Outstanding Performance \u2013 Ensemble\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web |title=The 16th Annual ACTRA Awards in Toronto Nominees |url=https://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/the-16th-annual-actra-awards-in-toronto-nominees-669015333.html |website=www.newswire.ca |accessdate=20 September 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|4855517}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* {{Instagram}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liu, Simu}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Chinese emigrants to Canada]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Harbin]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Canadian television writers]]\n[[Category:Canadian male television actors]]\n[[Category:Canadian male actors of Chinese descent]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian male actors]]\n", "name_user": "71.190.152.167", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Fccgcg)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Simu_Liu"}
{"title_page": "Tommaso A. Dragani", "text_new": "<noinclude><!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Tommaso A. Dragani|timestamp=20200414184933|year=2020|month=April|day=14|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Tommaso A. Dragani|date=14 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name           = Tommaso A. Dragani\n| image          = Tommaso Dragani 2016.jpg\n| birth_date     =\n| birth_place    = [[Ortona]], Italy\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| alma_mater     = [[University of Bologna]] <small>(Graduation with honors)</small><br />[[University of Milano]] <small>(Master in Medical Statistics and Statistical Methods in Epidemiology)</small>\n| occupation     = [[Cancer research]]er, [[Genetic epidemiologist]], [[toxicologist]]\n| spouse         =\n| children       =\n}}\n'''Tommaso A. Dragani''' is an Italian genetic [[epidemiologist]] who carried out a series of studies on genetic predisposition to [[cancer]].<ref>Cancer Res. 1993;53:209-11</ref><ref>Nat Genet. 1993;3:132-6</ref><ref>Nat Genet.1996;12:455-7</ref><ref>Oncogene. 2000;19:5324-8</ref><ref>PLoS Genet. 2014;10:e1004307</ref><ref>Cancer Lett. 2016;375:221-230</ref>\n\nResults of his studies allowed the chromosomal mapping of [[quantitative trait]] [[loci]] (QTLs) modulating the genetic predisposition to liver, lung and skin [[tumorigenesis]], in animal models<ref>Cancer Res. 1993;53:209-11</ref><ref>Nat Genet. 1993;3:132-6</ref><ref>Nat Genet.1996;12:455-7</ref><ref>Oncogene. 2000;19:5324-8</ref><ref>PLoS Genet. 2014;10:e1004307</ref><ref>Cancer Lett. 2016;375:221-230</ref>.\n\nHis population-based studies resulted in the identification of [[genetic polymorphisms]] associated with the [[risk]] and prognosis of [[lung cancer]]. He contributed to discovering the mechanism underlying the association between [[polymorphisms]] in [[nicotinic acetylcholine receptor]] subunit genes on [[chromosome 15]] and the risks of [[lung cancer]] and [[nicotine dependence]].<ref>J Natl Cancer Inst. 2010;102:1366-70</ref><ref>Carcinogenesis. 2013;34:1281-5</ref>\n\nHe contributed with a genome-wide study to the pharmacogenomics of [[pain relief]] in response to [[opioid therapy]] for [[cancer]] pain.<ref>Clin Cancer Res. 2011;17:4581-7</ref>\n\nOverall, he focused mainly on understanding the [[genetic control]] of complex [[phenotypes]], like cancer.\n\n== Biography ==\nTommaso A. Dragani was born in Ortona, Italy, studied Pharmacy at the University of Bologna and received the MPharm degree with honors in 1977, after which he joined the National Cancer Institute in Milan as a researcher.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nFrom June 1984 to June 1985, he was visiting scientist at the laboratory of [[Bernard Weinstein]], [[Columbia University]], and from September 1996 to February 1997 he was visiting scientist at the National Cancer Center of Japan, working with Dr. Minako Nagao.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 1998 Tommaso A. Dragani was appointed Director of the Genetic Epidemiology and Pharmacogenomics Research Unit at the National Cancer Institute in Milan. In 2007 he achieved a Masters in Medical Statistics and Statistical Methods in Epidemiology by the [[University of Milan]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Achievements and scientific merits ==\nTommaso A. Dragani identified genetic loci that influence the hereditary predisposition to liver cancer (Cancer Res. 1993;53:209-11<ref>Cancer Res. 1993;53:209-11</ref>), lung cancer (Nat Genet. 1993;3:132-6;<ref>Nat Genet. 1993;3:132-6</ref> Nat Genet.1996;12:455-7<ref>Nat Genet.1996;12:455-7</ref>), and skin cancer (Oncogene. 2000;19:5324-8<ref>Oncogene. 2000;19:5324-8</ref>). He characterized genes involved in the hereditary predisposition to lung cancer in mice and identified genetic loci that modulate the expression of these genes (PLoS Genet. 2014;10:e1004307;<ref>PLoS Genet. 2014;10:e1004307</ref> Cancer Lett. 2016;375:221-230<ref>Cancer Lett. 2016;375:221-230</ref>).\n\nHe conducted a [[genome-wide association study]] (GWAS) between genetic polymorphisms and lung cancer (J Clin Oncol. 2006;24:1672-8<ref>J Clin Oncol. 2006;24:1672-8</ref>). He demonstrated that polymorphisms in the CHRNA5 gene promoter modulated the transcription of this gene, and thereby showed that genetic variants affected the risks of lung cancer and nicotine dependence (J Natl Cancer Inst. 2010;102:1366-70;<ref>J Natl Cancer Inst. 2010;102:1366-70</ref> Carcinogenesis. 2013;34:1281-5<ref>Carcinogenesis. 2013;34:1281-5</ref>).\n\nHe did a GWAS  on pain relief in cancer patients treated with opioids, demonstrating that different genetic loci control the individual response to this therapy (Clin Cancer Res. 2011;17:4581-7<ref>Clin Cancer Res. 2011;17:4581-7</ref>).\n\nHe discovered the tumor-promoting activity of 1,4-bis[2-(3,5-dichloropyridiloxy)]benzene (TCPOBOP), a constitutive androstan receptor agonist ( [12] and he characterized carcinogenicity of [[2,3,7,8-tetrachlorodibenzo-p-dioxin]] (TCDD).<ref>Della Porta G, Dragani TA, Sozzi G. Carcinogenic effects of infantile and long-term 2,3,7,8-tetrachlorodibenzo-p-dioxin treatment in the mouse. Tumori. 1987;73(2):99\u2013107.</ref>\n\n== Member of International Working Groups ==\nTommaso A. Dragani participated as a member of International Working Groups on cancer research.\nIn particular, he was Member of six IARC Monographs Working Groups on the Evaluation of Carcinogenic Risks to Humans.<ref>World Health Organization International Agency for Research on Cancer, Iarc Monographs on the Evaluation of Carcinogenic Risks to Humans. Volume 57. Occupational exposures of hairdressers and barbers and personal use of hair colourants; some hair dyes, cosmetic colourants, industrial dyestuffs and aromatic amines, LYON</ref><ref>World Health Organization International Agency for Research on Cancer, Iarc Monographs on the Evaluation of Carcinogenic Risks to Humans. Volume 59. Hepatitis viruses, LYON</ref><ref>World Health Organization International Agency for Research on Cancer, Iarc Monographs on the Evaluation of Carcinogenic Risks to Humans. Volume 60. Some industrial chemicals, LYON</ref><ref>World Health Organization International Agency for Research on Cancer, Iarc Monographs on the Evaluation of Carcinogenic Risks to Humans. Volume 71. Re-evaluation of some organic chemicals, hydrazine and hydrogen peroxide, LYON</ref><ref>World Health Organization International Agency for Research on Cancer, Iarc Monographs on the Evaluation of Carcinogenic Risks to Humans. Volume 76. Some antiviral and antineoplastic drugs, and other pharmaceutical agents, LYON</ref><ref>World Health Organization International Agency for Research on Cancer, Iarc Monographs on the Evaluation of Carcinogenic Risks to Humans. Volume 77. Some industrial chemicals, LYON</ref>\n\nHe, also, served as a Member of the International Lung Cancer Consortium (ILCCO),<ref>International Lung Cancer Consortium (ILCCO)</ref> an organization that aims to share data from ongoing lung cancer case-control and cohort studies, in particular regarding genetic association studies. The overall objectives are to reduce duplication of research effort, replicate novel findings, and afford substantial cost savings through large collaborative efforts.\n\n== Publications ==\nTommaso A. Dragani published more than 180 peer-reviewed articles.\nHis [[H-index]] is 40 ([[Research Gate]]) and he has a ResearchGate score of 44.77.\n\nHe is author of Human Polygenic Diseases: Animal Models.\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dragani, Tommaso}}\n\n[[Category:Italian oncologists]]\n", "text_old": "<noinclude><!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion