{"title_page": "South African College Schools", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox School\n|name              = South African College Schools (SACS)\n|image             = \n|imagesize         =\n|caption           = Badge of the South African College Schools, based on the original South African College badge, which was replaced by the badges of the South African College Schools and the University of Cape Town.\n|location          =Newlands\n|streetaddress     = Newlands Avenue (High School)<br />Dean Street (Junior School)\n|region            =[[Southern Suburbs]]\n|city              = [[Cape Town]]\n|province          = [[Western Cape]]\n|postalcode        = 7700\n|country           = [[South Africa]]\n|country1          =\n|coordinates       =\n|schoolnumber      =\n|schoolboard       =\n|district          =\n|authority         =\n|religion          =\n|denomination      =\n|oversight         =\n|affiliation       =\n|superintendent    =\n|trustee           =\n|founder           =\n|specialist        =\n|president         =\n|head_label        = Headmaster\n|head              = Brendan Grant (High School) <br /> Fran\u00e7ois Nel (Junior School)\n|principal         =\n|viceprincipal     =\n|staff             =\n|ranking           =\n|faculty           =\n|teaching_staff    =\n|roll              =\n|national_ranking  =\n|classes           =\n|classes offered   =\n|avg_class_size    =\n|ratio             =\n|houses            = High School: <br/> Baxter <br /> Rosedale <br /> Russel <br /> Shaw <br /> <hr> Junior School: <Br /> Hofmeyr <br /> Kipps <br /> Lewis <br /> van Holdt\n|schooltype        =\n|fundingtype       =\n|system            =\n|fees              =\n|tuition           = Grade 8 R40,700 Grade 9\u201312 R38,900 (High School) <br /> R 35 500 (Junior School)\n|revenue           =\n|endowment         =\n|budget            =\n|products          =\n|grades            = R-12\n|age range         =\n|medium            =\n|language          = English (primary)\n|classrooms        =\n|campus            =\n|campus size       =\n|campus type       =\n|hours_in_day      =\n|athletics         =\n|conference        =\n|song              = [[#The S.A.C.|The S.A.C.]]\n|fightsong         =\n|motto             = ''[[Spectemur agendo]]''\n|motto_translation = Let us be judged by our deeds\n|accreditation     = [[Matriculation (South Africa)|Senior Certificate]], [[GCE Advanced Level|GCE A-levels]]\n|rival             =\n|mascot            =\n|mascot image      =\n|sports            =\n|patron            =\n|team_name         =\n|nickname          =\n|school_colours    = White, sky blue, navy blue\n|school_colors     =\n|yearbook          =\n|publication       =\n|opened            =\n|established       =\n|founded           = 1 October 1829\n|status            =\n|closed            =\n|students          =\n|pupils            =\n|alumni            =\n|nobel_laureates   =\n|enrollment        = 780 (High School) <br /> 650 (Junior School)\n|footnotes         =\n|picture           =\n|homepage          ={{url|sacollege.org.za}}\n}}\n\nThe '''South African College Schools''' is a [[State school|Semi-private]] [[English language|English medium]] primary and secondary education institution in the suburb of  [[Newlands, Cape Town|Newlands]] in [[Cape Town]] in the [[Western Cape]] province of [[South Africa]]. Founded in 1829,<ref>{{cite book|author=Everhardus Cornelis Gode Molsbergen|title=A History of South Africa for Use in Schools|year=2009|publisher=BiblioBazaar, LLC, 2009|page=186}}</ref> it is the oldest school in South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sacshigh.org.za/|title=SACS High School}}</ref> SACS is one of four schools expressly named by [[Cecil Rhodes|Cecil John Rhodes]] to offer an annual [[Rhodes Scholarship]] to one of its graduating students.<ref name=\"CJR1902\">{{cite web | last = Rhodes  | first = Cecil John | title = Will and Condicils of the Rt Hon. Cecil John Rhodes. | url = http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/files/governancedocs/WillandCodicils.pdf | publisher= Rhodes Trust, University Press Oxford | format=PDF | page=10 }}</ref> The schools are a combination of the South African College Junior School and the South African College High School.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Original SA College Schools Building.jpg|thumb|left|Rosedale House]]\n[[File:Detail of SACS sign above door.jpg|thumb|left|SACS Badge]]\nThe concept of the '''[[South African College]]''' was first formed in 1791 when the Dutch Commissioner-General, [[Jacob Abraham de Mist|Jacob Abraham Uitenhage de Mist]], asked for funding to be set aside to improve schooling in the Cape. After the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] took over control of the [[Cape Colony]] the second colonial governor, [[Lord Charles Somerset|Lord Charles Henry Somerset]] {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]}}, gave permission for the funds reserved by de Mist to be used to establish the South African College in 1814.\n\nThe founding committee met in the [[Groote Kerk, Cape Town|Groote Kerk]] to discuss funding and accommodation for the school and on 1 October 1829, the inauguration of the South African College was held and classes began. The original location of the school was in the ''Weeshuis'' on Long Street and moved to what is now known as the ''Egyptian Building'' in the Gardens district of Cape Town in 1841.\n\nIt was decided in 1874 that the younger students should be separated from their older counterparts. The South African College was separated into the ''College'' which became the [[University of Cape Town]] and the ''College School''.<ref>{{cite book|title=\tStandard encyclopaedia of Southern Africa, Volume 10|publisher=NASOU|year=1976|page=96}}</ref>\n\nThe College School moved to its own building on Orange Street, separate from the College, in 1896. For the next few decades, the school grew and the building became too small for the number of students attending.\n\nIn 1959 the school moved to its current home in the Montebello Estate in Newlands,<ref>{{cite book|title=Cape Town, city of good hope|last=Honikman|first=A. H.|publisher=H. B. Timmins|year=1966|page=63}}</ref> former home of the mining magnate [[Max Michaelis|Sir Max Michaelis]], after a decade-long negotiation with the Cape Administration.\n\nIn 2012, the school grounds were used to film Spud 2: The Madness Continues. \n\n{{Coord|33|58|13.45|S|18|27|36.38|E|display=title}}\n\n==School buildings==\nThe current school buildings are situated along Dean Street and Newlands Avenue in Cape Town.\n\nThe Junior School is located along Dean Street and is equipped with numerous fields for sporting activities, of which some are shared with the High School. The Junior School has a full length swimming pool with a smaller children's pool for the younger students. A number of [[tennis]] courts are also available to the students. The Junior School has a new Media Centre which hosts computer facilities, a new library and classrooms. The music department also has its own [[auditorium]] for cultural events and is also used for events with smaller audiences. The Junior School's [[boarding house]] is named after ''J E De Villiers''.\n\nThe High School is closest to Newlands Avenue which also hosts a number of sport fields for the various sports which the school offers throughout the year. The swimming pool is mainly used for [[Water Polo]] and is also heated to facilitate training and usage in winter. The High School also recently had a new Media Centre constructed with air-conditioned computer labs and library. The school hall is named after one of its most famous students, [[Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr (1894-1948)|Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr]]. The boarding houses for the High School are the ''Michaelis House'' (for the junior students) and ''Rosedale House'' (for the senior students).\n\n== High School Sport ==\nSACS offers a wide variety of summer and winter sports for boys to partake in during the year. Boys are made to partake in at least one main summer and winter sport and may also partake in other secondar sports, provided they are involved in a main sport first.\n\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*'''Main summer sports'''\n** [[Cricket]]\n** Swimming\n** [[Water polo|Waterpolo]]\n** [[Rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n** [[Tennis]]\n** [[Basketball]]\n** [[Sport of athletics|Athletics]]\n*'''Secondary summer sports'''\n** [[Sailing (sport)|Sailing]]\n**[[Road cycling]]\n*'''Main winter sports'''\n** [[Rugby union]]\n** [[Hockey]]\n** [[Cross country running|Cross-country]]\n** [[Squash (sport)|Squash]]\n** [[Mountain biking]]\n*'''Secondary winter sports'''\n** [[Bodyboarding]]\n** [[Golf]]\n** [[Surfing]]\n** [[Shooting sport|Shooting]] (Currently Inactive)\n{{div col end}}\n\n== High school clubs and societies  ==\nCulture plays a large role in the SACS High School community. Many clubs, societies and bands are situated within the high school and are largely run and coordinated by the boys, with each club or society being supervised by a teacher. As of 2016, there were active clubs, societies and bands operating within SACS. These are the: \n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* History Society\n* Marimba Band\n* Piano Legends\n* SACS Choir\n* SACS Big Band\n* SACS Junior Jazz Band\n* SACS Concert and Marching bands\n* SACS Clarinet Ensemble\n* SACS Flute Ensemble\n* SACS Brass Ensemble\n* SACS Saxophone Ensemble\n* SACS Piano Ensemble\n* Muslim Students' Association\n* Christian Union\n* Science Club\n* RCL\n* Interact Club\n* Photography Society\n* First Aid Society\n* Multimedia Society\n* Film Society\n* Chess Club\n* Waterpolo Table Officials\n* Afrikaans Society \n* Mountain Club\n* French Club\n* Debating Society\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Uniform==\nThe traditional school colour of navy blue was determined in the 1880s when SACS pupils purchased the only pattern available of alternating white, light- and dark-blue horizontal stripes from ''Porter Hodgson's Outfitters'' in Cape Town. Prior to this, the pupils wore what they could afford while still being presentable.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.capeargus.co.za/index.php?fSectionId=342&fArticleId=2516444|title=School uniforms \u2013 what purpose do they serve?|date=11 May 2005|first=Fouzia|last=van der Fort}}</ref>\n\nToday the High School uniform consists of a summer and winter uniform. During summer, boys wear khaki shorts with long khaki socks and brown shoes. In winter the basic uniform consists of long charcoal pants, black socks and black shoes. Both the summer and winter uniforms are accompanied by the SACS navy-blue blazer, white school shirt and school tie. Both these uniforms can be worn at any time during the school year, except for certain formal school functions where a certain uniform is required.\n\nThe Junior School uniform consists of a white shirt, charcoal shorts, a SACS Junior belt, charcoal socks with thin light and dark blue stripes at the top, black shoes and the Junior School tie, which is similar to the High School tie, apart from one minor difference. The Junior School uniform includes the same blazer as the High School, with the exception of the Junior School not modifying blazers for Blues (colours) awards, as is practised by the high school.\n\n==Rhodes Scholarship==\nWhen [[Cecil John Rhodes]] died in 1902, he specifically named the South African College in his will as one of four schools in the [[Cape Colony]] where the [[Rhodes Scholarship]] would be awarded on an annual basis for a former student to study at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rhodestrust.org.za/about.html|title=Rhodes Scholarships in Southern Africa|date=3 January 2009|first=Tim|last=Nuttall}}</ref>\n\n==Old Boys' Union==\n===Old Boys===\n[[File:The leader and his deputy, jan smuts on the right and jan hofmeyr on the left.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr and former Prime Minister of South Africa, [[Jan Smuts]]]]\n*Dr. [[Abdullah Abdurahman]] \u2013 Medical Doctor, Cape Muslim leader & founder of the anti-apartheid movement, African People's Organisation and human rights campaigner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sahistory.org.za/people/dr-abdullah-abdurahman|title=Dr. Abdullah Abdurahman|last=sahoboss|date=17 February 2011|website=South African History Online}}</ref>\n*Captain [[Andrew Beauchamp-Proctor]] [[Victoria Cross|VC]], [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]], [[Military Cross|MC and bar]], [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|DFC]]\n*[[Kyle Brown (rugby union)|Kyle Brown]] \u2013 [[South Africa national rugby sevens team|South Africa Sevens]] captain 2008\u2013present and [[Olympic Games]] medalist Rio 2016.\n*[[Abraham Fischer]] \u2013 Sole Prime Minister of the Orange River Colony in South Africa<ref>Clingman, Stephen (1998). Bram Fischer: Afrikaner revolutionary. David Philip Publishers. p. 8. {{ISBN|0-86486-677-1}}.</ref>\n*[[Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr (1894-1948)|Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr]] \u2014 former Deputy Prime Minister of South Africa, Minister of Finance and Education, Administrator of the [[Transvaal Province|Transvaal]] and [[Rhodes Scholar]]\n*[[Leonard Hoffmann, Baron Hoffmann]] {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]}} \u2014 former senior British justice\n*[[Peter Kirsten]] \u2014 former [[South African cricket team|South African]] cricketer\n*[[Dylan Lewis]]- South African sculptor and artist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dylanlewis.co.za/about/bio.php|title=Dylan Lewis \u2013 Biography|website=dylanlewis.co.za}}</ref>\n*[[Gino Lupini]] \u2013 [[Italy national rugby sevens team|Italy Seven]] Rugby 2016\u2013present.\n*[[Nicolaas Petrus van Wyk Louw]] \u2014 [[Afrikaans]]-language poet, playwright, and scholar\n*[[W. E. G. Louw|William Ewart Gladstone van Wyk Louw]] \u2014 Afrikaans-language poet\n*[[Percy Montgomery|Percival Colin \"Percy\" Montgomery]] \u2014 former [[South Africa national rugby union team|South African]] [[rugby union]] footballer, [[2007 Rugby World Cup]] winner & the first Springbok to earn 100 caps.\n*Dr. [[Cecil Moss]] \u2014 former South African rugby union player and South African Rugby Union coach<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugby15.co.za/rip-dr-cecil-moss-1925-2017/|title=RIP Dr Cecil Moss, 1925\u20132017 \u2013 15.co.za \u2013 - Rugby News, Live Scores, Results, Fixtures|website=rugby15.co.za}}</ref>\n*Sir [[Allan Mossop]], Chief Judge of the [[British Supreme Court for China]]\n*[[Sebastien Rousseau]] \u2013 Three time Olympian Swimmer for South Africa, Commonwealth Games Medalist, South African Record Holder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://floridagators.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3493|title=Sebastien Rousseau \u2013 Men's Swimming & Diving|website=Florida Gators}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sascoc.co.za/2009/04/14/rousseau-leads-the-charge/|title=Record for Rousseau|date=14 April 2009|website=sascoc.co.za}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecgf.com/results/athletes/65499|title=Sebastien Rousseau|website=Commonwealth Games Federation}}</ref>\n*[[Albie Sachs]] \u2014 former justice of the [[Constitutional Court of South Africa]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Sachs|first=Albie|title=Advancing human rights in South Africa|page=iii|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1992}}</ref>\n*[[Ryan Sandes]] \u2013 ultramarathon trail runner who has won all four of the [[4 Deserts]] races, amongst other achievements.\n*[[Stephen Simpson]] \u2014 race car driver and former [[A1 Team South Africa|A1 Grand Prix Team South Africa]] driver\n*[[Ross Skeate]] \u2014 rugby union footballer for [[RC Toulonnais|RC Toulon]] and formerly for [[Stormers]] and [[Western Province (rugby team)|Western Province]] rugby union teams[[File:Percy Montgomery.JPG|right|thumb|Percy Montgomery]]\n*[[Simon Walker (business)|Simon Walker]] \u2014 British business executive, government advisor and Director General of the UK's [[Institute of Directors]]\n*[[Eric Lloyd Williams]] \u2014 journalist and [[World War II]] correspondent\n*[[Solly Zuckerman, Baron Zuckerman]] {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Order of Merit|OM]], [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath|KCB]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]]}} \u2014 British zoologist, public servant and key World War II [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] strategic advisor\n* [[Benjamin Duff]] Springbok rugby player\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Saasveld Forestry College]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{cite book|url=|title=SACS 175 \u2013 A Celebration|last=Veitch|first=Neil|publisher=SACS 175 Book Committee|year=2002|isbn=|location=Cape Town|pages=260|doi=|id=|authorlink=|author2=}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sacollege.org.za/ South African College Schools Website]\n*[http://www.sacsjunior.org.za/ SACS Junior School]\n*[http://www.sacsrugby.com/ SACS Rugby Site]\n{{CapeTownSchools}}\n\n[[Category:Boarding schools in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Schools in Cape Town]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1829]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in South Africa]]\n[[Category:1829 establishments in the Cape Colony]]\n[[Category:Newlands, Cape Town]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox School\n|name              = South African College Schools (SACS)\n|image             = \n|imagesize         =\n|caption           = Badge of the South African College Schools, based on the original South African College badge, which was replaced by the badges of the South African College Schools and the University of Cape Town.\n|location          =Newlands\n|streetaddress     = Newlands Avenue (High School)<br />Dean Street (Junior School)\n|region            =[[Southern Suburbs]]\n|city              = [[Cape Town]]\n|province          = [[Western Cape]]\n|postalcode        = 7700\n|country           = [[South Africa]]\n|country1          =\n|coordinates       =\n|schoolnumber      =\n|schoolboard       =\n|district          =\n|authority         =\n|religion          =\n|denomination      =\n|oversight         =\n|affiliation       =\n|superintendent    =\n|trustee           =\n|founder           =\n|specialist        =\n|president         =\n|head_label        = Headmaster\n|head              = Brendan Grant (High School) <br /> Fran\u00e7ois Nel (Junior School)\n|principal         =\n|viceprincipal     =\n|staff             =\n|ranking           =\n|faculty           =\n|teaching_staff    =\n|roll              =\n|national_ranking  =\n|classes           =\n|classes offered   =\n|avg_class_size    =\n|ratio             =\n|houses            = High School: <br/> Baxter <br /> Rosedale <br /> Russel <br /> Shaw <br /> <hr> Junior School: <Br /> Hofmeyr <br /> Kipps <br /> Lewis <br /> van Holdt\n|schooltype        =\n|fundingtype       =\n|system            =\n|fees              =\n|tuition           = Grade 8 R40,700 Grade 9\u201312 R38,900 (High School) <br /> R 35 500 (Junior School)\n|revenue           =\n|endowment         =\n|budget            =\n|products          =\n|grades            = R-12\n|age range         =\n|medium            =\n|language          = English (primary)\n|classrooms        =\n|campus            =\n|campus size       =\n|campus type       =\n|hours_in_day      =\n|athletics         =\n|conference        =\n|song              = [[#The S.A.C.|The S.A.C.]]\n|fightsong         =\n|motto             = ''[[Spectemur agendo]]''\n|motto_translation = Let us be judged by our deeds\n|accreditation     = [[Matriculation (South Africa)|Senior Certificate]], [[GCE Advanced Level|GCE A-levels]]\n|rival             =\n|mascot            =\n|mascot image      =\n|sports            =\n|patron            =\n|team_name         =\n|nickname          =\n|school_colours    = White, sky blue, navy blue\n|school_colors     =\n|yearbook          =\n|publication       =\n|opened            =\n|established       =\n|founded           = 1 October 1829\n|status            =\n|closed            =\n|students          =\n|pupils            =\n|alumni            =\n|nobel_laureates   =\n|enrollment        = 780 (High School) <br /> 650 (Junior School)\n|footnotes         =\n|picture           =\n|homepage          ={{url|sacollege.org.za}}\n}}\n\nThe '''South African College Schools''' is a [[State school|Semi-private]] [[English language|English medium]] primary and secondary education institution in the suburb of  [[Newlands, Cape Town|Newlands]] in [[Cape Town]] in the [[Western Cape]] province of [[South Africa]]. Founded in 1829,<ref>{{cite book|author=Everhardus Cornelis Gode Molsbergen|title=A History of South Africa for Use in Schools|year=2009|publisher=BiblioBazaar, LLC, 2009|page=186}}</ref> it is the oldest school in South Africa.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sacshigh.org.za/|title=SACS High School}}</ref> SACS is one of four schools expressly named by [[Cecil Rhodes|Cecil John Rhodes]] to offer an annual [[Rhodes Scholarship]] to one of its graduating students.<ref name=\"CJR1902\">{{cite web | last = Rhodes  | first = Cecil John | title = Will and Condicils of the Rt Hon. Cecil John Rhodes. | url = http://www.rhodeshouse.ox.ac.uk/files/governancedocs/WillandCodicils.pdf | publisher= Rhodes Trust, University Press Oxford | format=PDF | page=10 }}</ref> The schools are a combination of the South African College Junior School and the South African College High School.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Original SA College Schools Building.jpg|thumb|left|Rosedale House]]\n[[File:Detail of SACS sign above door.jpg|thumb|left|SACS Badge]]\nThe concept of the '''[[South African College]]''' was first formed in 1791 when the Dutch Commissioner-General, [[Jacob Abraham de Mist|Jacob Abraham Uitenhage de Mist]], asked for funding to be set aside to improve schooling in the Cape. After the [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] took over control of the [[Cape Colony]] the second colonial governor, [[Lord Charles Somerset|Lord Charles Henry Somerset]] {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]}}, gave permission for the funds reserved by de Mist to be used to establish the South African College in 1814.\n\nThe founding committee met in the [[Groote Kerk, Cape Town|Groote Kerk]] to discuss funding and accommodation for the school and on 1 October 1829, the inauguration of the South African College was held and classes began. The original location of the school was in the ''Weeshuis'' on Long Street and moved to what is now known as the ''Egyptian Building'' in the Gardens district of Cape Town in 1841.\n\nIt was decided in 1874 that the younger students should be separated from their older counterparts. The South African College was separated into the ''College'' which became the [[University of Cape Town]] and the ''College School''.<ref>{{cite book|title=\tStandard encyclopaedia of Southern Africa, Volume 10|publisher=NASOU|year=1976|page=96}}</ref>\n\nThe College School moved to its own building on Orange Street, separate from the College, in 1896. For the next few decades, the school grew and the building became too small for the number of students attending.\n\nIn 1959 the school moved to its current home in the Montebello Estate in Newlands,<ref>{{cite book|title=Cape Town, city of good hope|last=Honikman|first=A. H.|publisher=H. B. Timmins|year=1966|page=63}}</ref> former home of the mining magnate [[Max Michaelis|Sir Max Michaelis]], after a decade-long negotiation with the Cape Administration.\n\nIn 2012, the school grounds were used to film Spud 2: The Madness Continues. \n\n{{Coord|33|58|13.45|S|18|27|36.38|E|display=title}}\n\n==School buildings==\nThe current school buildings are situated along Dean Street and Newlands Avenue in Cape Town.\n\nThe Junior School is located along Dean Street and is equipped with numerous fields for sporting activities, of which some are shared with the High School. The Junior School has a full length swimming pool with a smaller children's pool for the younger students. A number of [[tennis]] courts are also available to the students. The Junior School has a new Media Centre which hosts computer facilities, a new library and classrooms. The music department also has its own [[auditorium]] for cultural events and is also used for events with smaller audiences. The Junior School's [[boarding house]] is named after ''J E De Villiers''.\n\nThe High School is closest to Newlands Avenue which also hosts a number of sport fields for the various sports which the school offers throughout the year. The swimming pool is mainly used for [[Water Polo]] and is also heated to facilitate training and usage in winter. The High School also recently had a new Media Centre constructed with air-conditioned computer labs and library. The school hall is named after one of its most famous students, [[Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr (1894-1948)|Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr]]. The boarding houses for the High School are the ''Michaelis House'' (for the junior students) and ''Rosedale House'' (for the senior students).\n\n== High School Sport ==\nSACS offers a wide variety of summer and winter sports for boys to partake in during the year. Boys are made to partake in at least one main summer and winter sport and may also partake in other secondar sports, provided they are involved in a main sport first.\n\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*'''Main summer sports'''\n** [[Cricket]]\n** Swimming\n** [[Water polo|Waterpolo]]\n** [[Rowing (sport)|Rowing]]\n** [[Tennis]]\n** [[Basketball]]\n** [[Sport of athletics|Athletics]]\n*'''Secondary summer sports'''\n** [[Sailing (sport)|Sailing]]\n**[[Road cycling]]\n*'''Main winter sports'''\n** [[Rugby union]]\n** [[Rugby union|Hocke]] [[Field hockey|y]]\n** [[Cross country running|Cross-country]]\n** [[Squash (sport)|Squash]]\n** [[Mountain biking]]\n*'''Secondary winter sports'''\n** [[Bodyboarding]]\n** [[Golf]]\n** [[Surfing]]\n** [[Shooting sport|Shooting]] (Currently Inactive)\n{{div col end}}\n\n== High school clubs and societies  ==\nCulture plays a large role in the SACS High School community. Many clubs, societies and bands are situated within the high school and are largely run and coordinated by the boys, with each club or society being supervised by a teacher. As of 2016, there were active clubs, societies and bands operating within SACS. These are the: \n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* History Society\n* Marimba Band\n* Debating Society\n* SACS Choir\n* SACS Big Band\n* SACS Junior Jazz Band\n* SACS Concert and Marching bands\n* SACS Clarinet Ensemble \n* SACS Flute Ensemble \n* SACS Brass Ensemble \n* SACS Saxophone Ensemble \n* Muslim Students' Association\n* Christian Union\n* Science Club\n* RCL\n* Interact Club\n* Photography Society\n* First Aid Society\n* Multimedia Society\n* Film Society\n* Chess Club\n* Waterpolo Table Officials\n* Afrikaans Society \n* Mountain Club\n* French Club\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Uniform==\nThe traditional school colour of navy blue was determined in the 1880s when SACS pupils purchased the only pattern available of alternating white, light- and dark-blue horizontal stripes from ''Porter Hodgson's Outfitters'' in Cape Town. Prior to this, the pupils wore what they could afford while still being presentable.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.capeargus.co.za/index.php?fSectionId=342&fArticleId=2516444|title=School uniforms \u2013 what purpose do they serve?|date=11 May 2005|first=Fouzia|last=van der Fort}}</ref>\n\nToday the High School uniform consists of a summer and winter uniform. During summer, boys wear khaki shorts with long khaki socks and brown shoes. In winter the basic uniform consists of long charcoal pants, black socks and black shoes. Both the summer and winter uniforms are accompanied by the SACS navy-blue blazer, white school shirt and school tie. Both these uniforms can be worn at any time during the school year, except for certain formal school functions where a certain uniform is required.\n\nThe Junior School uniform consists of a white shirt, charcoal shorts, a SACS Junior belt, charcoal socks with thin light and dark blue stripes at the top, black shoes and the Junior School tie, which is similar to the High School tie, apart from one minor difference. The Junior School uniform includes the same blazer as the High School, with the exception of the Junior School not modifying blazers for Blues (colours) awards, as is practised by the high school.\n\n==Rhodes Scholarship==\nWhen [[Cecil John Rhodes]] died in 1902, he specifically named the South African College in his will as one of four schools in the [[Cape Colony]] where the [[Rhodes Scholarship]] would be awarded on an annual basis for a former student to study at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rhodestrust.org.za/about.html|title=Rhodes Scholarships in Southern Africa|date=3 January 2009|first=Tim|last=Nuttall}}</ref>\n\n==Old Boys' Union==\n===Old Boys===\n[[File:The leader and his deputy, jan smuts on the right and jan hofmeyr on the left.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr and former Prime Minister of South Africa, [[Jan Smuts]]]]\n*Dr. [[Abdullah Abdurahman]] \u2013 Medical Doctor, Cape Muslim leader & founder of the anti-apartheid movement, African People's Organisation and human rights campaigner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sahistory.org.za/people/dr-abdullah-abdurahman|title=Dr. Abdullah Abdurahman|last=sahoboss|date=17 February 2011|website=South African History Online}}</ref>\n*Captain [[Andrew Beauchamp-Proctor]] [[Victoria Cross|VC]], [[Distinguished Service Order|DSO]], [[Military Cross|MC and bar]], [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United Kingdom)|DFC]]\n*[[Kyle Brown (rugby union)|Kyle Brown]] \u2013 [[South Africa national rugby sevens team|South Africa Sevens]] captain 2008\u2013present and [[Olympic Games]] medalist Rio 2016.\n*[[Abraham Fischer]] \u2013 Sole Prime Minister of the Orange River Colony in South Africa<ref>Clingman, Stephen (1998). Bram Fischer: Afrikaner revolutionary. David Philip Publishers. p. 8. {{ISBN|0-86486-677-1}}.</ref>\n*[[Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr (1894-1948)|Jan Hendrik Hofmeyr]] \u2014 former Deputy Prime Minister of South Africa, Minister of Finance and Education, Administrator of the [[Transvaal Province|Transvaal]] and [[Rhodes Scholar]]\n*[[Leonard Hoffmann, Baron Hoffmann]] {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|PC]]}} \u2014 former senior British justice\n*[[Peter Kirsten]] \u2014 former [[South African cricket team|South African]] cricketer\n*[[Dylan Lewis]]- South African sculptor and artist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dylanlewis.co.za/about/bio.php|title=Dylan Lewis \u2013 Biography|website=dylanlewis.co.za}}</ref>\n*[[Gino Lupini]] \u2013 [[Italy national rugby sevens team|Italy Seven]] Rugby 2016\u2013present.\n*[[Nicolaas Petrus van Wyk Louw]] \u2014 [[Afrikaans]]-language poet, playwright, and scholar\n*[[W. E. G. Louw|William Ewart Gladstone van Wyk Louw]] \u2014 Afrikaans-language poet\n*[[Percy Montgomery|Percival Colin \"Percy\" Montgomery]] \u2014 former [[South Africa national rugby union team|South African]] [[rugby union]] footballer, [[2007 Rugby World Cup]] winner & the first Springbok to earn 100 caps.\n*Dr. [[Cecil Moss]] \u2014 former South African rugby union player and South African Rugby Union coach<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rugby15.co.za/rip-dr-cecil-moss-1925-2017/|title=RIP Dr Cecil Moss, 1925\u20132017 \u2013 15.co.za \u2013 - Rugby News, Live Scores, Results, Fixtures|website=rugby15.co.za}}</ref>\n*Sir [[Allan Mossop]], Chief Judge of the [[British Supreme Court for China]]\n*[[Sebastien Rousseau]] \u2013 Three time Olympian Swimmer for South Africa, Commonwealth Games Medalist, South African Record Holder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://floridagators.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=3493|title=Sebastien Rousseau \u2013 Men's Swimming & Diving|website=Florida Gators}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sascoc.co.za/2009/04/14/rousseau-leads-the-charge/|title=Record for Rousseau|date=14 April 2009|website=sascoc.co.za}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://thecgf.com/results/athletes/65499|title=Sebastien Rousseau|website=Commonwealth Games Federation}}</ref>\n*[[Albie Sachs]] \u2014 former justice of the [[Constitutional Court of South Africa]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Sachs|first=Albie|title=Advancing human rights in South Africa|page=iii|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1992}}</ref>\n*[[Ryan Sandes]] \u2013 ultramarathon trail runner who has won all four of the [[4 Deserts]] races, amongst other achievements.\n*[[Stephen Simpson]] \u2014 race car driver and former [[A1 Team South Africa|A1 Grand Prix Team South Africa]] driver\n*[[Ross Skeate]] \u2014 rugby union footballer for [[RC Toulonnais|RC Toulon]] and formerly for [[Stormers]] and [[Western Province (rugby team)|Western Province]] rugby union teams[[File:Percy Montgomery.JPG|right|thumb|Percy Montgomery]]\n*[[Simon Walker (business)|Simon Walker]] \u2014 British business executive, government advisor and Director General of the UK's [[Institute of Directors]]\n*[[Eric Lloyd Williams]] \u2014 journalist and [[World War II]] correspondent\n*[[Solly Zuckerman, Baron Zuckerman]] {{post-nominals|post-noms=[[Order of Merit|OM]], [[Knight Commander of the Order of the Bath|KCB]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]]}} \u2014 British zoologist, public servant and key World War II [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] strategic advisor\n* [[Benjamin Duff]] Springbok rugby player\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Saasveld Forestry College]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{cite book|url=|title=SACS 175 \u2013 A Celebration|last=Veitch|first=Neil|publisher=SACS 175 Book Committee|year=2002|isbn=|location=Cape Town|pages=260|doi=|id=|authorlink=|author2=}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.sacollege.org.za/ South African College Schools Website]\n*[http://www.sacsjunior.org.za/ SACS Junior School]\n*[http://www.sacsrugby.com/ SACS Rugby Site]\n{{CapeTownSchools}}\n\n[[Category:Boarding schools in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Schools in Cape Town]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1829]]\n[[Category:Boys' schools in South Africa]]\n[[Category:1829 establishments in the Cape Colony]]\n[[Category:Newlands, Cape Town]]\n", "name_user": "Stevevandermerve", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_African_College_Schools"}
{"title_page": "British Rail Class 321", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox EMU\n| name = British Rail Class&nbsp;321\n| image = 321344_at_Colchester.jpg\n| caption = [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]] 321344 at {{stnlnk|Colchester}}, coupled to another unit\n| interiorimage = Greater_Anglia_321_Standard_Class_Interior.jpg\n| imagesize = 300px\n| interiorcaption = Standard Class interior of a [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]] Class&nbsp;321 unit\n| background = #012545; color: #fff\n| manufacturer = [[British Rail Engineering Limited]]\n| family =  BR Second Generation ([[British Rail Mark 3|Mark&nbsp;3]])\n| operator = {{unbulleted list|[[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]|[[Northern Trains]]}}\n| formation = 4 cars per unit {{unbulleted list|321/3 and 321/4: {{abbr|DTCO|Driving Trailer Composite Open}}+{{abbr|TSO|Trailer Standard Open}}+{{abbr|PMSO|Pantograph Motor Standard Open}}+{{abbr|DTSO|Driving Trailer Standard Open}}|321/9: DTSO(A)+TSO+PMSO+DTSO(B)}}\n| numberbuilt = 117 units\n| numberservice = 105 units<br>(12 converted to Class&nbsp;320)\n| service = 15 September 1988 \u2013 present\n| weight =  Total - {{convert|137.9|t|LT|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n| carlength =  {{convert|19.95|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| width =  {{convert|2.82|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| height =  {{convert|3.78|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| capacity = '''321/9:''' 309 seats per unit\n| maxspeed =  {{convert|100|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}}\n| poweroutput =   {{convert|1438|hp|kW|0|abbr=on|lk=in}}\n| gauge = {{RailGauge|sg|allk=on}}\n| electricsystem = {{25 kV 50 Hz}} [[Overhead line|overhead]]\n| coupling = [[Tightlock coupling]] compatible \u2013 classes 313-322 inclusive\n}}\n\nThe '''British Rail Class&nbsp;321''' [[alternating current]] (AC) [[electric multiple unit]]s (EMU) were built by [[British Rail Engineering Limited]]'s [[Holgate Road carriage works, York|York Works]] in three batches between 1988 and 1991.<ref name=therailwaycentre>{{cite web|url=http://www.therailwaycentre.com/New%20EMU%20Tech%20Data/EMU_321.html|title=Class 321|work=TheRailwayCentre.Com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027134448/http://www.therailwaycentre.com/New%20EMU%20Tech%20Data/EMU_321.html|archivedate=27 October 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.competition-commission.org.uk/inquiries/ref2007/roscos/pdf/prov_find_glossary_classes_rolling_stock.pdf|archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20081023170025/http://www.competition-commission.org.uk/inquiries/ref2007/roscos/pdf/prov_find_glossary_classes_rolling_stock.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 October 2008|title=Glossary \u2014 Classes of rolling stock|work=Competition Commission}}</ref> The design was successful and led to the development of the similar [[British Rail Class 320|Class&nbsp;320]] and [[British Rail Class 322|Class&nbsp;322]].\n\nToday the class is operated by [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]] and [[Northern Trains]]. Some have been converted to Class&nbsp;320 and are operated by [[Abellio ScotRail]].\n\n==Description==\nThree sub-classes were built. The first two were built for the [[Network SouthEast]] sector for operation on services from [[Liverpool Street railway station|London Liverpool Street]] and [[Euston railway station|London Euston]], while the third was built for [[Regional Railways]] for use on [[West Yorkshire Metro|West Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive]] services from [[Leeds railway station|Leeds]]. As part of the [[privatisation of British Rail]], ownership of the class passed from [[British Rail]]  to the [[Eversholt Rail Group]] in April 1994.<ref>[https://www.eversholtrail.co.uk/fleet-portfolio Class 321] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151002065624/https://www.eversholtrail.co.uk/fleet-portfolio |date=2 October 2015 }} Eversholt Rail</ref>\n\nEach unit consisted of four carriages: two outer driving trailers, one of which contained first class seating; an intermediate motor coach with standard class seating only, roof mounted [[Brecknell Willis high speed pantograph]] and four [[Brush Traction]] TM2141C traction motors (two per bogie); and an intermediate trailer with standard class seating. All have a maximum speed of {{convert|100|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nThey have been modified by the different rail companies which use them. The modifications include new seats, paintwork, lighting and [[passenger information systems]]. \n\n===Class 321/3===\nIn September 1987,  Network SouthEast ordered 46 321/3s for use on services from [[Liverpool Street station|London Liverpool Street]] to [[Cambridge railway station|Cambridge]] and [[Southend Victoria railway station|Southend Victoria]]. The first was unveiled on 15 September 1988.<ref>\"321 rolled-out\" ''[[The Railway Magazine]]'' issue 1051 November 1988 page 687</ref> A further 20 were ordered later.<ref name=therailwaycentre/><ref name=TRUK154>\"The Class 321 EMUs\" ''[[Today's Railways UK]]'' issue 154 October 2014 pages 50-57</ref> Units were numbered 321301-366.\n\nThese units replaced slam-door [[British Rail Class 305|Class 305]], [[British Rail Class 307|Class 307]], [[British Rail Class 308|Class 308]] and [[British Rail Class 309|Class 309]] units on trains to [[Clacton railway station|Clacton]] and [[Southend Victoria railway station|Southend-on-Sea]], and worked services on the newly electrified routes to [[Ipswich railway station|Ipswich]] and [[Harwich Town railway station|Harwich]]. They also displaced many [[British Rail Class 312|Class 312]] slam-door units, which moved over to the [[London, Tilbury and Southend Railway]]. Some of the Class 309s were retained until 1994, and 24 of the newer Class 312 units were retained long-term to work services to [[Walton-on-the-Naze railway station|Walton-on-the-Naze]] and peak services to Clacton, Ipswich and [[Witham railway station|Witham]]. Units carried Network SouthEast livery from new.\n\nIn March 2008, 321361 was named ''Phoenix'' at [[Ilford EMU Depot|Ilford depot]] after it was rebuilt at the disused [[Colchester Carriage Servicing Depot|Colchester shed]] to repair damage caused by an arson attack at Southend Victoria on 10 July 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.therailwaycentre.com/News%20April%202008/290408-NEEA.html|title=321361 becomes Ilford's 'Phoenix'|work=TheRailwayCentre.Com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080505135254/http://www.therailwaycentre.com/News%20April%202008/290408-NEEA.html|archivedate=5 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe first of 30 321/3s to be refurbished at [[Doncaster Works]], as part of the Renatus project \u2013 which modernised the stock with features such as new air conditioning and heating, seating and Wi-Fi \u2013 was completed in December 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eversholtrail.co.uk/news/transformation-of-the-east-anglia-train-fleet-is-underway|title= Transformation of the East Anglia train fleet is underway|date=January 2017|publisher=Eversholt Rail Group}}</ref><ref>\"321 goes for Renatus\" ''Today's Railways UK'' issue 155 October 2015 page 67</ref><ref>\"Refurbished 321 Renatus Launched\" ''[[Modern Railways]]'' issue 821 February 2017 page 10</ref>\n\n===Class 321/4===\n[[File:321401 - Rugby (8959162488).jpg|thumb|right|321401 in [[Network SouthEast]] livery at [[Rugby railway station|Rugby]]]]\nIn October 1988 a second batch of 30 was ordered. It was intended that 25 be used on [[Great Eastern Main Line]] services and five on [[West Coast Main Line]] services, but in the event all were delivered to [[Bletchley TMD]] for use on the latter. A further 18 followed.<ref name=TRUK154/> Units were numbered 321401\u2013321448. The first was delivered in July 1989.<ref>\"Northampton line Class 321 handed over at BREL, York\" ''Rail'' issue 100 page 17</ref>\n\nThese were built for outer-suburban services on the [[West Coast Main Line]], from [[Euston railway station|London Euston]] to [[Northampton railway station|Northampton]], [[Rugby railway station|Rugby]] and [[Birmingham New Street railway station|Birmingham New Street]]. They displaced the then-recently cascaded [[British Rail Class 317|Class 317s]] dating from 1981 which had themselves only just been introduced to the route to replace [[British Rail Class 310|Class 310 units]].<ref name=TRUK154/>\n\nEleven 321/4s were transferred for Great Eastern Main Line services. Following this their First Class area was reduced in size to standardise with the 321/3 units in useon that route. This involved removal of the centre partition and double doors and re-upholstering the First Class style 2+2 seats (which were retained at that time) in the de-classified area into the same fabric as the Standard Class seats. Later the First Class 2+2 seats in this de-classified area were replaced with the standard style 2+3 seating. These 11 units were also fitted with a facility to lock out the power door operation within the unit (a basic kind of Selective Operation) to permit operation of 12-car trains on the Braintree and Southminster branch lines, where some platforms were only long enough for 8-car trains.\n\nThe 11 Great Eastern sets passed to [[First Great Eastern]] in January 1997, passing with the franchise to [[National Express East Anglia]] in April 2004 and [[Abellio Greater Anglia]] in February 2012. The 37 West Coast sets passed to [[Silverlink]] in January 1997, passing with the franchise to [[London Midland]] in November 2007. In 2006 unit 321423 was loaned to [[Northern Rail]] while the 321/9s were being overhauled.\n\nFollowing the delivery of the [[British Rail Class 350|Class 350/2]] fleet, 13 Class 321/4s (401\u2013410, 418\u2013420) were transferred from London Midland to [[First Capital Connect]] and overhauled by [[Wabtec Corporation|Wabtec's]] [[Doncaster Works]].<ref>\"FCC receives its first Class 321\" ''Today's Railways UK'' issue 89 May 2009 page 65</ref><ref>\"FCC signs lease for extra Class 321s and 313s\" ''Today's Railways UK'' issue 101 May 2010 page 65</ref> These passed with the franchise to [[Thameslink and Great Northern|Great Northern]] in September 2014. London Midland also released 17 (421\u2013437) for transfer to National Express East Anglia. The remaining seven (411\u2013417) passed to [[Abellio ScotRail]] in 2015, after being converted to three-car [[British Rail Class 320|Class 320/4]] at Doncaster Works.<ref name=\"auto\">\"ScotRail to receive LM Class 321/4s\" ''Rail'' issue 766 21 January 2015 page 27</ref>\n\nIn 2017 ten units (402, 405\u2013410, 418\u2013420) were transferred from Great Northern to Abellio Greater Anglia.<ref name=MR817>\"More EMUs for Anglia\" ''Modern Railways'' issue 817 October 2016 page 12</ref> As at May 2018 the remaining three (401, 403, 404) are to be converted by Wabtec at [[Kilmarnock]] to Class 320/4 for use with Abellio ScotRail. Another two were to follow.<ref>\"Class 321/4s to be reformed ready for Scottish duties\" ''[[Rail (magazine)|Rail]]'' issue 827 24 May 2017 page 28</ref><ref>\"More Class 320s for ScotRail\" ''[[Railways Illustrated]]'' issue 179 January 2018 page 18</ref>\n\n===Class 321/9===\n[[File:321903 B Doncaster.JPG|thumb|right|321903 in [[West Yorkshire Metro|West Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive]] livery at {{stnlnk|Doncaster}}]]\nThe final batch of three Class 321 were classified 321/9 and were constructed in 1991,<ref name=therailwaycentre/> as an add-on to the main batches. These units have a similar formation to the earlier units except that there is no first class seating. They were ordered by [[Regional Railways]] for use on [[West Yorkshire Metro|West Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive]] services on the newly electrified [[Wakefield line|Doncaster to Leeds]] route, entering service in 1993. From 1995 they also worked on [[Wharfedale line]] services from Leeds to [[Ilkley railway station|Ilkley]].<ref>\"Ilkley working for Class 321\" ''Rail'' issue 264 25 October 1995 page 26</ref> In March 1997 they passed with the Regional Railways North East franchise to Northern Spirit, which became [[Arriva Trains Northern]] in April 2001. In June 1998 they were loaned to [[Great North Eastern Railway|GNER]] to operate Leeds to [[London King's Cross railway station|London King's Cross]] services while its [[InterCity 225]] fleet was grounded with mechanical issues.<ref>\"GNER drafts in foreign EMUs to covers for 225s\" ''Rail'' issue 334 1 July 1998 page 9</ref> All three passed with the franchise to [[Northern Rail]] in December 2004.\n\nThe Class 321/9 units were refurbished at [[Andrew Barclay Sons & Co.|Hunslet-Barclay]], [[Kilmarnock]] from late 2006 to early 2007.<ref name=\"Railway Herald\">{{cite news | url =http://www.railwayherald.co.uk/magazine/pdf/RHUK/Issue60HIGH.pdf| title = News Desk| magazine = Railway Herald | page = 6,7 | issue = 60 | date = 3 November 2006 | accessdate = 16 July 2011}}</ref> The refurbishment included a new livery, refurbished interiors and reliability improvements, similar to the [[British Rail Class 322|Class 322]] EMUs, which were also refurbished at Kilmarnock.<ref name=\"Railway Herald \"/>\n\nThe units transferred to [[Arriva Rail North]] in April 2016, and then [[Northern Trains]] on 1 March 2020. With the Class 331s now in service, 2 of the Class 321/9s transferred to Greater Anglia, as an interim measure until their Class 720 fleet is in service, however neither unit has operated a service as of 12th April 2020\n\n==Current operations==\n===Greater Anglia===\n[[First Great Eastern]] inherited all 66 Class 321/3s and 11 Class 321/4s. The [[East Anglia franchise]] was subsequently taken over by [[National Express East Anglia]], initially branded 'one', and then subsequently by [[Abellio Greater Anglia|Greater Anglia]]. A further 16 were added, upon release from [[London Midland]]. In 2016, 10 of the sets formerly operated by [[Thameslink and Great Northern|Great Northern]] also transferred to Greater Anglia.\n\nThese trains are primarily used for [[Liverpool Street railway station|London Liverpool Street]] to {{stnlnk|Braintree|England}}, {{stnlnk|Southend Victoria}}, {{stnlnk|Southminster}}, {{stnlnk|Ipswich}} (extending to {{stnlnk|Norwich}} during peak time), {{stnlnk|Walton-on-the-Naze}}, {{stnlnk|Clacton-on-Sea}} and [[Colchester Town railway station|Colchester Town]] but can be seen running on any electrified route if other trains fail. These operate as 4, 8 or 12 carriage sets.\n\nThey have also received 2 Class 321/9s from Northern until the [[British Rail Class 720|Class 720s]] enter service, however neither have entered service as of April 2020.\n\n=== Northern Trains ===\n[[Northern Trains]] inherited three Class 321/9 units from the previous operator, [[Arriva Rail North|Northern]]. These units operate on the [[Leeds railway station|Leeds]] to [[Doncaster railway station|Doncaster]] [[Wakefield line]] service and occasionally on the [[Wharfedale line|Wharfedale]] and [[Airedale line|Airedale]] lines alongside [[British Rail Class 322|Class 322]], [[British Rail Class 333|Class 333s]] and [[British Rail Class 331|Class 331s]]. All passed on to [[Northern Rail]] in 2004 and were refurbished in 2006/07. With the Class 331s having replaced them on Northern Trains duties, 2 of the class 321/9s moved to [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]] in March 2020, however, as of April 2020, 321903 remains with Northern Trains.\n\n==Former operations==\n===Silverlink / London Midland===\n[[File:321425 A A Watford Junction.JPG|thumb|left|[[Silverlink]] liveried 321425 at {{stnlnk|Watford Junction}}]]\n[[File:321411 Watford Junction E.JPG|thumb|right|[[London Midland]] 321411 at [[Watford Junction railway station|Watford Junction]]]]\n[[Silverlink]] inherited 37 of the 48 Class 321/4 units. In September 2003, Silverlink's class 321 units were temporarily withdrawn following the discovery of loose bolts on brake discs in some units.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/entire-fleet-of-commuter-trains-withdrawn-579574.html|last=Elston|first=Laura|title=Entire fleet of commuter trains withdrawn|work=[[The Independent]]|date=11 September 2003}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2004, London Euston to Birmingham local services were divided into two separate services: Silverlink retained London to Northampton services, while fellow [[National Express]] subsidiary [[Central Trains]] taking over all local services between Northampton and Birmingham. Initially, Central Trains hired Class 321 units from Silverlink to work their new services, but the arrival of [[British Rail Class 350|Class 350/1s]] meant that very few Class 321 units were then required.\n\nTo accommodate this sub-lease, three Class 321/3 units were transferred from [[National Express East Anglia]] to Silverlink. These were not permitted north of [[Rugby railway station|Rugby]] due to lack of the National Radio Network system (Eastern Region units only had the Cab Secure Radio System used for Driver Only Operated Passenger services) and therefore could not be used on Central Trains services (although they occasionally appeared on services to Rugby at weekends due to the line being closed between Rugby and Birmingham New Street). This ceased in late 2005 with the introduction of Class 350 trains on the Birmingham to [[Liverpool Lime Street railway station|Liverpool]] route. One of these sub-leased units was involved in a low-speed derailment at Watford Yard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/raib-reports/derailment-at-watford-junction-yard|title=Rail Accident Investigation Branch report, Derailment at Watford Junction yard|work=UK Government|accessdate=2 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2007, Central Trains began using Class 321 units on some morning services from Birmingham New Street to [[Walsall railway station|Walsall]].\n\nIn November 2007, [[London Midland]] took over operation of the Class 321 fleet previously used by Silverlink and Central Trains. An order was placed by London Midland for 37 [[British Rail Class 350|Class 350/2s]] to replace the Class 321s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.railnews.co.uk/news/general/2008/07/01-bletchley-depot-closes.html|title=End of the line for award-winning depot|work=Railnews|date=1 July 2008|accessdate=2 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nLondon Midland withdrew most, retaining seven units (411-417).<ref>\"London Midland keeps seven Class 321s\" ''[[Rail Express]]'' issue 158 July 2009 page 51</ref><ref>\"London Midland confirms retention of seven Class 321s\" ''Today's Railways'' issue 92 August 2009 page 63</ref> They were used for peak hour workings between London Euston and Northampton and on the [[Abbey line]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonmidland.com/news/latest-news/london-midlands-321-trains-get-a-fresh-coat-of-paint|title=London Midland\u2019s 321 trains get a fresh coat of paint|work=London Midland|date=11 June 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101126134251/http://londonmidland.com/news/latest-news/london-midlands-321-trains-get-a-fresh-coat-of-paint/|archivedate=26 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonmidland.com/news/latest-news/london-midland-to-introduce-more-seats-for-london-commuters|title=London Midland to introduce more seats for London commuters|work=London Midland|date=1 October 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100122103913/http://www.londonmidland.com/news/latest-news/london-midland-to-introduce-more-seats-for-london-commuters|archivedate=22 January 2010}}</ref> In 2015 all seven were withdrawn for transfer to [[Abellio ScotRail]] to operate on [[Glasgow]] suburban lines, with the last withdrawn on 20 September 2015.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto1\">\"London Midand starts operation of four-car Class 319s\" ''Rail'' issue 785 14 October 2015 page 28</ref> They were replaced by [[British Rail Class 319|Class 319s]].<ref>\"London Midland takes on Class 319s for Euston work\" ''Rail'' issue 779 22 July 2015 page 30</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/> Two (413/414) briefly operated for [[London Overground Rail Operations]] in late 2015, being revinyled in [[London Overground]] livery.<ref>\"LO hires Scottish bound ex LM Class 321/4s\" ''Rail'' issue 788 25 November 2015 page 28</ref> The cascaded Class 321s were reformed to three-car units, by removing the TSO vehicle and reclassified as [[British Rail Class 320|Class 320/4s]].<ref>[http://www.transportscotland.gov.uk/system/files/documents/tsc-basic-pages/Redacted%20Franchise%20Agreement%20-%20CU%20version.pdf The Scottish Ministers and Abellio Scotrail Limited: Scotrail Franchise Agreement] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151129050858/http://www.transportscotland.gov.uk/system/files/documents/tsc-basic-pages/Redacted%20Franchise%20Agreement%20-%20CU%20version.pdf |date=29 November 2015 }} Transport Scotland 6 March 2015</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>\"London Midland 321s Scotland Bound\" ''[[Railways Illustrated]]'' September 2015 page 10</ref> The TSO has been discarded, but one reserve is reserved for Doncaster Wabtec works.<ref>\"321 coaches to be scrapped\" ''Rail'' issue 818 18 January 2017 page 29</ref><ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/james_pilbeam/48139019546/in/photolist-2gkT4nC 769424 (319424) Doncaster 22/06/19]</ref>\n\n===First Capital Connect / Great Northern===\n[[File:321420 321405 London Kings Cross.jpg|thumb|[[First Capital Connect]] 321420 + 321405 at [[London King's Cross railway station|London King's Cross]]]]\n[[First Capital Connect]] received thirteen units (401-410, 418-420) from [[London Midland]], following deliveries of the new [[British Rail Class 350|Class 350/2s]]. The units worked on the Great Northern services from [[London King's Cross railway station|London King's Cross]] to [[Peterborough railway station|Peterborough]] and [[Cambridge railway station|Cambridge]] from December 2010 until May 2017. They passed with the franchise to [[Thameslink and Great Northern|Great Northern]] in September 2014.\n\nAll were replaced in 2016 by [[British Rail Class 387|Class 387s]], cascaded from the [[Thameslink (route)|Thameslink route]].<ref>\"387s Enter Service on Great Northern\" ''Modern Railways'' issue 818 November 2016 page 84</ref> Ten (402, 405-410 and 418-420) moved to [[Ilford EMU Depot|Ilford depot]] for use by [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]<ref>{{cite journal|work=[[Rail (magazine)|Rail]]|issue=754|date=July 2014|title=Govia to switch Class 377 Electrostars to Cambridge|issn=0953-4563}}</ref> with the remaining three (401, 403, 404) are to be converted to Class 320/4s for [[Abellio ScotRail]].<ref>\"More 321s to be reformed for ScotRail\" ''[[The Railway Magazine]]'' issue 1395 June 2017 page 92</ref>\n\n===Arriva Trains Northern / Northern Rail / Arriva Rail North / Northern Trains===\n\nNorthern Trains formerly operated 2 Class 321/9s until these were replaced in 2020 and have transferred to [[Abellio Greater Anglia|Greater Anglia]].\n\n==Renatus project==\n[[File:321304 Ipswich.jpg|thumb|left|Refurbished Class 321 Renatus No. 321304 at [[Ipswich railway station|Ipswich]] in December 2016]]\n[[File:321303 MSO Standard Class Interior.jpg|thumb|right|The interior of Standard Class aboard a Renatus refurbished Class 321]]\nIn December 2013 [[Eversholt Rail Group]] rebuilt 321448 as a demonstrator at [[Doncaster Works]] for a proposed upgrade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eversholtrail.co.uk/news/class-321-demonstrator-launched-on-the-abellio-greater-anglia-network |title=Class 321 Demonstrator launched on the Abellio Greater Anglia Network}}</ref> It featured a new livery, completely refitted interior including two examples of sitting arrangements including 2+2 and 2+3, and a new First Class area. The demonstrator also featured air conditioning, not previously seen on Class 321 trains, along with fixed panel windows to replace opening windows and a new [[Kiepe Electric|Vossloh Kiepe]] traction package.<ref>[http://www.kiepe.knorr-bremse.com/news/press-releases/eversholt-rail-group-vergibt-auftrag-zur-umruestung-der-class-321-fahrzeuge-auf-25kv-ac-antriebstechnik-an-vossloh-kiepe Eversholt Rail Group Award Class 321 AC  25 kV Re-Traction Contract to Vossloh Kiepe] Vossloh Kiepe December 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.railtechnologymagazine.com/rail-news/eversholt-rail-launches-class-321-demonstrator/66425 Eversholt Rail launches Class 321 demonstrator] ''Railway Technology Magazine'' 18 December 2013</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.railtechnologymagazine.com/Rail-News/eversholt-previews-60m-class-321-overhaul |title=Eversholt previews \u00a360m Class 321 overhaul |date=13 August 2015 |website=Rail Technology Magazine}}</ref>\n\nThe production run covered 30 units. The Vossloh Kiepe traction package was installed at [[Wolverton railway works|Wolverton Works]] with the rest of the work performed at Doncaster. The first was completed in December 2016.<ref>[http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/rolling-stock/greater-anglia-launches-modernised-emus.html Greater Anglia launches modernised EMUs] ''[[International Railway Journal]]'' 27 December 2016</ref> In 2017 the prototype returned to Doncaster to be modified to the same specifications as the production units, including being refitted with hopper windows.<ref>\"In Brief\" ''[[Railways Illustrated]]'' issue 178 December 2017 page 13</ref>\n\n==Future==\n\nAfter being awarded the new [[East Anglia franchise]] in August 2016, [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]] placed an order for [[British Rail Class 720|Class 720s]] which will replace the 321s despite the Renatus project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eversholtrail.co.uk/news/class-321-renatus|title=Eversholt Rail|publisher=}}</ref> The first of the new trains is due to enter service in 2020.<ref>The New Face of Rail in Anglia\" ''Modern Railways'' issue 818 November 2016 page 12</ref> \n\nIn the meantime and to support the Renatus project, Greater Anglia leased ten additional Class 321/4s, released by [[Thameslink and Great Northern|Great Northern]].<ref>\"GTR Class 317s confirmed for Anglia switch\" ''Rail'' issue 809 14 September 2016 page 29</ref> These entered service in January 2017 in debranded Great Northern livery.\n\n===Hydrogen conversion===\nIn May 2018 plans were announced to convert some units with [[Alstom]] hydrogen cells, giving the acronym HMU (hydrogen multiple unit).<ref>[http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/traction-rolling-stock/single-view/view/alstom-and-eversholt-plan-fuel-cell-emus.html Alstom and Eversholt plan fuel cell EMUs] ''Railway Gazette International'' 15 May 2018</ref> A number of this class of train will be converted to hydrogen power and operational by 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eadt.co.uk/news/greater-anglia-trains-to-get-hydrogen-engines-1-5844284|title=Old trains\u2019 new life as hydrogen project gets set for take-off|first=Paul|last=Geater|website=East Anglian Daily Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cars/news/hydrogen-fuel-cell-trains-run-british-railways-2022/|title=Hydrogen fuel cell trains to run on British railways from 2022|first=Ed|last=Wiseman|date=7 January 2019|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> The first concept of this conversion, dubbed \"Breeze\", was revealed by Alstom and Eversholt Rail in January 2019.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.railjournal.com/fleet/alstom-and-eversholt-rail-unveil-breeze-hydrogen-train-for-britain/|title=Alstom and Eversholt Rail unveil Breeze hydrogen train for Britain|magazine=International Railway Journal|date=7 January 2019|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Fleet details==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Class\n!Operator\n!No. Built\n!Year Built\n!Unit nos.\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Class 321/3'''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]\n|align=center|66\n|align=\"center\" |1988-90\n|align=left|321301&ndash;366\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|'''Class 321/4'''\n|align=center|36\n|rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" |1989-90\n|align=left|321402, 321405&ndash;410, 321419, 321421-448\n|\n|-\n| Converted to [[British Rail Class 320|Class 320/4s]]\n| align=\"center\" |12\n| align=\"left\" |321401, 321403, 321404<br>321411&ndash;418, 321420\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |'''Class 321/9'''\n|[[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]\n|align=center|2\n| rowspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" |1991\n|align=\"left\"|321901-902\n|Currently being prepared for service\n|-\n|[[Northern Trains]]\n|align=center|1\n|align=\"left\"|321903\n|\n|-\n|}\n[[File:Class 321 Diagram.png|center|800px]]\n\n==Trivia==\n*The Class 321s are nicknamed \"Dusty Bins\". This nickname is derived from an animated character on the game show [[3-2-1]].<ref>{{Cite book\n  | first = Iain| last = Ellis\n  | title = Ellis' British railway Engineering Encyclopedia\n  | publisher = Lulu.com\n  | year = 2006\n  | isbn = 978-1-84728-643-7\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat-inline|British Rail Class 321}}\n\n{{Mark 3-derived}}\n{{British Rail EMU}}\n\n[[Category:British Rail electric multiple units|321]]\n[[Category:BREL products|321]]\n[[Category:Train-related introductions in 1988]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox EMU\n| name = British Rail Class&nbsp;321\n| image = 321344_at_Colchester.jpg\n| caption = [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]] 321344 at {{stnlnk|Colchester}}, coupled to another unit\n| interiorimage = Greater_Anglia_321_Standard_Class_Interior.jpg\n| imagesize = 300px\n| interiorcaption = Standard Class interior of a [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]] Class&nbsp;321 unit\n| background = #012545; color: #fff\n| manufacturer = [[British Rail Engineering Limited]]\n| family =  BR Second Generation ([[British Rail Mark 3|Mark&nbsp;3]])\n| operator = {{unbulleted list|[[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]|[[Northern Trains]]}}\n| formation = 4 cars per unit {{unbulleted list|321/3 and 321/4: {{abbr|DTCO|Driving Trailer Composite Open}}+{{abbr|TSO|Trailer Standard Open}}+{{abbr|PMSO|Pantograph Motor Standard Open}}+{{abbr|DTSO|Driving Trailer Standard Open}}|321/9: DTSO(A)+TSO+PMSO+DTSO(B)}}\n| numberbuilt = 117 units\n| numberservice = 105 units<br>(12 converted to Class&nbsp;320)\n| service = 15 September 1988 \u2013 present\n| weight =  Total - {{convert|137.9|t|LT|abbr=on|lk=on}}\n| carlength =  {{convert|19.95|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| width =  {{convert|2.82|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| height =  {{convert|3.78|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| capacity = '''321/9:''' 309 seats per unit\n| maxspeed =  {{convert|100|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}}\n| poweroutput =   {{convert|1438|hp|kW|0|abbr=on|lk=in}}\n| gauge = {{RailGauge|sg|allk=on}}\n| electricsystem = {{25 kV 50 Hz}} [[Overhead line|overhead]]\n| coupling = [[Tightlock coupling]] compatible \u2013 classes 313-322 inclusive\n}}\n\nThe '''British Rail Class&nbsp;321''' [[alternating current]] (AC) [[electric multiple unit]]s (EMU) were built by [[British Rail Engineering Limited]]'s [[Holgate Road carriage works, York|York Works]] in three batches between 1988 and 1991.<ref name=therailwaycentre>{{cite web|url=http://www.therailwaycentre.com/New%20EMU%20Tech%20Data/EMU_321.html|title=Class 321|work=TheRailwayCentre.Com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071027134448/http://www.therailwaycentre.com/New%20EMU%20Tech%20Data/EMU_321.html|archivedate=27 October 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.competition-commission.org.uk/inquiries/ref2007/roscos/pdf/prov_find_glossary_classes_rolling_stock.pdf|archive-url=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20081023170025/http://www.competition-commission.org.uk/inquiries/ref2007/roscos/pdf/prov_find_glossary_classes_rolling_stock.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 October 2008|title=Glossary \u2014 Classes of rolling stock|work=Competition Commission}}</ref> The design was successful and led to the development of the similar [[British Rail Class 320|Class&nbsp;320]] and [[British Rail Class 322|Class&nbsp;322]].\n\nToday the class is operated by [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]] and [[Northern Trains]]. Some have been converted to Class&nbsp;320 and are operated by [[Abellio ScotRail]].\n\n==Description==\nThree sub-classes were built. The first two were built for the [[Network SouthEast]] sector for operation on services from [[Liverpool Street railway station|London Liverpool Street]] and [[Euston railway station|London Euston]], while the third was built for [[Regional Railways]] for use on [[West Yorkshire Metro|West Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive]] services from [[Leeds railway station|Leeds]]. As part of the [[privatisation of British Rail]], ownership of the class passed from [[British Rail]]  to the [[Eversholt Rail Group]] in April 1994.<ref>[https://www.eversholtrail.co.uk/fleet-portfolio Class 321] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151002065624/https://www.eversholtrail.co.uk/fleet-portfolio |date=2 October 2015 }} Eversholt Rail</ref>\n\nEach unit consisted of four carriages: two outer driving trailers, one of which contained first class seating; an intermediate motor coach with standard class seating only, roof mounted [[Brecknell Willis high speed pantograph]] and four [[Brush Traction]] TM2141C traction motors (two per bogie); and an intermediate trailer with standard class seating. All have a maximum speed of {{convert|100|mph|km/h|0|abbr=on}}.\n\nThey have been modified by the different rail companies which use them. The modifications include new seats, paintwork, lighting and [[passenger information systems]]. \n\n===Class 321/3===\nIn September 1987,  Network SouthEast ordered 46 321/3s for use on services from [[Liverpool Street station|London Liverpool Street]] to [[Cambridge railway station|Cambridge]] and [[Southend Victoria railway station|Southend Victoria]]. The first was unveiled on 15 September 1988.<ref>\"321 rolled-out\" ''[[The Railway Magazine]]'' issue 1051 November 1988 page 687</ref> A further 20 were ordered later.<ref name=therailwaycentre/><ref name=TRUK154>\"The Class 321 EMUs\" ''[[Today's Railways UK]]'' issue 154 October 2014 pages 50-57</ref> Units were numbered 321301-366.\n\nThese units replaced slam-door [[British Rail Class 305|Class 305]], [[British Rail Class 307|Class 307]], [[British Rail Class 308|Class 308]] and [[British Rail Class 309|Class 309]] units on trains to [[Clacton railway station|Clacton]] and [[Southend Victoria railway station|Southend-on-Sea]], and worked services on the newly electrified routes to [[Ipswich railway station|Ipswich]] and [[Harwich Town railway station|Harwich]]. They also displaced many [[British Rail Class 312|Class 312]] slam-door units, which moved over to the [[London, Tilbury and Southend Railway]]. Some of the Class 309s were retained until 1994, and 24 of the newer Class 312 units were retained long-term to work services to [[Walton-on-the-Naze railway station|Walton-on-the-Naze]] and peak services to Clacton, Ipswich and [[Witham railway station|Witham]]. Units carried Network SouthEast livery from new.\n\nIn March 2008, 321361 was named ''Phoenix'' at [[Ilford EMU Depot|Ilford depot]] after it was rebuilt at the disused [[Colchester Carriage Servicing Depot|Colchester shed]] to repair damage caused by an arson attack at Southend Victoria on 10 July 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.therailwaycentre.com/News%20April%202008/290408-NEEA.html|title=321361 becomes Ilford's 'Phoenix'|work=TheRailwayCentre.Com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080505135254/http://www.therailwaycentre.com/News%20April%202008/290408-NEEA.html|archivedate=5 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe first of 30 321/3s to be refurbished at [[Doncaster Works]], as part of the Renatus project \u2013 which modernised the stock with features such as new air conditioning and heating, seating and Wi-Fi \u2013 was completed in December 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eversholtrail.co.uk/news/transformation-of-the-east-anglia-train-fleet-is-underway|title= Transformation of the East Anglia train fleet is underway|date=January 2017|publisher=Eversholt Rail Group}}</ref><ref>\"321 goes for Renatus\" ''Today's Railways UK'' issue 155 October 2015 page 67</ref><ref>\"Refurbished 321 Renatus Launched\" ''[[Modern Railways]]'' issue 821 February 2017 page 10</ref>\n\n===Class 321/4===\n[[File:321401 - Rugby (8959162488).jpg|thumb|right|321401 in [[Network SouthEast]] livery at [[Rugby railway station|Rugby]]]]\nIn October 1988 a second batch of 30 was ordered. It was intended that 25 be used on [[Great Eastern Main Line]] services and five on [[West Coast Main Line]] services, but in the event all were delivered to [[Bletchley TMD]] for use on the latter. A further 18 followed.<ref name=TRUK154/> Units were numbered 321401\u2013321448. The first was delivered in July 1989.<ref>\"Northampton line Class 321 handed over at BREL, York\" ''Rail'' issue 100 page 17</ref>\n\nThese were built for outer-suburban services on the [[West Coast Main Line]], from [[Euston railway station|London Euston]] to [[Northampton railway station|Northampton]], [[Rugby railway station|Rugby]] and [[Birmingham New Street railway station|Birmingham New Street]]. They displaced the then-recently cascaded [[British Rail Class 317|Class 317s]] dating from 1981 which had themselves only just been introduced to the route to replace [[British Rail Class 310|Class 310 units]].<ref name=TRUK154/>\n\nEleven 321/4s were transferred for Great Eastern Main Line services. Following this their First Class area was reduced in size to standardise with the 321/3 units in useon that route. This involved removal of the centre partition and double doors and re-upholstering the First Class style 2+2 seats (which were retained at that time) in the de-classified area into the same fabric as the Standard Class seats. Later the First Class 2+2 seats in this de-classified area were replaced with the standard style 2+3 seating. These 11 units were also fitted with a facility to lock out the power door operation within the unit (a basic kind of Selective Operation) to permit operation of 12-car trains on the Braintree and Southminster branch lines, where some platforms were only long enough for 8-car trains.\n\nThe 11 Great Eastern sets passed to [[First Great Eastern]] in January 1997, passing with the franchise to [[National Express East Anglia]] in April 2004 and [[Abellio Greater Anglia]] in February 2012. The 37 West Coast sets passed to [[Silverlink]] in January 1997, passing with the franchise to [[London Midland]] in November 2007. In 2006 unit 321423 was loaned to [[Northern Rail]] while the 321/9s were being overhauled.\n\nFollowing the delivery of the [[British Rail Class 350|Class 350/2]] fleet, 13 Class 321/4s (401\u2013410, 418\u2013420) were transferred from London Midland to [[First Capital Connect]] and overhauled by [[Wabtec Corporation|Wabtec's]] [[Doncaster Works]].<ref>\"FCC receives its first Class 321\" ''Today's Railways UK'' issue 89 May 2009 page 65</ref><ref>\"FCC signs lease for extra Class 321s and 313s\" ''Today's Railways UK'' issue 101 May 2010 page 65</ref> These passed with the franchise to [[Thameslink and Great Northern|Great Northern]] in September 2014. London Midland also released 17 (421\u2013437) for transfer to National Express East Anglia. The remaining seven (411\u2013417) passed to [[Abellio ScotRail]] in 2015, after being converted to three-car [[British Rail Class 320|Class 320/4]] at Doncaster Works.<ref name=\"auto\">\"ScotRail to receive LM Class 321/4s\" ''Rail'' issue 766 21 January 2015 page 27</ref>\n\nIn 2017 ten units (402, 405\u2013410, 418\u2013420) were transferred from Great Northern to Abellio Greater Anglia.<ref name=MR817>\"More EMUs for Anglia\" ''Modern Railways'' issue 817 October 2016 page 12</ref> As at May 2018 the remaining three (401, 403, 404) are to be converted by Wabtec at [[Kilmarnock]] to Class 320/4 for use with Abellio ScotRail. Another two were to follow.<ref>\"Class 321/4s to be reformed ready for Scottish duties\" ''[[Rail (magazine)|Rail]]'' issue 827 24 May 2017 page 28</ref><ref>\"More Class 320s for ScotRail\" ''[[Railways Illustrated]]'' issue 179 January 2018 page 18</ref>\n\n===Class 321/9===\n[[File:321903 B Doncaster.JPG|thumb|right|321903 in [[West Yorkshire Metro|West Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive]] livery at {{stnlnk|Doncaster}}]]\nThe final batch of three Class 321 were classified 321/9 and were constructed in 1991,<ref name=therailwaycentre/> as an add-on to the main batches. These units have a similar formation to the earlier units except that there is no first class seating. They were ordered by [[Regional Railways]] for use on [[West Yorkshire Metro|West Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive]] services on the newly electrified [[Wakefield line|Doncaster to Leeds]] route, entering service in 1993. From 1995 they also worked on [[Wharfedale line]] services from Leeds to [[Ilkley railway station|Ilkley]].<ref>\"Ilkley working for Class 321\" ''Rail'' issue 264 25 October 1995 page 26</ref> In March 1997 they passed with the Regional Railways North East franchise to Northern Spirit, which became [[Arriva Trains Northern]] in April 2001. In June 1998 they were loaned to [[Great North Eastern Railway|GNER]] to operate Leeds to [[London King's Cross railway station|London King's Cross]] services while its [[InterCity 225]] fleet was grounded with mechanical issues.<ref>\"GNER drafts in foreign EMUs to covers for 225s\" ''Rail'' issue 334 1 July 1998 page 9</ref> All three passed with the franchise to [[Northern Rail]] in December 2004.\n\nThe Class 321/9 units were refurbished at [[Andrew Barclay Sons & Co.|Hunslet-Barclay]], [[Kilmarnock]] from late 2006 to early 2007.<ref name=\"Railway Herald\">{{cite news | url =http://www.railwayherald.co.uk/magazine/pdf/RHUK/Issue60HIGH.pdf| title = News Desk| magazine = Railway Herald | page = 6,7 | issue = 60 | date = 3 November 2006 | accessdate = 16 July 2011}}</ref> The refurbishment included a new livery, refurbished interiors and reliability improvements, similar to the [[British Rail Class 322|Class 322]] EMUs, which were also refurbished at Kilmarnock.<ref name=\"Railway Herald \"/>\n\nThe units transferred to [[Arriva Rail North]] in April 2016, and then [[Northern Trains]] on 1 March 2020. With the Class 331s now in service, 2 of the Class 321/9s transferred to Greater Anglia, as an interim measure until their Class 720 fleet is in service, however neither unit has operated a service as of 12th April 2020\n\n==Current operations==\n===Greater Anglia===\n[[First Great Eastern]] inherited all 66 Class 321/3s and 11 Class 321/4s. The [[East Anglia franchise]] was subsequently taken over by [[National Express East Anglia]], initially branded 'one', and then subsequently by [[Abellio Greater Anglia|Greater Anglia]]. A further 16 were added, upon release from [[London Midland]]. In 2016, 10 of the sets formerly operated by [[Thameslink and Great Northern|Great Northern]] also transferred to Greater Anglia.\n\nThese trains are primarily used for [[Liverpool Street railway station|London Liverpool Street]] to {{stnlnk|Braintree|England}}, {{stnlnk|Southend Victoria}}, {{stnlnk|Southminster}}, {{stnlnk|Ipswich}} (extending to {{stnlnk|Norwich}} during peak time), {{stnlnk|Walton-on-the-Naze}}, {{stnlnk|Clacton-on-Sea}} and [[Colchester Town railway station|Colchester Town]] but can be seen running on any electrified route if other trains fail. These operate as 4, 8 or 12 carriage sets.\n\nThey have also received 2 Class 321/9s from Northern until the [[British Rail Class 720|Class 720s]] enter service, however neither have entered service as of April 2020.\n\n=== Northern Trains ===\n[[Northern Trains]] inherited three Class 321/9 units from the previous operator, [[Arriva Rail North|Northern]]. These units operate on the [[Leeds railway station|Leeds]] to [[Doncaster railway station|Doncaster]] [[Wakefield line]] service and occasionally on the [[Wharfedale line|Wharfedale]] and [[Airedale line|Airedale]] lines alongside [[British Rail Class 322|Class 322]], [[British Rail Class 333|Class 333s]] and [[British Rail Class 331|Class 331s]]. All passed on to [[Northern Rail]] in 2004 and were refurbished in 2006/07. With the Class 331s having replaced them on Northern Trains duties, 2 of the class 321/9s moved to [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]] in March 2020, however, as of April 2020, 321903 remains with Northern Trains.\n\n==Former operations==\n===Silverlink / London Midland===\n[[File:321425 A A Watford Junction.JPG|thumb|left|[[Silverlink]] liveried 321425 at {{stnlnk|Watford Junction}}]]\n[[File:321411 Watford Junction E.JPG|thumb|right|[[London Midland]] 321411 at [[Watford Junction railway station|Watford Junction]]]]\n[[Silverlink]] inherited 37 of the 48 Class 321/4 units. In September 2003, Silverlink's class 321 units were temporarily withdrawn following the discovery of loose bolts on brake discs in some units.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/entire-fleet-of-commuter-trains-withdrawn-579574.html|last=Elston|first=Laura|title=Entire fleet of commuter trains withdrawn|work=[[The Independent]]|date=11 September 2003}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2004, London Euston to Birmingham local services were divided into two separate services: Silverlink retained London to Northampton services, while fellow [[National Express]] subsidiary [[Central Trains]] taking over all local services between Northampton and Birmingham. Initially, Central Trains hired Class 321 units from Silverlink to work their new services, but the arrival of [[British Rail Class 350|Class 350/1s]] meant that very few Class 321 units were then required.\n\nTo accommodate this sub-lease, three Class 321/3 units were transferred from [[National Express East Anglia]] to Silverlink. These were not permitted north of [[Rugby railway station|Rugby]] due to lack of the National Radio Network system (Eastern Region units only had the Cab Secure Radio System used for Driver Only Operated Passenger services) and therefore could not be used on Central Trains services (although they occasionally appeared on services to Rugby at weekends due to the line being closed between Rugby and Birmingham New Street). This ceased in late 2005 with the introduction of Class 350 trains on the Birmingham to [[Liverpool Lime Street railway station|Liverpool]] route. One of these sub-leased units was involved in a low-speed derailment at Watford Yard.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/raib-reports/derailment-at-watford-junction-yard|title=Rail Accident Investigation Branch report, Derailment at Watford Junction yard|work=UK Government|accessdate=2 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2007, Central Trains began using Class 321 units on some morning services from Birmingham New Street to [[Walsall railway station|Walsall]].\n\nIn November 2007, [[London Midland]] took over operation of the Class 321 fleet previously used by Silverlink and Central Trains. An order was placed by London Midland for 37 [[British Rail Class 350|Class 350/2s]] to replace the Class 321s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.railnews.co.uk/news/general/2008/07/01-bletchley-depot-closes.html|title=End of the line for award-winning depot|work=Railnews|date=1 July 2008|accessdate=2 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nLondon Midland withdrew most, retaining seven units (411-417).<ref>\"London Midland keeps seven Class 321s\" ''[[Rail Express]]'' issue 158 July 2009 page 51</ref><ref>\"London Midland confirms retention of seven Class 321s\" ''Today's Railways'' issue 92 August 2009 page 63</ref> They were used for peak hour workings between London Euston and Northampton and on the [[Abbey line]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonmidland.com/news/latest-news/london-midlands-321-trains-get-a-fresh-coat-of-paint|title=London Midland\u2019s 321 trains get a fresh coat of paint|work=London Midland|date=11 June 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101126134251/http://londonmidland.com/news/latest-news/london-midlands-321-trains-get-a-fresh-coat-of-paint/|archivedate=26 November 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.londonmidland.com/news/latest-news/london-midland-to-introduce-more-seats-for-london-commuters|title=London Midland to introduce more seats for London commuters|work=London Midland|date=1 October 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100122103913/http://www.londonmidland.com/news/latest-news/london-midland-to-introduce-more-seats-for-london-commuters|archivedate=22 January 2010}}</ref> In 2015 all seven were withdrawn for transfer to [[Abellio ScotRail]] to operate on [[Glasgow]] suburban lines, with the last withdrawn on 20 September 2015.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref name=\"auto1\">\"London Midand starts operation of four-car Class 319s\" ''Rail'' issue 785 14 October 2015 page 28</ref> They were replaced by [[British Rail Class 319|Class 319s]].<ref>\"London Midland takes on Class 319s for Euston work\" ''Rail'' issue 779 22 July 2015 page 30</ref><ref name=\"auto1\"/> Two (413/414) briefly operated for [[London Overground Rail Operations]] in late 2015, being revinyled in [[London Overground]] livery.<ref>\"LO hires Scottish bound ex LM Class 321/4s\" ''Rail'' issue 788 25 November 2015 page 28</ref> The cascaded Class 321s were reformed to three-car units, by removing the TSO vehicle and reclassified as [[British Rail Class 320|Class 320/4s]].<ref>[http://www.transportscotland.gov.uk/system/files/documents/tsc-basic-pages/Redacted%20Franchise%20Agreement%20-%20CU%20version.pdf The Scottish Ministers and Abellio Scotrail Limited: Scotrail Franchise Agreement] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151129050858/http://www.transportscotland.gov.uk/system/files/documents/tsc-basic-pages/Redacted%20Franchise%20Agreement%20-%20CU%20version.pdf |date=29 November 2015 }} Transport Scotland 6 March 2015</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>\"London Midland 321s Scotland Bound\" ''[[Railways Illustrated]]'' September 2015 page 10</ref> The TSO has been discarded, but one reserve is reserved for Doncaster Wabtec works.<ref>\"321 coaches to be scrapped\" ''Rail'' issue 818 18 January 2017 page 29</ref><ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/james_pilbeam/48139019546/in/photolist-2gkT4nC 769424 (319424) Doncaster 22/06/19]</ref>\n\n===First Capital Connect / Great Northern===\n[[File:321420 321405 London Kings Cross.jpg|thumb|[[First Capital Connect]] 321420 + 321405 at [[London King's Cross railway station|London King's Cross]]]]\n[[First Capital Connect]] received thirteen units (401-410, 418-420) from [[London Midland]], following deliveries of the new [[British Rail Class 350|Class 350/2s]]. The units worked on the Great Northern services from [[London King's Cross railway station|London King's Cross]] to [[Peterborough railway station|Peterborough]] and [[Cambridge railway station|Cambridge]] from December 2010 until May 2017. They passed with the franchise to [[Thameslink and Great Northern|Great Northern]] in September 2014.\n\nAll were replaced in 2016 by [[British Rail Class 387|Class 387s]], cascaded from the [[Thameslink (route)|Thameslink route]].<ref>\"387s Enter Service on Great Northern\" ''Modern Railways'' issue 818 November 2016 page 84</ref> Ten (402, 405-410 and 418-420) moved to [[Ilford EMU Depot|Ilford depot]] for use by [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]<ref>{{cite journal|work=[[Rail (magazine)|Rail]]|issue=754|date=July 2014|title=Govia to switch Class 377 Electrostars to Cambridge|issn=0953-4563}}</ref> with the remaining three (401, 403, 404) are to be converted to Class 320/4s for [[Abellio ScotRail]].<ref>\"More 321s to be reformed for ScotRail\" ''[[The Railway Magazine]]'' issue 1395 June 2017 page 92</ref>\n\n===Arriva Trains Northern / Northern Rail / Arriva Rail North / Northern Trains===\n\nNorthern Trains formerly operated 2 Class 321/9s until these were replaced in 2020 and have transferred to [[Abellio Greater Anglia|Greater Anglia]].\n\n==Renatus project==\n[[File:321304 Ipswich.jpg|thumb|left|Refurbished Class 321 Renatus No. 321304 at [[Ipswich railway station|Ipswich]] in December 2016]]\n[[File:321303 MSO Standard Class Interior.jpg|thumb|right|The interior of Standard Class aboard a Renatus refurbished Class 321]]\nIn December 2013 [[Eversholt Rail Group]] rebuilt 321448 as a demonstrator at [[Doncaster Works]] for a proposed upgrade.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eversholtrail.co.uk/news/class-321-demonstrator-launched-on-the-abellio-greater-anglia-network |title=Class 321 Demonstrator launched on the Abellio Greater Anglia Network}}</ref> It featured a new livery, completely refitted interior including two examples of sitting arrangements including 2+2 and 2+3, and a new First Class area. The demonstrator also featured air conditioning, not previously seen on Class 321 trains, along with fixed panel windows to replace opening windows and a new [[Kiepe Electric|Vossloh Kiepe]] traction package.<ref>[http://www.kiepe.knorr-bremse.com/news/press-releases/eversholt-rail-group-vergibt-auftrag-zur-umruestung-der-class-321-fahrzeuge-auf-25kv-ac-antriebstechnik-an-vossloh-kiepe Eversholt Rail Group Award Class 321 AC  25 kV Re-Traction Contract to Vossloh Kiepe] Vossloh Kiepe December 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.railtechnologymagazine.com/rail-news/eversholt-rail-launches-class-321-demonstrator/66425 Eversholt Rail launches Class 321 demonstrator] ''Railway Technology Magazine'' 18 December 2013</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.railtechnologymagazine.com/Rail-News/eversholt-previews-60m-class-321-overhaul |title=Eversholt previews \u00a360m Class 321 overhaul |date=13 August 2015 |website=Rail Technology Magazine}}</ref>\n\nThe production run covered 30 units. The Vossloh Kiepe traction package was installed at [[Wolverton railway works|Wolverton Works]] with the rest of the work performed at Doncaster. The first was completed in December 2016.<ref>[http://www.railjournal.com/index.php/rolling-stock/greater-anglia-launches-modernised-emus.html Greater Anglia launches modernised EMUs] ''[[International Railway Journal]]'' 27 December 2016</ref> In 2017 the prototype returned to Doncaster to be modified to the same specifications as the production units, including being refitted with hopper windows.<ref>\"In Brief\" ''[[Railways Illustrated]]'' issue 178 December 2017 page 13</ref>\n\n==Future==\n\nAfter being awarded the new [[East Anglia franchise]] in August 2016, [[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]] placed an order for [[British Rail Class 720|Class 720s]] which will replace the 321s despite the Renatus project.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eversholtrail.co.uk/news/class-321-renatus|title=Eversholt Rail|publisher=}}</ref> The first of the new trains is due to enter service in 2020.<ref>The New Face of Rail in Anglia\" ''Modern Railways'' issue 818 November 2016 page 12</ref> \n\nIn the meantime and to support the Renatus project, Greater Anglia leased ten additional Class 321/4s, released by [[Thameslink and Great Northern|Great Northern]].<ref>\"GTR Class 317s confirmed for Anglia switch\" ''Rail'' issue 809 14 September 2016 page 29</ref> These entered service in January 2017 in debranded Great Northern livery.\n\n===Hydrogen conversion===\nIn May 2018 plans were announced to convert some units with [[Alstom]] hydrogen cells, giving the acronym HMU (hydrogen multiple unit).<ref>[http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/traction-rolling-stock/single-view/view/alstom-and-eversholt-plan-fuel-cell-emus.html Alstom and Eversholt plan fuel cell EMUs] ''Railway Gazette International'' 15 May 2018</ref> A number of this class of train will be converted to hydrogen power and operational by 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eadt.co.uk/news/greater-anglia-trains-to-get-hydrogen-engines-1-5844284|title=Old trains\u2019 new life as hydrogen project gets set for take-off|first=Paul|last=Geater|website=East Anglian Daily Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/cars/news/hydrogen-fuel-cell-trains-run-british-railways-2022/|title=Hydrogen fuel cell trains to run on British railways from 2022|first=Ed|last=Wiseman|date=7 January 2019|publisher=|via=www.telegraph.co.uk}}</ref> The first concept of this conversion, dubbed \"Breeze\", was revealed by Alstom and Eversholt Rail in January 2019.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.railjournal.com/fleet/alstom-and-eversholt-rail-unveil-breeze-hydrogen-train-for-britain/|title=Alstom and Eversholt Rail unveil Breeze hydrogen train for Britain|magazine=International Railway Journal|date=7 January 2019|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Fleet details==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Class\n!Operator\n!No. Built\n!Year Built\n!Unit nos.\n!Notes\n|-\n|'''Class 321/3'''\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]\n|align=center|66\n|align=\"center\" |1988-90\n|align=left|321301&ndash;366\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|'''Class 321/4'''\n|align=center|36\n|rowspan=\"2\" align=\"center\" |1989-90\n|align=left|321402, 321405&ndash;410, 321419, 321421-448\n|\n|-\n| Converted to [[British Rail Class 320|Class 320/4s]]\n| align=\"center\" |12\n| align=\"left\" |321401, 321403, 321404<br>321411&ndash;418, 321420\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |'''Class 321/9'''\n|[[Greater Anglia (train operating company)|Greater Anglia]]\n|align=center|2\n| rowspan=\"3\" align=\"center\" |1991\n|align=\"left\"|321901-902\n|Neither are currently in service\n|-\n|[[Northern Trains]]\n|align=center|1\n|align=\"left\"|321903\n|\n|-\n|}\n[[File:Class 321 Diagram.png|center|800px]]\n\n==Trivia==\n*The Class 321s are nicknamed \"Dusty Bins\". This nickname is derived from an animated character on the game show [[3-2-1]].<ref>{{Cite book\n  | first = Iain| last = Ellis\n  | title = Ellis' British railway Engineering Encyclopedia\n  | publisher = Lulu.com\n  | year = 2006\n  | isbn = 978-1-84728-643-7\n}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat-inline|British Rail Class 321}}\n\n{{Mark 3-derived}}\n{{British Rail EMU}}\n\n[[Category:British Rail electric multiple units|321]]\n[[Category:BREL products|321]]\n[[Category:Train-related introductions in 1988]]\n", "name_user": "Greateranglia170", "label": "safe", "comment": "321901 and 902 are currently being prepared for service", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_Rail_Class_321"}
{"title_page": "AMU Literary Festival", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=January 2019}}\n{| class=\"infobox\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" | '''<div style=\"text-align: center;\">AMU Literary Festival</div>'''\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\" | [[File:AMU Literary Festival Logo.jpg|thumb|Logo of the AMU Literary Festival|135x135px]]\n|-\n| '''Genre''' || [[Literary festival]]\n|-\n| '''Frequency''' || Annually, Feb-March\n|-\n| '''Institute''' || [[Aligarh Muslim University]]\n|-\n| '''Organised By''' || University Debating and<br>Literary Club\n|-\n| '''Dates for 2017''' || 3\u20135 March\n|-\n| '''Venue''' || Kennedy House Complex\n|-\n| '''Location''' || [[Aligarh]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]\n|-\n| '''Country''' || [[India]]\n|-\n| '''Patron''' || Prof. Tariq Mansoor\n|-\n| '''Years Active''' || 2015\u2013present\n|-\n| '''Activities''' || Workshops, Lectures,<br>Interaction sessions, Discussions\n|-\n| '''Participants''' || Open for all\n|}\n'''AMU Literary Festival''' is an annual literary festival organised by [[Aligarh Muslim University]]. University Debating and Literary Club (UDLC) formerly University Literary Club of the university organises the festival. Some of the previous invitees include news anchor and author [[Rajdeep Sardesai]], poet [[Keki N. Daruwalla]], politician [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]] and independent journalist [[Rana Ayyub]].\n\n==Organisation==\n{{unsourced section}}\nThe festival is organized under the auspices of the University Literary and Debating Club of the [[Aligarh Muslim University]]. The club consists of students as its members. The festival is the University Debating and Literary Club's flagship event. \n\nJournalists like [[Rajdeep Sardesai]] talking about media, activists such as [[Paranjoy Guha Thakurta]] talking about crony capitalism and novelists like [[:de:Chandrahas Choudhury|Chandrahas Choudhury]] having panel discussions about the Indian novel; the festival is a diverse celebration of literature and mass communication, in all its forms.\n\nThe festival attracts audience from all across the city, transcending the boundary of the university. Previous invitees include the poet [[Keki N. Daruwalla]], politician [[Mani Shankar Aiyar]] and independent journalist [[Rana Ayyub]]. With people from diverse areas coming together and talking about the issues of the day and age, the festival is truly a melting pot of culture. Workshops to teach students about the ins and outs of various forms of writing and public speaking are also conducted as a part of the festival, which rounds out the educational experience.\n\nThe University Literary Club was established in 1973. The club is the extension of the oldest literary Society of AMU, the \"[[Muhammadan Anglo-Oriental College]] Literary Society\" founded by [[Sir Syed Ahmad Khan]] himself. The University Literary Club was rechristened as University Debating Literary Club in 2015.\n\n==Past festivals==\n\n=== Lit Fest 2017 ===\nThe festival was organised from 3-5 March, 2017.\n\n* '''List of Guests in 2017'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Field\n|-\n| [[Swara Bhaskar]] ||  Actress\n|-\n| [[Ashok Vajpeyi]] ||  Poet in Hindi, essayist, literary-cultural critic and a former civil servant\n|-\n| Prof. Manoj K Jha || Professor of Social Work\n|-\n| [[Aditi Rao]] || Poet, activist and essayist. \n|-\n| [[Zafar Anjum]] || Author and journalist\n|-\n| [[Tushar Gandhi]] || Journalist\n|-\n| [[Hansda Sowvendra Shekhar]] || Medical officer and activist\n|-\n| [[Omair Ahmad]] || Writer\n|-\n| Hilal Ahmed<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=About Hilal Ahmed|url=http://www.csds.in/faculty_hilal_ahmed.htm}}</ref> || Editor, writer, teacher and producer ||\n|-\n| [[:de:Chandrahas Choudhury]] || Literary critic and novelist\n|}\n\n=== Literary Festival (2016) ===\n\n* '''List of Guests'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Field !! Video link\n|-\n| [[Rajdeep Sardesai]] || News anchor and author || Watch video - [https://www.youtube.com