ettri/|archive-date=2 February 2017|accessdate=31 March 2015}}</ref>|| Head of first Gross National Happiness Centre<ref name=\"Dr. Saamdu Chettri was the man chosen to head up Bhutan's first Gross National Happiness Centre based in Thimpu.\">{{cite news|author=Dr. Saamdu Chettri|title=The turbulent life story of Bhutan's happiness guru|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-33617673|accessdate=25 July 2015|agency=Candida Beveridge BBC World Service, Bhutan|publisher=BBC|date=25 July 2015}}</ref> ||\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Literary festival]]\n* [[List of literary festivals in India]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|40em}}\n\n{{Aligarh Muslim University}}\n\n[[Category:Literary festivals in India]]\n[[Category:Aligarh Muslim University]]\n", "name_user": "Kleuske", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOrganisation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AMU_Literary_Festival"}
{"title_page": "Billa II", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Billa II The Beginning\n| image          = Billa II poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Chakri Toleti]]\n| producer       = Sunir Kheterpal<br />[[Suresh Balaje]]<br />George Pius\n| story          = Chakri Toleti<br />[[Eric Felberg]]<br />[[Sarath Mandava]]\n| screenplay     = Chakri Toleti<br />[[Sarath Mandava]]<br />Jaffer Mohammed\n| starring       = [[Ajith Kumar]]<br />[[Parvathy Omanakuttan]]<br />[[Bruna Abdullah]]<br />[[Vidyut Jammwal]]<br/>[[Rohit Khurana]]<br />[[Sudhanshu Pandey]]\n| music          = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n| cinematography = [[R. D. Rajasekhar]]\n| editing        = [[Suresh Urs]]\n| studio         = Wide Angle Creations<br />[[Hinduja Group|IN Entertainment]]\n| distributor    = [[Aascar Films]] <small>(India)</small><br />GK Media <small>(USA)</small>\n| released       = {{Film date|2012|07|13|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/83166.html|title='Billa 2' from July 13| work=Indiaglitz| date=25 June 2012| accessdate=4 July 2012 }}</ref>\n| runtime        = 127 minutes<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/billa-2-2012|title=BILLA 2 &#124; British Board of Film Classification|website=bbfc.co.uk}}</ref>\n| language       = Tamil\n| country        = India\n| budget         = {{INR}}35 crore<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-articles/45-for-Enthiran-17-for-Billa-2-18-07-12.html|title=Billa 2 Ajith's costliest|publisher=Behindwoods.com|accessdate=25 April 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218085838/http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-articles/45-for-Enthiran-17-for-Billa-2-18-07-12.html|archivedate=18 February 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| gross          = <!--Must be attributed to a reliable published source with an established reputation for fact-checking. No blogs, no IMDb.-->\n}}\n\n'''''Billa II: The Beginning''''' is a 2012 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]]-language [[action thriller film]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/billa-2|title=BILLA 2 &#124; British Board of Film Classification|website=bbfc.co.uk}}</ref> directed by [[Chakri Toleti]]. It is a [[Prequel]] to ''[[Billa (2007 film)|Billa]]'' and focuses on how David, an ordinary man from the coastal regions of Sri Lanka, becomes Billa, a dreaded underworld don, with [[Ajith Kumar]] reprising the role of the titular character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/66818.html|title=Billa 2's plot revealed|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref> [[Parvathy Omanakuttan]], [[Bruna Abdullah]], [[Vidyut Jammwal]] and [[Sudhanshu Pandey]] appear in supporting roles, all of them marking their debut in Tamil cinema. The film's soundtrack and background score were composed by [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]], while [[R. D. Rajasekhar]] handled the cinematography and [[Suresh Urs]] worked as the editor.\n\nThe film, produced by Wide Angle Creations in association with the [[Hinduja Group]] company IN Entertainment, was officially announced in November 2010, with [[Vishnuvardhan (director)|Vishnuvardhan]] as the director. Due to schedule clashes, Vishnuvardhan was replaced by Chakri Toleti, with a new script having been penned by a team involving Toleti, [[Sarath Mandava]] and Eric Felberg.\n\nPrincipal photography happened between July 2011 and December 2011. The filming primarily took place at [[Tamil Nadu]], Goa, [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]] and in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]. ''Billa II'' was released worldwide on 13 July 2012 and a dubbed Telugu version titled ''David Billa'' was also simultaneously released in [[Andhra Pradesh]] and [[Telangana]] (then both states were combined under Andhra Pradesh state).<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-to-release-wide-in-foreign-languages-news-tamil-mg0jN1dcgjg.html?scategory=tamil|title=Billa 2 to release wide in foreign languages!|publisher=Sify|date=26 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> The film garnered mixed reviews on release, though it collected decently at the box office because of the hype that created during pre-release. Eventually the film turned out to be one of the cults in Tamil films for its making and stylish presentation of protogonist.\n\n==Plot==\nDavid Billa ([[Ajith Kumar]]), an Sri Lankan refugee along with several others, arrives to the camp in [[Rameswaram]] where he befriends Ranjith ([[Yog Japee]]). The refugee camp is constantly terrorised by corrupt police officer Raghubir Sinha ([[Krishna Kumar (actor)|Krishna Kumar]]). Billa attacks Raghubir when he tries to forcefully detain one of his friends and for revenge he gets Billa tortured in police cell and vows to make him suffer. A few days later, Billa and Ranjith are hired to transport fish from Rameswaram to Chennai. But unknown to them, it was a plot by Raghubir to trap them as the truck they were driving had diamonds inside. But Billa realises the ploy and kills all the cops and drive the truck to its destination where they meet Selvaraj ([[Ilavarasu]]), who is pleased by Billa's loyalty and includes him in his business. Billa murders Raghubir at a [[brothel]].\n\nKotiswara Rao ([[Manoj K. Jayan]]) visits Selvaraj and asks him if he could help in selling off the heroin he had brought along with him. Billa volunteers to sell it off and tries to deal the heroin to a local thug who refuses to pay for it in return. In a brutal scuffle that ensues where one of Billa's friends is slaughtered, Billa kills them all and goes directly to Koti's boss Abbasi ([[Sudhanshu Pandey]]) with the money and the heroin, who is very impressed by the former and recruits him. Abbasi is in business with Barovian mafia led by Dimitri ([[Vidyut Jammwal]]), who tells him that his arms consignment has been held by the Indian coastal guard and he asks for his help. Billa and Ranjith agree to retrieve the consignment for him and are congratulated by Dimitri for their work.\n\nBilla climbs the ladder of Abbasi's gang quickly. Later he learns of his sister death and brings his niece Jasmine ([[Parvathy Omanakuttan]]) with him. Billa and Koti travel to Russia to meet Dimitri, who happens to own an arms and ammunition manufacturing unit. Billa signs a deal with Dimitri without Abbasi's knowledge who learns this from Koti and is furious at Billa. Tensions further increase when Billa beats up Satish Kumar ([[Rohit Khurana]]), the son of an influential minister Praveen Kumar ([[Dinesh Lamba]]), when he tries to misbehave with Jasmine in a party. Abbasi expresses his discontent and vents at him. Billa, surprised and enraged at his ingratitude, walks away with Ranjith. Billa, Ranjith, and Ram (Sarath Mandava) plot to venture into the drug business on their own during the carnival. At the carnival, Billa is betrayed by Ram and is brutally attacked. However, he survives and finishes off the assailants, kills Abbasi and Ram, and becomes Goa's most powerful gangster. He begins a relationship with Abbasi's girlfriend Sameera ([[Bruna Abdullah]]).\n\nDimitri arrives to Goa and has a fallout with Billa when they try to negotiate a deal with Billa. So, Dimitri seeks to oust him. Dimitri seeks out the help of Koti, Satish, and Praveen to eliminate David. They proceed to kill Chief Minister Mohan Kanth ([[Madhusudhan Rao (actor)|Madhusudhan Rao]]), and the blame falls upon Billa. However, Billa is freed by threatening the judge and his family. After coming out, Billa rescues his niece from Koti's men and informs Sameera to take Jasmine to safety. But Sameera betrays Billa, informs the minister's son who hold Billa and Jasmine captives. Billa while being held to the ground and is mocked at by Satish, who slits Jasmine's throat. Enraged at her death, Billa overpowers and kills everyone.\n\nMeanwhile, in Russia, Dimitri is having an auction of his weapons, and Koti is present with him. He shows his factory in his computer via a series of webcams and much to everyone's shock, Billa is seen destroying his factory in Georgia. He also sees his consignment train go off course. He gets angered and kills Koti for not killing Billa, and he sets out himself to finish the task. The arms factory is destroyed by Billa and his friends. Dimitri arrives and follows his delivery train, when to his shock, the delivery train is blown by Billa, who would be waiting for him on his own helicopter. After an intense battle, Billa kills Dimitri. In the epilogue, Billa and Ranjith board a plane out of the country, and the loose threads (Sameera, Police and Lawyer) are eliminated by Billa's men.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Ajith Kumar]] as David Billa\n* [[Parvathy Omanakuttan]] as Jasmine\n* [[Bruna Abdullah]] as Sameera\n* [[Sudhanshu Pandey]] as Abbasi\n* [[Vidyut Jammwal]] as Russian Arms dealer Dimitri\n* [[Yog Japee]] as Ranjith\n* [[Manoj K. Jayan]] as Kotiswara Rao\n* [[Ilavarasu]] as Selvaraj\n* [[Sricharan (actor)|Sricharan]] as Bobby\n* [[Krishna Kumar (actor)|Krishna Kumar]] as Raghubir Sinha\n* [[Sriman (actor)|Sriman]] as Billa's Lawyer\n* [[Madhusudhan Rao (actor)|Madhusudhan Rao]] as Goa Chief Minister Mohan Kanth\n* [[Janaki Sabesh]] as David Billa's sister\n* Byron Gibson as Russian Mafia Boss\n* [[Rohit Khurana]] as Satish Kumar\n* [[Dinesh Lamba]] as Praveen Kumar\n* Ron Smoorenburg as Russian Martial Artist\n* Balaji shathivel as Billa 's henchmen\n* [[Sarath Mandava]] as Ram\n* Theepatti Ganesh as Muthu\n* Ashok Bentwal\n* [[Rahman (actor)|Rahman]] as Jagdish (quick cameo, reprising role from Billa 1)\n* [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]] as special appearance \n* [[Meenakshi Dixit]] special appearance in item number \"Madurai Ponnu\"\n* Nicole Amy Madell special appearance in item number \"Yedho Mayakkam\" and \"Gangster\" \n* [[Gabriela Bertante]] special appearance in item number \"Yedho Mayakkam\"\n* [[Ashok Selvan]] as young Billa in photograph (uncredited role)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/did-you-know-/Ashok-Selvans-picture-was-featured-in-Billa-2/articleshow/46986564.cms|title=Ashok Selvan's picture was featured in Billa 2 - Times of India|publisher=|accessdate=30 September 2016}}</ref>\n{{colend}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\nIn 2008, reports claimed that [[Soundarya Rajinikanth]] was planning to make a follow-up after noting ''[[Billa (2007 film)|Billa]]''{{'}}s commercial success, to be produced by [[Ocher Studios]] in association with [[Warner Bros.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/may-08-01/billa-07-05-08.html|title=Will Ajith do Billa \u2013 2 ?|publisher=Behindwoods|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/tamil/exclusive/2008/soundarya-rajinikanth-billa-2-190508.html|title=Soundarya Rajini confirms Billa-2|publisher=Oneindia.in|date=19 May 2008|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> However, the sequel did not materialise and the idea was dropped, with Ajith Kumar, Vishnuvardhan and Soundarya getting busy with other projects.\n\nIn 2010, sources confirmed that Vishnuvardhan had finished penning the script for a prequel, which would star Ajith Kumar as the titular character again,<ref>{{cite web|title=BREAKING NEWS: AJITH'S BILLA 2|publisher=Behindwoods|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jul-10-05/ajith-vishnuvardhan-billa-28-07-10.html|year=|accessdate=28 July 2010}}</ref> and would commence in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|author=Moviebuzz|title=Vishnuvardhan to make Billa prequel!|publisher=Sify|url=http://sify.com/movies/tamil/fullstory.php?id=14951341|year=2010|accessdate=29 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100801210130/http://sify.com/movies/tamil/fullstory.php?id=14951341|archive-date=1 August 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> The project became officially announced in late 2010, after Ajith Kumar signed up to the prequel and first production poster were published to the media.<ref name=\"Billa2sify11\">{{cite web|title=It's official: Ajith signs 'Billa II'|publisher=IndiaGlitz|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/61364.html|year=2010|accessdate=4 November 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Billa2sify\">{{cite web|author=Moviebuzz|title=Breaking News- Billa 2 confirmed|publisher=Sify|url=http://sify.com/movies/breaking-news-billa-2-confirmed-news-tamil-klel6kcbgfc.html|year=2010|accessdate=4 November 2010}}</ref> Further details were disclosed, with [[Suresh Balaje]], son of producer and actor K. Balaji, who produced the original ''Billa'' with Rajinikanth, and George Pius from Wide Angle Creations banner, being confirmed as the producer,<ref name=\"Billa2sify11\"/> who would associate with Mumbai-based IN Entertainment Limited, a [[Hinduja Group|Hinduja group company]].<ref name=\"Billa2sify\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiainfoline.com/Markets/News/IN-Entertainment-ties-up-with-Wide-Angle-Creations/5071125059|title=IN Entertainment ties up with Wide Angle Creations|publisher=Indiainfoline.com|date=1 February 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> The entire production team of the ''Billa'' remake, including cinematographer [[Nirav Shah]], editor [[A. Sreekar Prasad]] and music director [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]], were announced to be retained for the sequel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-02-02/news-interviews/28372663_1_vishnu-telugu-film-heroine|title=Vishnuvardhan's double dhamaka|work=The Times of India|date=2 February 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn a turn of events, [[Vishnuvardhan (director)|Vishnuvardhan]] opted out of the project citing that his dates clashed with the making of his Telugu film, ''[[Panjaa]]'' (earlier titled as ''The Shadow'').<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-02-18/news-interviews/28614918_1_director-vishnuvardhan-venkat-prabhu-directed-mankatha-film|title=Vishnu cancels billa date|work=The Times of India|date= 18 February 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> [[Chakri Toleti]] who directed the 2009 [[Kamal Haasan]]-[[Mohanlal]] starrer ''[[Unnaipol Oruvan (2009 film)|Unnaipol Oruvan]]'' was subsequently signed on by the producers to direct the venture.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-02-22/news-interviews/28624795_1_ajith-billa-thala|title=Ajith gets new script, director for Billa 2|work=The Times of India|date=22 February 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> In May 2011, Chakri Toleti held his first press conference stating that production would begin in late June 2011 and revealing that \"''Billa 2'' would focus on how David, an ordinary man from the coastal [[Thoothukudi]] in South Tamil Nadu, becomes Billa, a dreaded underworld don\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-to-start-by-june-end-news-kollywood-lfsoQhdhgia.html|title=Billa 2 to start by June end|publisher=Sify|date=18 May 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> David's character was afterwards widely reported to be either a refugee from [[Tamil Eelam]] or a Tamilian from [[Sri Lanka]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/70525.html|title=How does Ajith become a don in 'Billa 2'?|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/ajith-not-a-sri-lankan-refugee-in-billa-ii/239098-62-128.html|title='Billa II': Ajith not playing Sri Lankan refugee|work= [[CNN-IBN]]|date=|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> Both the director and the producer refused to confirm the statements, disclosing only that the film would depict David's journey over a period of five years.<ref name=\"articles.timesofindia.indiatimes\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-13/news-interviews/31158865_1_billa-thala-ajith-death-defying-stunts|title=Death-defying stunts, Ajith style!|work=The Times of India|date=13 March 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nWith Vishnuvardhan's exit from the project, his script was also scrapped, and Toleti along with Ajith Kumar began penning a new script for the prequel.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\"/> Yuvan Shankar Raja only was retained from the original production team,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/64393.html|title='Billa 2': Yuvan on board|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> with the rest of the technical crew being finalised in the following weeks.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-03-02/news-interviews/28646721_1_mankatha-ajith-billa|title=Ajith bonding with Yuvan|work=The Times of India|date=2 March 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> [[Hemant Chaturvedi]], who hitherto had worked in [[Bollywood]] productions only, was signed on to replace [[Nirav Shah]] as the cinematographer after the latter's schedules clashed with the making of his other film, ''[[Vettai]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/hemant-chaturvedi-is-billa-2-cameraman-news-tamil-lehlhliadcd.html|title=Hemant Chaturvedi is Billa 2, cameraman|publisher=Sify|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> However, in July 2011, Hemant Chaturvedi too moved out of the project, fearing that the delay in commencement of ''Billa 2'' may hurt his chances in Bollywood, and [[R. D. Rajasekhar]] was appointed as the new cinematographer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Who moved out of Billa 2 now?|publisher=Behindwoods|accessdate=8 July 2011|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jul-11-02/ajith-billa-2-08-07-11.html}}</ref> V. Selvakumar who had notably worked in ''[[Madrasapattinam]]'' was selected as the art director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/68543.html|title='Billa 2' starts rolling|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> The crew also announced that the film would become the first Indian production to be filmed with an [[Red Digital Cinema Camera Company|RED EPIC Camera]], being shot at 5K resolution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jul-11-01/billa-2-ajith-05-07-11.html|title=Billa-2 and the James Cameron Connection|publisher=Behindwoods|date=5 July 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> Writer Ee. Raa. Murugan, who had previously collaborated with Chakri Toleti in the [[Kamal Hassan]]-starrer ''Unnaipol Oruvan'', was appointed to write the dialogue.\n\n===Casting===\nFrom the previous film, the producers made it clear that apart from [[Ajith Kumar]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/66737.html|title=Ajith's new look in 'Billa 2'|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> and [[Rahman (actor)|Rahman]], most of the other characters would not be retained. The female lead role was expected to be handed to [[Anushka Shetty]], but despite media speculation she was not signed on.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/will-anushka-sign-billa-2-opposite-ajit-news-tamil-lb1ufQdjjhj.html|title=Will Anushka sign Billa-2 opposite Ajit?|publisher=Sify|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/most-wanted-anushka-news-tamil-lcmlAiabeah.html|title=Most Wanted- Anushka|publisher=Sify|date=12 February 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> The female lead role was handed to debutant [[Huma Qureshi (actress)|Huma Qureshi]], a Mumbai-based theatre actor who had previously been featured in commercials, with Toleti finalising Qureshi after a nationwide search for an actress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/Huma-Qureshi-opposite-Ajit-in-Billa-2/785737/|title=Huma Qureshi opposite Ajit in Billa 2|work=The Indian Express |accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/south-first-look-ajiths-new-heroine/20110412.htm|title=Meet Ajith's new heroine|publisher=Rediff|date=12 April 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/65678.html|title=Billa 2 to bring on fresh beauty|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> However, she was removed from the project by September 2011, due to date clashes,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-10/news-interviews/30138845_1_billa-ajith-50th-film|work=The Times of India | title=Huma Qureshi out of Billa 2?| date=10 September 2011}}</ref> and became replaced by [[Miss India World]] 2008 [[Parvathy Omanakuttan]] later that month,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moviecrow.com/News/97/parvathy-omnakuttan-to-pair-with-ajith|title=Parvathy Omnakuttan to pair with Ajith|publisher=|accessdate=30 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/parvathy-is-ajiths-heroine-in-billa-2-news-tamil-lj3j5degaba.html|title=Parvathy is Ajiths heroine in Billa-2|publisher=Sify|date=29 September 2011|accessdate=29 September 2011}}</ref> who the director had spotted and offered the role of Jasmine at a fashion show.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jiji Ann Cherian|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/tabloid/kochi/bowled-over-billa-935|title=Bowled over by Billa|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=6 April 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> Parvathy described her character as a \"simple girl who transforms into a modern person\" and that Billa looks up to, adding that she was had more scenes in the \"emotional part\" of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/view/regional/158051?device=iphone|title=Parvathy Omanakuttan signs Billa 2|work = [[NDTV]]|date=15 December 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> Bollywood actress and model [[Bruna Abdullah]] was selected to portray another significant character,<ref name=\"Rediff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/miss-world-runner-up-in-billa-two/20111018.htm|title=Miss World runner-up in Billa 2|publisher=Rediff|date=18 October 2011|accessdate=17 December 2011}}</ref> which she went on term as \"super powerful, very strong and sexy\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-12-21/news-interviews/30542105_1_billa-ajith-chakri-toleti|title=I'm here to stay: Bruna Abdullah|work=The Times of India|date=21 December 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> Besides models Abdullah, and Parvathy Omanakuttan, [[Meenakshi Dixit]] was recruited for the item number \"Madurai Ponnu\". Another three models including, [[Gabriela Bertante]], [[Nicole Amy Madell]], and an unknown artist, was recruited to perform a dance number \"Yedho Mayakkam\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-08/news-interviews/31305238_1_billa-ajith-chakri-toleti|title=Brazilian model for Ajith|work=The Times of India|date=8 April 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-17/news-interviews/32269934_1_ajith-dancing-tamil-film|title=Billa II's Oomph factor!|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=17 June 2012|accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nTelevision actor [[Krishna Kumar (actor)|Krishna Kumar]], was signed on to play a \"dirty cop\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-09/news-interviews/29397248_1_malayalam-film-kk-three-films|title=Krishnakumar is a happy man|work=The Times of India|date= 9 April 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> In June 2011, [[Sudhanshu Pandey]], a former model who has appeared in several Hindi films, was given the role of a \"greying ganglord\", who becomes the mentor to the young David,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/sudhanshu-pandey-plays-a-baddie-in-billa-2/885449/0|title=Sudhanshu Pandey plays a baddie in Billa 2|work=The Indian Express|date=9 December 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> whilst Malayalam character actor [[Manoj K. Jayan]] was roped in for a \"key role\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/ajiths-7-million-billa-2-starts-rolling-news-tamil-lhorF9ecfia.html|title=Ajith's $7 million Billa 2 starts rolling|publisher=Sify.com|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> Actress [[Vimala Raman]] was signed on to make a special appearance in the film,<ref>{{cite web|author= Anupama Subramanian|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/vimala-raman-enters-bollywood-078|title=Vimala Raman enters Bollywood|work=Deccan Chronicle |date=2 July 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/66818.html|title='Billa 2's plot revealed|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> however she opted out in July 2011 citing date problems.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-07-13/news-interviews/29768327_1_billa-tamil-film-vimala-raman|title=Vimala says no to Billa 2|work=The Times of India|date=13 July 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> [[Meenakshi Dixit]] was later finalised for that role and shot her scenes in July 2011 during the first schedule.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-11-16/news-interviews/30410671_1_billa-girl-flick|work=The Times of India | title=Meenaxi Dixit: Item girl for Billa 2| date=16 November 2011}}</ref> [[Vidyut Jamwal]], who played negative roles in the Hindi film ''[[Force (2011 film)|Force]]'' (2011) and the Telugu film ''[[Oosaravelli]]'' (2011), was selected to play the villain, also making his debut in Tamil cinema.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-11-14/news-interviews/30402013_1_billa-ajith-martial-arts|work=The Times of India | title=Vidyut takes on Ajith| date=14 November 2011}}</ref> In December 2011 sources revealed that [[Sricharan (actor)|Sricharan]], who starred in ''[[Payanam (2011 film)|Payanam]]'', was shooting for a supporting role in the film.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-12-03/news-interviews/30471298_1_sricharan-tehran-flight|title=Sricharan's dramatic airport experience|work=The Times of India |date=3 December 2011|accessdate=18 December 2011}}</ref> Reports in February 2012 suggested that the team was trying to sign [[Nayantara]], who played the female lead in ''Billa'', for a [[cameo role]];<ref>{{cite web|author=Anupama Subramanian|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/nayanthara-%E2%80%99s-cameo-billa-2-006|title=Nayanthara 's cameo in Billa 2|work=Deccan Chronicle |date=26 February 2012|accessdate=11 March 2012}}</ref> the actress refuted the rumours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/feb-12-04/ajith-nayan-27-02-12.html|title=Nayanthara Denies Ajith Rumors|publisher=Behindwoods|date=27 February 2012|accessdate=11 March 2012}}</ref> Furthermore, composer [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]] on Toleti's insistence agreed to make a brief appearance in one of the songs.<ref>{{cite news|author=Janani Karthik|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/yuvan-dances-billa-2-050|title=Yuvan dances in Billa 2|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=16 April 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> Sources also reported that director [[Sebastian Seeman|Seeman]] would be acting in the film.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}\n\n===Filming===\nThe film's production was delayed as Ajith Kumar's previous film, ''[[Mankatha]]'', progressed beyond the anticipated completion dates. In March 2011, the producers released a press note that the film would begin in early May 2011, however this failed to happen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-press-release-news-tamil-ldbjoSbaije.html|title=Billa 2 \u2013 Press Release|publisher=Sify|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> During that period, it was also suggested that ''Billa II'' may not be Ajith Kumar's successive project and commence only after the actor completed a film with [[M. Raja]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-20/news-interviews/29459707_1_billa-50th-film-mankatha-thala|title=Billa 2 isn't Ajith's 51sth film!|work=The Times of India|date=20 April 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> Eventually, a photo shoot was held in June 2011 with Ajith sporting an appearance of a man in his mid-twenties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jun-11-04/ajith-billa-2-24-06-11.html|title=Ajith's Look in Billa 2!|publisher=Behindwoods|date=24 June 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> [[Principal photography]] commenced on 14 July 2011 at the [[Ramoji Film City]] in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> Filming during the first 30-day schedule throughout July and August 2011 was held in Hyderabad and [[Visakhapatnam|Vizag]].<ref name=\"Rediff\"/> As part of the schedule, one song was shot in [[Puducherry]] under the direction of choreographer [[Raju Sundaram]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Prakash K. L.|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/tamil/news/2011/ajith-shoots-foot-tapping-billa-300811.html|title=Ajith shoots foot-tapping number for Billa|publisher=Oneindia.in|date=30 August 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> Both actresses Parvathy Omanakuttan and Bruna Abdullah joined the crew for the second schedule in [[Goa]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/70435.html|title=Ajith's 'Billa 2' status quo|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> that lasted for 39 days and ended in the first week of November.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/meet-the-villian-of-ajiths-billa-two/20111117.htm|title=Meet the {{sic|villian|nolink=y}} of Ajith's Billa 2|publisher=Rediff|date=17 November 2011|accessdate=17 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the third week of November, a unit of thirty-six members left for [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] in Eastern Europe for the final 20-day schedule of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-goa-schedule-complete-news-tamil-llfkmHceidd.html|title=Billa 2, Goa schedule complete|publisher=[[Sify]]|date=6 November 2011|accessdate=17 December 2011}}</ref> In Georgia, the crew filmed at the country's capital, [[Tbilisi]], [[Borjomi]] and [[Rustavi]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-12-19/news-interviews/30533751_1_shot-shooting-songs|work=The Times of India | title=K-Town goes to Europe| date=19 December 2011}}</ref> ''Billa II'' became the first Indian film to be shot at the [[Likani|Likani Palace]], which functions as a summer residence of the [[President of Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/snowfall-play-games-on-the-sets-of-billa-2-news-tamil-mf4of4bhjaj.html?ref=false|title=Snowfall play games on the sets of Billa-2|publisher=Sify|date=30 May 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> Midway through the filming, heavy snowfall began. The crew, however, carried on shooting and later reshot the complete sequence with the snowy background to maintain the continuity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/may-12-05/billa-2-ajith-30-05-12.html|title=Billa 2 Was Shot at Likani Palace|publisher=Behindwoods|date=30 May 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> The climax portions were also filmed there against a snowy backdrop, for which [[aerial shot]]s were done from a helicopter.<ref>{{cite news|author=Janani Karthik|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/billa-2-done-967|title=Billa 2 is done!|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=19 December 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> Approximately half a million dollars were spent for the whole schedule in Georgia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.investingeorgia.org/?107/1732/|title=Billa-2 First \"Bollywood\" movie is shot in Georgia|publisher=Invest in Georgia|date=|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> which was finished by mid-December.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/dec-11-03/ajith-billa-2-20-12-11.html|title=Billa 2 wrapped up|publisher=Behindwoods|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref> In February 2012, the remaining scenes, including the film's title song,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-02-18/news-interviews/31074689_1_billa-chakri-toleti-51st-film|title=Billa 2 title song finally shot!|work=The Times of India|date=18 February 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-title-song-picturised-news-tamil-mctmocicbae.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 title song picturised|publisher=Sify|date=19 February 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> were canned at the [[Ramoji Film City]] in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]],<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-makes-brisk-progress-news-tamil-mcqlVwagfeb.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 makes brisk progress|publisher=Sify|date=16 February 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> despite the ongoing strike in the film industry.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-02-16/news-interviews/31066307_1_billa-chakri-toleti-strike|title=Billa 2 shoot despite strike|work=The Times of India|date=16 February 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> An [[item number]] \"Yedo Mayakkam\" featuring three models was shot in a studio in Goa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/80649.html|title=Ajith to shake a leg with Gabriela Bertante!|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=9 April 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> Although producer Kheterpal had named [[Bangkok]], Thailand as a potential location for filming,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.filmbiz.asia/news/billa-2-is-big-budget-bet-for-tamil-films|title=Billa 2 is big budget bet for Tamil films| publisher=Filmbiz.asia|date=14 July 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> shooting was not held there. The entire filming was completed over a period of 90 days.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/billa-2-done-967|work=Deccan Chronicle|accessdate=20 December 2011|title=Billa 2 is done!}}</ref>\n\nThree stunt choreographers were involved in the making of ''Billa II''. The stunt sequences in Georgia were partly choreographed by an award-winning German-based company led by stuntman Stefan Richter,<ref name=\"articles.timesofindia.indiatimes\" /><ref>{{cite news|author=K. R. Manigandan|url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article3303485.ece|title=Shot Cuts|work=The Hindu|date=11 April 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012|location=Chennai, India}}</ref> while the climax action scenes were done by Kecha Khamphakdee's Jaika Stunt team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-stunt-master-praises-ajit-news-tamil-mesoqxgaeih.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 stunt master praises Ajit!|publisher=Sify.com|date=18 April 2012|accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"indiatimes2\">{{cite news|author=V Lakshmi|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-29/news-interviews/32458399_1_chakri-toleti-stunt-action-sequences|title=When Billa got into action!|work=The Times of India|date=29 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> K. Rajasekhar choreographed the fight sequences in Hyderabad and Goa.<ref name=\"indiatimes2\"/> Madhu Sudhanan, a [[VFX creative director]], said that [[visual effects|VFX]] had been used in action sequences, in \"set extensions\" and in sequences involving [[3-D film|3D]].<ref>{{cite news|author=K. Jeshi|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article3588625.ece|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130204072159/http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article3588625.ece|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 February 2013|title=Behind the Frames|work=The Hindu|date=30 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012|location=Chennai, India}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{main|Billa II (soundtrack)}}\n\n[[Yuvan Shankar Raja]], who had also worked on the score of ''[[Billa (2007 film)|Billa]]'' (2007), composed the soundtrack and score of ''Billa II'', becoming his fifth project starring [[Ajith Kumar]]. The album consists of six tracks, five songs and a [[theme music]] track.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/sony-music-snaps-billa-2-audio-news-tamil-mdglVqbcgaf.html|title=Sony Music snaps Billa 2 audio|publisher=Sify|date=6 March 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> The producer however confirmed that the film would feature a sixth song, not included in the soundtrack that was composed for a [[belly dance]] sequence.<ref>{{cite news|author=K. R. Manigandan|url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article3569004.ece|title=Shot Cuts: A weird friendship|work=The Hindu|date=25 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012|location=Chennai, India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/83267.html|title=New song in 'Billa 2!'|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=28 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> [[Na. Muthukumar]] agreed to write the lyrics for the songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newindianexpress.com/entertainment/interviews/article432929.ece|title=I compete only with myself|work=The New Indian Express|location=India|date=9 June 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> In a departure from convention, the lyrics were penned first which were set to tunes later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.Behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/apr-12-01/billa-2-thala-ajith-02-04-12.html|title=Billa 2 Is Full of Thrills|publisher=Behindwoods|date=2 April 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe audio launch was initially to be released in mid-March 2012, but was then pushed to second week of April. Actor [[Rajinikanth]] was approached to unveil the soundtrack, with the team supposedly rescheduling the audio launch to suit Rajinikanth's dates, who had left for London for the filming of his film ''[[Kochadaiyaan]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-19/news-interviews/31210077_1_billa-ajith-rajini|title=Will Rajini attend Billa 2 audio launch?|work=The Times of India|date=19 March 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/79668.html|title=Rajini to unveil Ajith's 'Billa 2' music?|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> The soundtrack was unveiled on 1 May 2012, coinciding with [[Ajith Kumar]]'s birthday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-audio-on-ajiths-birthday-news-tamil-metlCHjcabj.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 audio, on Ajith's birthday?|publisher=Sify.com|date=19 April 2012|accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref> [[Sony Music Entertainment]] that marketed the [[Mankatha (soundtrack)|album]] of Ajith Kumar's previous film ''[[Mankatha]]'', acquired the music rights of ''Billa II'' as well for an unprecedented sum after some weeks-long negotiations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/sony-music-snaps-billa-2-audio-news-tamil-mdglVqbcgaf.html?ref=false|title=Sony Music snaps Billa 2 audio|publisher=Sify|date=6 March 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> In the week before the audio launch, Sony Music began releasing teasers of each of the songs every day and promoted them across social platforms.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-25/news-interviews/31398664_1_billa-ajith-s-birthday-new-song|title=Billa 2 audio online! \u2013 Times of India|publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com|date=|accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioandmusic.com/content/editorial/news/sony-music-goes-viral-promote-tamil-movie-billa-2-songs|title=Sony Music goes viral to promote Tamil movie 'Billa 2' songs &#124; Editorial-News|publisher=Radioandmusic.com|date=14 January 2010|accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref> The Telugu version of the soundtrack was released on 5 June 2012 at the Taj Deccan in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/article/82681.html|title=David Billa audio released|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=5 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> The soundtrack received positive response from critics<ref>{{cite web|title=BILLA 2 MUSIC REVIEW|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-music-reviews/review-1/may-12-01/billa-2-music-review.html|accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Review: Billa 2 music is quite promising|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/review/south-review-billa-2-music-is-quite-promising/20120504.htm|accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref> and topped the charts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Billa 2 music sets charts on fire|url=http://www.123telugu.com/mnews/billa-2-music-sets-charts-on-fire.html|accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ajith Billa 2 Movie Grand Release in USA|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-08/news-interviews/32588285_1_grand-release-screens-makers|work=Times of India|accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Billa 2 trailer to hit online today|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jul-12-01/billa-2-ajith-02-07-12.html|accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\n''Billa II'' underwent an extensive marketing spree before its release.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article3364380.ece|title=The don of summer|author=Nikhil Raghavan|date=28 April 2012|accessdate=14 July 2012|work=The Hindu|location=Chennai, India}}</ref> A first [[teaser poster]] displaying the new logo design was published in [[Diwali]] 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/ajith-s-billa-2-logo-design-unveiled-news-tamil-lk5nb5ibbif.html?ref=false|title=Ajith's Billa 2 logo design unveiled|publisher=Sify|date=1 November 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> while the first posters depicting Ajith Kumar's look were released in January 2012 during the [[Pongal (festival)|Pongal]] festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-first-look-unveiled-news-tamil-mbpolSijdej.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 first look unveiled|publisher=Sify|date=16 January 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> From late February onwards, further posters featuring Ajith were unveiled,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/ajith-s-billa-2-latest-update-news-tamil-mc3jo1cgafh.html|title=Ajith's Billa- 2 latest update|publisher=Sify|date=29 February 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> with one poster in late March portraying a young Ajith carrying a kerosene can on a boat that led to speculations over the character's origin.<ref>{{cite web|author=Anupama Subramanian|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/young-ajith%E2%80%99s-first-look-billa-2-552|title=Young Ajith's first look from Billa 2|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=28 March 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> On 13 April 2012, a one-minute [[teaser trailer]] was uploaded to YouTube.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-15/news-interviews/31344917_1_billa-ajith-teaser|title=Billa 2 teaser sets records|work=The Times of India|date=15 April 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> The teaser garnered over 500,000 views within the first three days of its release, setting a new record for Tamil films.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-teaser-creates-a-sensation-news-tamil-meqk60eebhf.html|title=Billa 2 teaser creates a sensation|publisher=Sify|date=16 April 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the marketing, the makers planned to release a ''Billa 2'' calendar featuring the two lead actresses, Parvathy Omanakuttan and Bruna Abdulla; the stills were shot exclusively for the calendar in Goa.<ref>{{cite news|author=Lata Srinivasan|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-22/miss-india/31379326_1_billa-audio-release-parvathy-omanakuttan|title=Parvathy Omanakuttan sizzles in Billa 2 calendar|work=The Times of India|date=22 April 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> An event to launch the official theatrical trailer was planned to be held on 2 July at the [[Anna Centenary Library]] auditorium in [[Kotturpuram]], Chennai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/ajith-s-billa-2-to-have-a-new-trailer-launch-news-tamil-mg3iopecfih.html?scategory=tamil|title=Ajith's 'Billa 2' to have a new trailer launch|publisher=Sify|date=29 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> The entire cast and crew along with Russian dancers were expected to attend the function, which was to be telecast on television later.<ref name=\"indiatimes3\">{{cite news|author=Lata Srinivasan|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-03/news-interviews/32509437_1_trailer-ajith-venue|title=Billa II trailer launch cancelled; fans upset|work=The Times of India|date=3 July 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> The event was cancelled at short notice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-trailer-launch-cancelled-news-tamil-mhcjXWidhdi.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 trailer launch cancelled|publisher=Sify|date=2 July 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> The trailer was however uploaded to YouTube the same day, gaining record views.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/billa-2-grand-trailer-launch-on-july-2/268433-71-180.html|title='Billa 2': Grand trailer launch on July 2|publisher=CNN-IBN|date=28 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-new-trailer-rocks-news-tamil-mhdku4gjejg.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 new trailer rocks!|publisher=Sify|date=3 July 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> Moreover, a promotional video featuring Ajith with composer Yuvan Shankar Raja was shot as well, but was not released either.<ref name=\"indiatimes3\"/>\n\n==Release==\nBilla 2 was released in 2500 theatres worldwide.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}} On first day Mayajaal Multiplex released Billa 2 in all screens and all shows \u2013 a total of 102 shows in 14 screens. \nThe overseas distribution rights were sold for 53&nbsp;million to the US-based company GK Media, the highest ever for an Ajith film.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> In March 2012, The [[Sun TV (India)|Sun TV]] bought the satellite rights for a record price,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/79307.html|title=Sun bags Ajith's 'Billa 2' satellite rights!|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> with sources estimating the price at {{INR}}6&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|author=Prakash|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/tamil/news/2012/billa-2-satellite-rights-130312.html|title=Billa 2 satellite rights sold for Rs 6.25 cr|publisher=Oneindia.in|date=13 March 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> Three prominent production houses were reportedly trying to purchase the domestical theatrical rights then.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-satellite-rights-sold-news-tamil-mdnro2fccdh.html|title=Billa 2 satellite rights sold|publisher=Sify|date=13 March 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> [[Venu Ravichandran]]'s [[Aascar Films]] eventually acquired the theatrical distribution rights of Tamil Nadu for {{INR}}260&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|author=22 April 2012 By Anupama Subramanian DC chennai|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/%E2%80%98billa-2-worth-shot%E2%80%99-877|title='Billa 2 is worst film ever in Ajith's career |work=Deccan Chronicle|date=22 April 2012|accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-records-rs-40-crore-sales-in-rights-news-tamil-meyjRKidiae.html|title=Billa 2 records Rs 3Crore sales in rights!|publisher=Sify.com|date=24 April 2012|accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref> All the distribution rights of the film, except the Kerala and Hindi dubbing rights had been sold at a record price of more than {{INR}}400&nbsp;million, making ''Billa II'' one of the top pre-release revenue generating films of all time in the Tamil film industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-ajith-starrer-billa-2-sold-for-record-price/20120424.htm|title=Ajith-starrer Billa 2 sold at record price \u2013 Rediff.com Movies|publisher=Rediff.com|date=24 April 2012|accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref> In early May 2012, the Kerala release rights were finally sold to Sagara Entertainment and Money Tree Entertainment for {{INR}}8million, likewise a new record for an Ajith film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-kerala-rights-sold-news-malayalam-mfdkE1fcaig.html?scategory=tamil|title=Billa 2- Kerala rights sold|publisher=Sify|date=3 March 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> ''Billa II'' received an adult rating (\"A\" certificate) from the [[Central Board of Film Certification]], due to its \"high glamour quotient, violence and the mature content\".<ref>{{cite web|title='Billa 2' gets 'A'! Release date & certificate rating to change?|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/82896.html|work=Indiaglitz|accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref> In the UK, the film was issued an [[15 (British Board of Film Classification)|15 certificate]] by the [[British Board of Film Classification]] with an advice that it contained \"very strong violence and revenge theme\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/AFF291235/|title=British Board of Film Classification|publisher=BBFC|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Billa II'' was initially planned to release on 13 April 2012, coinciding with [[Puthandu|Tamil New Year]], but the release was postponed to 1 May 2012, coinciding with Ajith Kumar's birthday,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/82273.html|title='Billa 2' likely to release on july 8|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=18 May 2012}}</ref> with the makers considering to bring forward the film by four days to release it on a Friday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/billa-iis-title-song-to-be-released-this-week/235197-8-68.html|title=Ajith's Billa II's title song to be released in March 2012|work= CNN-IBN|date=|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> However, the release became further delayed and was pushed to the second half of May 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-release-postponed-further-news-kollywood-mdkj7kfbedg.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 release postponed further|publisher=Sify|date=10 March 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/79179.html|title='Billa 2' sees a delay in release?|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> After considering the first four Fridays in June 2012 for the film's release,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-re-recording-in-mumbai-news-tamil-mfvrmEjheeb.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 re-recording in Mumbai?|publisher=Sify|date=21 March 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/ajith-s-billa-2-on-june-8-news-tamil-mfsh7Kgebfa.html?ref=false|title=Ajith's 'Billa- 2' on June 8?|publisher=Sify|date=18 March 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/the-biggies-are-coming-news-tamil-mgcmabddfjd.html?ref=false|title=The Biggies are coming!|publisher=Sify|date=2 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jun-12-03/billa-2-chakri-toleti-20-06-12.html|title=Billa 2 has unexpected twists: Chakri Toleti|publisher=behindwoods|date=20 June 2012|accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> the producer finally zeroed in on 13 July as the release date.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-26/news-interviews/32424299_1_wide-angle-creations-billa-aascar-films|title= Billa 2 from July 13|date=26 June 2012 | work=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n''Billa 2'' was released across over 1,400 screens worldwide, making it one of the largest Tamil releases ever.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\"/> The film was released simultaneously in the four southern states, Tamil Nadu, Karnataka, Andhra Pradesh and Kerala as well as in North India and international markets.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\"/> In Tamil Nadu, it opened across 550 theatres,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-confirmed-for-july-13-news-tamil-mgyqOzhdiid.html?scategory=tamil|title=Billa 2 confirmed for July 13|publisher=Sify|date=24 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> while a [[dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbed]] Telugu version of the film released in Andhra Pradesh as ''David Billa''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/article/80871.html|title=Ajith's Billa2 will be dubbed into Telugu|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> In Kerala, the Tamil version was screened and Karnataka saw the release of both the versions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/82857.html|title='Billa 2': Release plans|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=13 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> The film was also released by Aanna Films in most of the major multiplexes in France with French subtitles;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jun-12-01/billa-2-ajith-05-06-12.html|title=Billa 2 goes to France|publisher=Behindwoods|date=5 June 2012|accessdate=5 June 2012}}</ref> in Malaysia, North India and the Gulf Nations, [[Malay language|Malay]], [[Hindi]] and [[Arabic]] subtitles were added to the film, respectively, while in other international markets, it was screened with English subtitles.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-06/news-interviews/32078091_1_chakri-toleti-tinsel-town-subtitles|title=Billa 2 in multiple languages|work=Times of India|date=9 June 2012|accessdate=9 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Reception===\nKarthik Subramanian of ''[[The Hindu]]'' said, \"Where the movie lacks in substance, it does try to score with technical aspects. The camerawork by R. D. Rajasekhar, background score by Yuvan Shankar Raja and editing by [[Suresh Urs]] are superlative for the most part\", and that the film \"does live up to the hype\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Karthik Subramanian |url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article3639256.ece |title=Arts / Cinema : Does 'Billa II' beckon? |work=The Hindu |date=14 July 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> [[MSN|MSN India]] said \"''Billa 2'' would be an interesting film for ajith fans&watchable film for general audience\"<ref name=MSN>{{cite web |author=Ians |url=http://entertainment.in.msn.com/southcinema/reviews/review-billa-2 |title=Review: 'Billa 2' \u2013 Reviews |publisher=MSN India Entertainment |date=16 July 2012 |accessdate=15 May 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002190033/http://entertainment.in.msn.com/southcinema/reviews/review-billa-2 |archive-date=2 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nMeena Iyer of ''[[The Times of India]]'' recommended it with a 3 star rating, \"If you're {{sic|a|hide=yes}} Ajith fan\u2014''Billa 2'' is a must. If you're an action aficionado, it's a treat. If you're neither, then don't bother.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/tamil/movie-reviews/Billa-2/movie-review/14864866.cms |title=Billa 2 movie review: Wallpaper, Story, Trailer at Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date= |accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> Indiaglitz called it as a slick entertainer running for just 129 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/review/12833.html |title=Billa II Tamil Movie Review \u2013 cinema preview stills gallery trailer video clips showtimes |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date=13 July 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> Prathibha Parameswaran of [[IBN Live]] said, \"If you liked ''[[Billa 2007|Billa]]'' and ''[[Mankatha]]'', and expected as much from the prequel, it falls well short of expectations.\" and further wrote, \"watch it only for Thala.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/review-watch-sluggish-billa-2-only-for-ajith/271114-71-178.html |title=Tamil Review: 'Billa 2' lacks pace, but watch it for Ajith if you must- Tamil Reviews- IBNLive |publisher=Ibnlive.in.com |date=13 July 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> Anupama Subramanian of [[Deccan Chronicle]] rated the film 3 out of 5 stars and said, \"The film works to a great extent because of the sheer screen presence of a star called Ajith Kumar. After all, it is his film all the way!\"<ref name=DECCAN>{{cite news|author=Anupama Subramanian |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/movie-reviews/billa-2-review-no-message-behind-violence-749 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120726114209/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/movie-reviews/billa-2-review-no-message-behind-violence-749 |archivedate=26 July 2012 |title=Billa 2 review: No message behind the violence |work=Deccan Chronicle |date=15 July 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n\n====India====\nIn the domestic market, ''Billa II'' had a great opening with 95% occupancy in single screens and multiplexes. In the opening week, it grossed around {{INR}}4.79 crore at the Chennai box office and after 5 weeks, it amounted to {{INR}}7.79 crore after tax deduction. It grossed around 41 crore at Tamil Nadu, 2.4 crore at kerala, 2.1 crore at karnataka, 2 crore at andra and  1 crore at rest of India.<ref name=\"OPEN\">{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/ajith-kumars-billa-2/1/208645.html |title=Ajith Kumar's Billa 2 continues to get thumpdown response at box office : Bollywood, News \u2013 India Today |publisher=Indiatoday.intoday.in |date=17 July 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://behindwoods.com/tamil-movies/billa-2/billa-2-box-office-aug-12.html |title=Billa 2 box office collection |publisher=Behindwoods.com |date= |accessdate=15 May 2013}}</ref> The film did not get exemption from entertainment tax due to A certificate. It yielded {{INR}}7 crore or 10 per cent of the total entertainment tax revenue of the year for the exchequer.\n\n====Overseas====\nIn Malaysia, ''Billa II'' collected US$348,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/intl/malaysia/yearly/?yr=2012&p=.htm|title=2012 Malaysia Yearly Box Office Results|publisher=|accessdate=30 September 2016}}</ref> The film grossed $78,000 in the UK<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?page=&country=UK&wk=2012W29&id=_fBILLA201|title=Billa 2|publisher=|accessdate=30 September 2016}}</ref> and approximately $20,000 in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?page=&country=AU&wk=2012W29&id=_fBILLA201|title=Billa 2|publisher=|accessdate=30 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=1891755}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|id=billa_2|title=Billa II}}\n\n{{Don film series|state=expanded}}\n{{Chakri Toleti}}\n{{Salim-Javed}}\n\n[[Category:Indian gangster films]]\n[[Category:2012 films]]\n[[Category:2010s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime action films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s prequel films]]\n[[Category:Indian action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Puducherry]]\n[[Category:Films featuring an item number]]\n[[Category:Films about organised crime in India]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Goa]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Tbilisi]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Georgia (country)]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n[[Category:2010s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian crime action films]]\n[[Category:Indian crime thriller films]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Billa II The Beginning\n| image          = Billa II poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Chakri Toleti]]\n| producer       = Sunir Kheterpal<br />[[Suresh Balaje]]<br />George Pius\n| story          = Chakri Toleti<br />[[Eric Felberg]]<br />[[Sarath Mandava]]\n| screenplay     = Chakri Toleti<br />Sarath Mandava<br />Jaffer Mohammed\n| starring       = [[Ajith Kumar]]<br />[[Parvathy Omanakuttan]]<br />[[Bruna Abdullah]]<br />[[Vidyut Jammwal]]<br/>[[Rohit Khurana]]<br />[[Sudhanshu Pandey]]\n| music          = [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n| cinematography = [[R. D. Rajasekhar]]\n| editing        = [[Suresh Urs]]\n| studio         = Wide Angle Creations<br />[[Hinduja Group|IN Entertainment]]\n| distributor    = [[Aascar Films]] <small>(India)</small><br />GK Media <small>(USA)</small>\n| released       = {{Film date|2012|07|13|df=y}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/83166.html|title='Billa 2' from July 13| work=Indiaglitz| date=25 June 2012| accessdate=4 July 2012 }}</ref>\n| runtime        = 127 minutes<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/billa-2-2012|title=BILLA 2 &#124; British Board of Film Classification|website=bbfc.co.uk}}</ref>\n| language       = Tamil\n| country        = India\n| budget         = {{INR}}35 crore<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-articles/45-for-Enthiran-17-for-Billa-2-18-07-12.html|title=Billa 2 Ajith's costliest|publisher=Behindwoods.com|accessdate=25 April 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218085838/http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movies-cinema-articles/45-for-Enthiran-17-for-Billa-2-18-07-12.html|archivedate=18 February 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| gross          = <!--Must be attributed to a reliable published source with an established reputation for fact-checking. No blogs, no IMDb.-->\n}}\n\n'''''Billa II: The Beginning''''' is a 2012 Indian [[Tamil language|Tamil]]-language [[action thriller film]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bbfc.co.uk/releases/billa-2|title=BILLA 2 &#124; British Board of Film Classification|website=bbfc.co.uk}}</ref> directed by [[Chakri Toleti]]. It is a [[Prequel]] to ''[[Billa (2007 film)|Billa]]'' and focuses on how David, an ordinary man from the coastal regions of Sri Lanka, becomes Billa, a dreaded underworld don, with [[Ajith Kumar]] reprising the role of the titular character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/66818.html|title=Billa 2's plot revealed|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=28 January 2012}}</ref> [[Parvathy Omanakuttan]], [[Bruna Abdullah]], [[Vidyut Jammwal]] and [[Sudhanshu Pandey]] appear in supporting roles, all of them marking their debut in Tamil cinema. The film's soundtrack and background score were composed by [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]], while [[R. D. Rajasekhar]] handled the cinematography and [[Suresh Urs]] worked as the editor.\n\nThe film, produced by Wide Angle Creations in association with the [[Hinduja Group]] company IN Entertainment, was officially announced in November 2010, with [[Vishnuvardhan (director)|Vishnuvardhan]] as the director. Due to schedule clashes, Vishnuvardhan was replaced by Chakri Toleti, with a new script having been penned by a team involving Toleti, Sarath Mandava and Eric Felberg.\n\nPrincipal photography happened between July 2011 and December 2011. The filming primarily took place at [[Tamil Nadu]], Goa, [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]] and in [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]. ''Billa II'' was released worldwide on 13 July 2012 and a dubbed Telugu version titled ''David Billa'' was also simultaneously released in [[Andhra Pradesh]] and [[Telangana]] (then both states were combined under Andhra Pradesh state).<ref name=\"autogenerated3\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-to-release-wide-in-foreign-languages-news-tamil-mg0jN1dcgjg.html?scategory=tamil|title=Billa 2 to release wide in foreign languages!|publisher=Sify|date=26 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> The film garnered mixed reviews on release, though it collected decently at the box office because of the hype that created during pre-release. Eventually the film turned out to be one of the cults in Tamil films for its making and stylish presentation of protogonist.\n\n==Plot==\nDavid Billa ([[Ajith Kumar]]), an Sri Lankan refugee along with several others, arrives to the camp in [[Rameswaram]] where he befriends Ranjith ([[Yog Japee]]). The refugee camp is constantly terrorised by corrupt police officer Raghubir Sinha ([[Krishna Kumar (actor)|Krishna Kumar]]). Billa attacks Raghubir when he tries to forcefully detain one of his friends and for revenge he gets Billa tortured in police cell and vows to make him suffer. A few days later, Billa and Ranjith are hired to transport fish from Rameswaram to Chennai. But unknown to them, it was a plot by Raghubir to trap them as the truck they were driving had diamonds inside. But Billa realises the ploy and kills all the cops and drive the truck to its destination where they meet Selvaraj ([[Ilavarasu]]), who is pleased by Billa's loyalty and includes him in his business. Billa murders Raghubir at a [[brothel]].\n\nKotiswara Rao ([[Manoj K. Jayan]]) visits Selvaraj and asks him if he could help in selling off the heroin he had brought along with him. Billa volunteers to sell it off and tries to deal the heroin to a local thug who refuses to pay for it in return. In a brutal scuffle that ensues where one of Billa's friends is slaughtered, Billa kills them all and goes directly to Koti's boss Abbasi ([[Sudhanshu Pandey]]) with the money and the heroin, who is very impressed by the former and recruits him. Abbasi is in business with Barovian mafia led by Dimitri ([[Vidyut Jammwal]]), who tells him that his arms consignment has been held by the Indian coastal guard and he asks for his help. Billa and Ranjith agree to retrieve the consignment for him and are congratulated by Dimitri for their work.\n\nBilla climbs the ladder of Abbasi's gang quickly. Later he learns of his sister death and brings his niece Jasmine ([[Parvathy Omanakuttan]]) with him. Billa and Koti travel to Russia to meet Dimitri, who happens to own an arms and ammunition manufacturing unit. Billa signs a deal with Dimitri without Abbasi's knowledge who learns this from Koti and is furious at Billa. Tensions further increase when Billa beats up Satish Kumar ([[Rohit Khurana]]), the son of an influential minister Praveen Kumar ([[Dinesh Lamba]]), when he tries to misbehave with Jasmine in a party. Abbasi expresses his discontent and vents at him. Billa, surprised and enraged at his ingratitude, walks away with Ranjith. Billa, Ranjith, and Ram (Sarath Mandava) plot to venture into the drug business on their own during the carnival. At the carnival, Billa is betrayed by Ram and is brutally attacked. However, he survives and finishes off the assailants, kills Abbasi and Ram, and becomes Goa's most powerful gangster. He begins a relationship with Abbasi's girlfriend Sameera ([[Bruna Abdullah]]).\n\nDimitri arrives to Goa and has a fallout with Billa when they try to negotiate a deal with Billa. So, Dimitri seeks to oust him. Dimitri seeks out the help of Koti, Satish, and Praveen to eliminate David. They proceed to kill Chief Minister Mohan Kanth ([[Madhusudhan Rao (actor)|Madhusudhan Rao]]), and the blame falls upon Billa. However, Billa is freed by threatening the judge and his family. After coming out, Billa rescues his niece from Koti's men and informs Sameera to take Jasmine to safety. But Sameera betrays Billa, informs the minister's son who hold Billa and Jasmine captives. Billa while being held to the ground and is mocked at by Satish, who slits Jasmine's throat. Enraged at her death, Billa overpowers and kills everyone.\n\nMeanwhile, in Russia, Dimitri is having an auction of his weapons, and Koti is present with him. He shows his factory in his computer via a series of webcams and much to everyone's shock, Billa is seen destroying his factory in Georgia. He also sees his consignment train go off course. He gets angered and kills Koti for not killing Billa, and he sets out himself to finish the task. The arms factory is destroyed by Billa and his friends. Dimitri arrives and follows his delivery train, when to his shock, the delivery train is blown by Billa, who would be waiting for him on his own helicopter. After an intense battle, Billa kills Dimitri. In the epilogue, Billa and Ranjith board a plane out of the country, and the loose threads (Sameera, Police and Lawyer) are eliminated by Billa's men.\n\n==Cast==\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Ajith Kumar]] as David Billa\n* [[Parvathy Omanakuttan]] as Jasmine\n* [[Bruna Abdullah]] as Sameera\n* [[Sudhanshu Pandey]] as Abbasi\n* [[Vidyut Jammwal]] as Russian Arms dealer Dimitri\n* [[Yog Japee]] as Ranjith\n* [[Manoj K. Jayan]] as Kotiswara Rao\n* [[Ilavarasu]] as Selvaraj\n* [[Sricharan (actor)|Sricharan]] as Bobby\n* [[Krishna Kumar (actor)|Krishna Kumar]] as Raghubir Sinha\n* [[Sriman (actor)|Sriman]] as Billa's Lawyer\n* [[Madhusudhan Rao (actor)|Madhusudhan Rao]] as Goa Chief Minister Mohan Kanth\n* [[Janaki Sabesh]] as David Billa's sister\n* Byron Gibson as Russian Mafia Boss\n* [[Rohit Khurana]] as Satish Kumar\n* [[Dinesh Lamba]] as Praveen Kumar\n* Ron Smoorenburg as Russian Martial Artist\n* Balaji shathivel as Billa 's henchmen\n* Sarath Mandava as Ram\n* Theepatti Ganesh as Muthu\n* Ashok Bentwal\n* [[Rahman (actor)|Rahman]] as Jagdish (quick cameo, reprising role from Billa 1)\n* [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]] as special appearance \n* [[Meenakshi Dixit]] special appearance in item number \"Madurai Ponnu\"\n* Nicole Amy Madell special appearance in item number \"Yedho Mayakkam\" and \"Gangster\" \n* [[Gabriela Bertante]] special appearance in item number \"Yedho Mayakkam\"\n* [[Ashok Selvan]] as young Billa in photograph (uncredited role)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/tamil/movies/did-you-know-/Ashok-Selvans-picture-was-featured-in-Billa-2/articleshow/46986564.cms|title=Ashok Selvan's picture was featured in Billa 2 - Times of India|publisher=|accessdate=30 September 2016}}</ref>\n{{colend}}\n\n==Production==\n\n===Development===\nIn 2008, reports claimed that [[Soundarya Rajinikanth]] was planning to make a follow-up after noting ''[[Billa (2007 film)|Billa]]''{{'}}s commercial success, to be produced by [[Ocher Studios]] in association with [[Warner Bros.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/may-08-01/billa-07-05-08.html|title=Will Ajith do Billa \u2013 2 ?|publisher=Behindwoods|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/tamil/exclusive/2008/soundarya-rajinikanth-billa-2-190508.html|title=Soundarya Rajini confirms Billa-2|publisher=Oneindia.in|date=19 May 2008|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> However, the sequel did not materialise and the idea was dropped, with Ajith Kumar, Vishnuvardhan and Soundarya getting busy with other projects.\n\nIn 2010, sources confirmed that Vishnuvardhan had finished penning the script for a prequel, which would star Ajith Kumar as the titular character again,<ref>{{cite web|title=BREAKING NEWS: AJITH'S BILLA 2|publisher=Behindwoods|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jul-10-05/ajith-vishnuvardhan-billa-28-07-10.html|year=|accessdate=28 July 2010}}</ref> and would commence in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|author=Moviebuzz|title=Vishnuvardhan to make Billa prequel!|publisher=Sify|url=http://sify.com/movies/tamil/fullstory.php?id=14951341|year=2010|accessdate=29 July 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100801210130/http://sify.com/movies/tamil/fullstory.php?id=14951341|archive-date=1 August 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> The project became officially announced in late 2010, after Ajith Kumar signed up to the prequel and first production poster were published to the media.<ref name=\"Billa2sify11\">{{cite web|title=It's official: Ajith signs 'Billa II'|publisher=IndiaGlitz|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/61364.html|year=2010|accessdate=4 November 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Billa2sify\">{{cite web|author=Moviebuzz|title=Breaking News- Billa 2 confirmed|publisher=Sify|url=http://sify.com/movies/breaking-news-billa-2-confirmed-news-tamil-klel6kcbgfc.html|year=2010|accessdate=4 November 2010}}</ref> Further details were disclosed, with [[Suresh Balaje]], son of producer and actor K. Balaji, who produced the original ''Billa'' with Rajinikanth, and George Pius from Wide Angle Creations banner, being confirmed as the producer,<ref name=\"Billa2sify11\"/> who would associate with Mumbai-based IN Entertainment Limited, a [[Hinduja Group|Hinduja group company]].<ref name=\"Billa2sify\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiainfoline.com/Markets/News/IN-Entertainment-ties-up-with-Wide-Angle-Creations/5071125059|title=IN Entertainment ties up with Wide Angle Creations|publisher=Indiainfoline.com|date=1 February 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> The entire production team of the ''Billa'' remake, including cinematographer [[Nirav Shah]], editor [[A. Sreekar Prasad]] and music director [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]], were announced to be retained for the sequel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-02-02/news-interviews/28372663_1_vishnu-telugu-film-heroine|title=Vishnuvardhan's double dhamaka|work=The Times of India|date=2 February 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn a turn of events, [[Vishnuvardhan (director)|Vishnuvardhan]] opted out of the project citing that his dates clashed with the making of his Telugu film, ''[[Panjaa]]'' (earlier titled as ''The Shadow'').<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-02-18/news-interviews/28614918_1_director-vishnuvardhan-venkat-prabhu-directed-mankatha-film|title=Vishnu cancels billa date|work=The Times of India|date= 18 February 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> [[Chakri Toleti]] who directed the 2009 [[Kamal Haasan]]-[[Mohanlal]] starrer ''[[Unnaipol Oruvan (2009 film)|Unnaipol Oruvan]]'' was subsequently signed on by the producers to direct the venture.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-02-22/news-interviews/28624795_1_ajith-billa-thala|title=Ajith gets new script, director for Billa 2|work=The Times of India|date=22 February 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> In May 2011, Chakri Toleti held his first press conference stating that production would begin in late June 2011 and revealing that \"''Billa 2'' would focus on how David, an ordinary man from the coastal [[Thoothukudi]] in South Tamil Nadu, becomes Billa, a dreaded underworld don\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-to-start-by-june-end-news-kollywood-lfsoQhdhgia.html|title=Billa 2 to start by June end|publisher=Sify|date=18 May 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> David's character was afterwards widely reported to be either a refugee from [[Tamil Eelam]] or a Tamilian from [[Sri Lanka]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/70525.html|title=How does Ajith become a don in 'Billa 2'?|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/ajith-not-a-sri-lankan-refugee-in-billa-ii/239098-62-128.html|title='Billa II': Ajith not playing Sri Lankan refugee|work= [[CNN-IBN]]|date=|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> Both the director and the producer refused to confirm the statements, disclosing only that the film would depict David's journey over a period of five years.<ref name=\"articles.timesofindia.indiatimes\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-13/news-interviews/31158865_1_billa-thala-ajith-death-defying-stunts|title=Death-defying stunts, Ajith style!|work=The Times of India|date=13 March 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nWith Vishnuvardhan's exit from the project, his script was also scrapped, and Toleti along with Ajith Kumar began penning a new script for the prequel.<ref name=\"indiatimes1\"/> Yuvan Shankar Raja only was retained from the original production team,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/64393.html|title='Billa 2': Yuvan on board|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> with the rest of the technical crew being finalised in the following weeks.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-03-02/news-interviews/28646721_1_mankatha-ajith-billa|title=Ajith bonding with Yuvan|work=The Times of India|date=2 March 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> [[Hemant Chaturvedi]], who hitherto had worked in [[Bollywood]] productions only, was signed on to replace [[Nirav Shah]] as the cinematographer after the latter's schedules clashed with the making of his other film, ''[[Vettai]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/hemant-chaturvedi-is-billa-2-cameraman-news-tamil-lehlhliadcd.html|title=Hemant Chaturvedi is Billa 2, cameraman|publisher=Sify|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> However, in July 2011, Hemant Chaturvedi too moved out of the project, fearing that the delay in commencement of ''Billa 2'' may hurt his chances in Bollywood, and [[R. D. Rajasekhar]] was appointed as the new cinematographer.<ref>{{cite web|title=Who moved out of Billa 2 now?|publisher=Behindwoods|accessdate=8 July 2011|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jul-11-02/ajith-billa-2-08-07-11.html}}</ref> V. Selvakumar who had notably worked in ''[[Madrasapattinam]]'' was selected as the art director.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/68543.html|title='Billa 2' starts rolling|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> The crew also announced that the film would become the first Indian production to be filmed with an [[Red Digital Cinema Camera Company|RED EPIC Camera]], being shot at 5K resolution.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jul-11-01/billa-2-ajith-05-07-11.html|title=Billa-2 and the James Cameron Connection|publisher=Behindwoods|date=5 July 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> Writer Ee. Raa. Murugan, who had previously collaborated with Chakri Toleti in the [[Kamal Hassan]]-starrer ''Unnaipol Oruvan'', was appointed to write the dialogue.\n\n===Casting===\nFrom the previous film, the producers made it clear that apart from [[Ajith Kumar]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/66737.html|title=Ajith's new look in 'Billa 2'|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> and [[Rahman (actor)|Rahman]], most of the other characters would not be retained. The female lead role was expected to be handed to [[Anushka Shetty]], but despite media speculation she was not signed on.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/will-anushka-sign-billa-2-opposite-ajit-news-tamil-lb1ufQdjjhj.html|title=Will Anushka sign Billa-2 opposite Ajit?|publisher=Sify|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/most-wanted-anushka-news-tamil-lcmlAiabeah.html|title=Most Wanted- Anushka|publisher=Sify|date=12 February 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> The female lead role was handed to debutant [[Huma Qureshi (actress)|Huma Qureshi]], a Mumbai-based theatre actor who had previously been featured in commercials, with Toleti finalising Qureshi after a nationwide search for an actress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/Huma-Qureshi-opposite-Ajit-in-Billa-2/785737/|title=Huma Qureshi opposite Ajit in Billa 2|work=The Indian Express |accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/south-first-look-ajiths-new-heroine/20110412.htm|title=Meet Ajith's new heroine|publisher=Rediff|date=12 April 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/65678.html|title=Billa 2 to bring on fresh beauty|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> However, she was removed from the project by September 2011, due to date clashes,<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-09-10/news-interviews/30138845_1_billa-ajith-50th-film|work=The Times of India | title=Huma Qureshi out of Billa 2?| date=10 September 2011}}</ref> and became replaced by [[Miss India World]] 2008 [[Parvathy Omanakuttan]] later that month,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.moviecrow.com/News/97/parvathy-omnakuttan-to-pair-with-ajith|title=Parvathy Omnakuttan to pair with Ajith|publisher=|accessdate=30 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/parvathy-is-ajiths-heroine-in-billa-2-news-tamil-lj3j5degaba.html|title=Parvathy is Ajiths heroine in Billa-2|publisher=Sify|date=29 September 2011|accessdate=29 September 2011}}</ref> who the director had spotted and offered the role of Jasmine at a fashion show.<ref>{{cite news|author=Jiji Ann Cherian|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/tabloid/kochi/bowled-over-billa-935|title=Bowled over by Billa|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=6 April 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> Parvathy described her character as a \"simple girl who transforms into a modern person\" and that Billa looks up to, adding that she was had more scenes in the \"emotional part\" of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/view/regional/158051?device=iphone|title=Parvathy Omanakuttan signs Billa 2|work = [[NDTV]]|date=15 December 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> Bollywood actress and model [[Bruna Abdullah]] was selected to portray another significant character,<ref name=\"Rediff\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/miss-world-runner-up-in-billa-two/20111018.htm|title=Miss World runner-up in Billa 2|publisher=Rediff|date=18 October 2011|accessdate=17 December 2011}}</ref> which she went on term as \"super powerful, very strong and sexy\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-12-21/news-interviews/30542105_1_billa-ajith-chakri-toleti|title=I'm here to stay: Bruna Abdullah|work=The Times of India|date=21 December 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> Besides models Abdullah, and Parvathy Omanakuttan, [[Meenakshi Dixit]] was recruited for the item number \"Madurai Ponnu\". Another three models including, [[Gabriela Bertante]], [[Nicole Amy Madell]], and an unknown artist, was recruited to perform a dance number \"Yedho Mayakkam\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-08/news-interviews/31305238_1_billa-ajith-chakri-toleti|title=Brazilian model for Ajith|work=The Times of India|date=8 April 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-17/news-interviews/32269934_1_ajith-dancing-tamil-film|title=Billa II's Oomph factor!|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=17 June 2012|accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nTelevision actor [[Krishna Kumar (actor)|Krishna Kumar]], was signed on to play a \"dirty cop\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-09/news-interviews/29397248_1_malayalam-film-kk-three-films|title=Krishnakumar is a happy man|work=The Times of India|date= 9 April 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> In June 2011, [[Sudhanshu Pandey]], a former model who has appeared in several Hindi films, was given the role of a \"greying ganglord\", who becomes the mentor to the young David,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/sudhanshu-pandey-plays-a-baddie-in-billa-2/885449/0|title=Sudhanshu Pandey plays a baddie in Billa 2|work=The Indian Express|date=9 December 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> whilst Malayalam character actor [[Manoj K. Jayan]] was roped in for a \"key role\".<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/ajiths-7-million-billa-2-starts-rolling-news-tamil-lhorF9ecfia.html|title=Ajith's $7 million Billa 2 starts rolling|publisher=Sify.com|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> Actress [[Vimala Raman]] was signed on to make a special appearance in the film,<ref>{{cite web|author= Anupama Subramanian|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/vimala-raman-enters-bollywood-078|title=Vimala Raman enters Bollywood|work=Deccan Chronicle |date=2 July 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/66818.html|title='Billa 2's plot revealed|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> however she opted out in July 2011 citing date problems.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-07-13/news-interviews/29768327_1_billa-tamil-film-vimala-raman|title=Vimala says no to Billa 2|work=The Times of India|date=13 July 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> [[Meenakshi Dixit]] was later finalised for that role and shot her scenes in July 2011 during the first schedule.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-11-16/news-interviews/30410671_1_billa-girl-flick|work=The Times of India | title=Meenaxi Dixit: Item girl for Billa 2| date=16 November 2011}}</ref> [[Vidyut Jamwal]], who played negative roles in the Hindi film ''[[Force (2011 film)|Force]]'' (2011) and the Telugu film ''[[Oosaravelli]]'' (2011), was selected to play the villain, also making his debut in Tamil cinema.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-11-14/news-interviews/30402013_1_billa-ajith-martial-arts|work=The Times of India | title=Vidyut takes on Ajith| date=14 November 2011}}</ref> In December 2011 sources revealed that [[Sricharan (actor)|Sricharan]], who starred in ''[[Payanam (2011 film)|Payanam]]'', was shooting for a supporting role in the film.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-12-03/news-interviews/30471298_1_sricharan-tehran-flight|title=Sricharan's dramatic airport experience|work=The Times of India |date=3 December 2011|accessdate=18 December 2011}}</ref> Reports in February 2012 suggested that the team was trying to sign [[Nayantara]], who played the female lead in ''Billa'', for a [[cameo role]];<ref>{{cite web|author=Anupama Subramanian|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/nayanthara-%E2%80%99s-cameo-billa-2-006|title=Nayanthara 's cameo in Billa 2|work=Deccan Chronicle |date=26 February 2012|accessdate=11 March 2012}}</ref> the actress refuted the rumours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/feb-12-04/ajith-nayan-27-02-12.html|title=Nayanthara Denies Ajith Rumors|publisher=Behindwoods|date=27 February 2012|accessdate=11 March 2012}}</ref> Furthermore, composer [[Yuvan Shankar Raja]] on Toleti's insistence agreed to make a brief appearance in one of the songs.<ref>{{cite news|author=Janani Karthik|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/yuvan-dances-billa-2-050|title=Yuvan dances in Billa 2|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=16 April 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> Sources also reported that director [[Sebastian Seeman|Seeman]] would be acting in the film.{{citation needed|date=July 2012}}\n\n===Filming===\nThe film's production was delayed as Ajith Kumar's previous film, ''[[Mankatha]]'', progressed beyond the anticipated completion dates. In March 2011, the producers released a press note that the film would begin in early May 2011, however this failed to happen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-press-release-news-tamil-ldbjoSbaije.html|title=Billa 2 \u2013 Press Release|publisher=Sify|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> During that period, it was also suggested that ''Billa II'' may not be Ajith Kumar's successive project and commence only after the actor completed a film with [[M. Raja]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-04-20/news-interviews/29459707_1_billa-50th-film-mankatha-thala|title=Billa 2 isn't Ajith's 51sth film!|work=The Times of India|date=20 April 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> Eventually, a photo shoot was held in June 2011 with Ajith sporting an appearance of a man in his mid-twenties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jun-11-04/ajith-billa-2-24-06-11.html|title=Ajith's Look in Billa 2!|publisher=Behindwoods|date=24 June 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> [[Principal photography]] commenced on 14 July 2011 at the [[Ramoji Film City]] in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> Filming during the first 30-day schedule throughout July and August 2011 was held in Hyderabad and [[Visakhapatnam|Vizag]].<ref name=\"Rediff\"/> As part of the schedule, one song was shot in [[Puducherry]] under the direction of choreographer [[Raju Sundaram]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Prakash K. L.|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/tamil/news/2011/ajith-shoots-foot-tapping-billa-300811.html|title=Ajith shoots foot-tapping number for Billa|publisher=Oneindia.in|date=30 August 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> Both actresses Parvathy Omanakuttan and Bruna Abdullah joined the crew for the second schedule in [[Goa]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/70435.html|title=Ajith's 'Billa 2' status quo|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> that lasted for 39 days and ended in the first week of November.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/meet-the-villian-of-ajiths-billa-two/20111117.htm|title=Meet the {{sic|villian|nolink=y}} of Ajith's Billa 2|publisher=Rediff|date=17 November 2011|accessdate=17 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the third week of November, a unit of thirty-six members left for [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] in Eastern Europe for the final 20-day schedule of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-goa-schedule-complete-news-tamil-llfkmHceidd.html|title=Billa 2, Goa schedule complete|publisher=[[Sify]]|date=6 November 2011|accessdate=17 December 2011}}</ref> In Georgia, the crew filmed at the country's capital, [[Tbilisi]], [[Borjomi]] and [[Rustavi]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-12-19/news-interviews/30533751_1_shot-shooting-songs|work=The Times of India | title=K-Town goes to Europe| date=19 December 2011}}</ref> ''Billa II'' became the first Indian film to be shot at the [[Likani|Likani Palace]], which functions as a summer residence of the [[President of Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/snowfall-play-games-on-the-sets-of-billa-2-news-tamil-mf4of4bhjaj.html?ref=false|title=Snowfall play games on the sets of Billa-2|publisher=Sify|date=30 May 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> Midway through the filming, heavy snowfall began. The crew, however, carried on shooting and later reshot the complete sequence with the snowy background to maintain the continuity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/may-12-05/billa-2-ajith-30-05-12.html|title=Billa 2 Was Shot at Likani Palace|publisher=Behindwoods|date=30 May 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> The climax portions were also filmed there against a snowy backdrop, for which [[aerial shot]]s were done from a helicopter.<ref>{{cite news|author=Janani Karthik|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/billa-2-done-967|title=Billa 2 is done!|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=19 December 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> Approximately half a million dollars were spent for the whole schedule in Georgia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.investingeorgia.org/?107/1732/|title=Billa-2 First \"Bollywood\" movie is shot in Georgia|publisher=Invest in Georgia|date=|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> which was finished by mid-December.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/dec-11-03/ajith-billa-2-20-12-11.html|title=Billa 2 wrapped up|publisher=Behindwoods|accessdate=20 December 2011}}</ref> In February 2012, the remaining scenes, including the film's title song,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-02-18/news-interviews/31074689_1_billa-chakri-toleti-51st-film|title=Billa 2 title song finally shot!|work=The Times of India|date=18 February 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-title-song-picturised-news-tamil-mctmocicbae.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 title song picturised|publisher=Sify|date=19 February 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> were canned at the [[Ramoji Film City]] in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]],<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-makes-brisk-progress-news-tamil-mcqlVwagfeb.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 makes brisk progress|publisher=Sify|date=16 February 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> despite the ongoing strike in the film industry.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-02-16/news-interviews/31066307_1_billa-chakri-toleti-strike|title=Billa 2 shoot despite strike|work=The Times of India|date=16 February 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> An [[item number]] \"Yedo Mayakkam\" featuring three models was shot in a studio in Goa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/80649.html|title=Ajith to shake a leg with Gabriela Bertante!|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=9 April 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> Although producer Kheterpal had named [[Bangkok]], Thailand as a potential location for filming,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.filmbiz.asia/news/billa-2-is-big-budget-bet-for-tamil-films|title=Billa 2 is big budget bet for Tamil films| publisher=Filmbiz.asia|date=14 July 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> shooting was not held there. The entire filming was completed over a period of 90 days.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/billa-2-done-967|work=Deccan Chronicle|accessdate=20 December 2011|title=Billa 2 is done!}}</ref>\n\nThree stunt choreographers were involved in the making of ''Billa II''. The stunt sequences in Georgia were partly choreographed by an award-winning German-based company led by stuntman Stefan Richter,<ref name=\"articles.timesofindia.indiatimes\" /><ref>{{cite news|author=K. R. Manigandan|url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article3303485.ece|title=Shot Cuts|work=The Hindu|date=11 April 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012|location=Chennai, India}}</ref> while the climax action scenes were done by Kecha Khamphakdee's Jaika Stunt team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-stunt-master-praises-ajit-news-tamil-mesoqxgaeih.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 stunt master praises Ajit!|publisher=Sify.com|date=18 April 2012|accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"indiatimes2\">{{cite news|author=V Lakshmi|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-29/news-interviews/32458399_1_chakri-toleti-stunt-action-sequences|title=When Billa got into action!|work=The Times of India|date=29 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> K. Rajasekhar choreographed the fight sequences in Hyderabad and Goa.<ref name=\"indiatimes2\"/> Madhu Sudhanan, a [[VFX creative director]], said that [[visual effects|VFX]] had been used in action sequences, in \"set extensions\" and in sequences involving [[3-D film|3D]].<ref>{{cite news|author=K. Jeshi|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article3588625.ece|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130204072159/http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article3588625.ece|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 February 2013|title=Behind the Frames|work=The Hindu|date=30 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012|location=Chennai, India}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{main|Billa II (soundtrack)}}\n\n[[Yuvan Shankar Raja]], who had also worked on the score of ''[[Billa (2007 film)|Billa]]'' (2007), composed the soundtrack and score of ''Billa II'', becoming his fifth project starring [[Ajith Kumar]]. The album consists of six tracks, five songs and a [[theme music]] track.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/sony-music-snaps-billa-2-audio-news-tamil-mdglVqbcgaf.html|title=Sony Music snaps Billa 2 audio|publisher=Sify|date=6 March 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> The producer however confirmed that the film would feature a sixth song, not included in the soundtrack that was composed for a [[belly dance]] sequence.<ref>{{cite news|author=K. R. Manigandan|url=http://www.thehindu.com/life-and-style/metroplus/article3569004.ece|title=Shot Cuts: A weird friendship|work=The Hindu|date=25 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012|location=Chennai, India}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/83267.html|title=New song in 'Billa 2!'|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=28 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> [[Na. Muthukumar]] agreed to write the lyrics for the songs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://newindianexpress.com/entertainment/interviews/article432929.ece|title=I compete only with myself|work=The New Indian Express|location=India|date=9 June 2011|accessdate=16 September 2011}}</ref> In a departure from convention, the lyrics were penned first which were set to tunes later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.Behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/apr-12-01/billa-2-thala-ajith-02-04-12.html|title=Billa 2 Is Full of Thrills|publisher=Behindwoods|date=2 April 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe audio launch was initially to be released in mid-March 2012, but was then pushed to second week of April. Actor [[Rajinikanth]] was approached to unveil the soundtrack, with the team supposedly rescheduling the audio launch to suit Rajinikanth's dates, who had left for London for the filming of his film ''[[Kochadaiyaan]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-19/news-interviews/31210077_1_billa-ajith-rajini|title=Will Rajini attend Billa 2 audio launch?|work=The Times of India|date=19 March 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/79668.html|title=Rajini to unveil Ajith's 'Billa 2' music?|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> The soundtrack was unveiled on 1 May 2012, coinciding with [[Ajith Kumar]]'s birthday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-audio-on-ajiths-birthday-news-tamil-metlCHjcabj.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 audio, on Ajith's birthday?|publisher=Sify.com|date=19 April 2012|accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref> [[Sony Music Entertainment]] that marketed the [[Mankatha (soundtrack)|album]] of Ajith Kumar's previous film ''[[Mankatha]]'', acquired the music rights of ''Billa II'' as well for an unprecedented sum after some weeks-long negotiations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/sony-music-snaps-billa-2-audio-news-tamil-mdglVqbcgaf.html?ref=false|title=Sony Music snaps Billa 2 audio|publisher=Sify|date=6 March 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> In the week before the audio launch, Sony Music began releasing teasers of each of the songs every day and promoted them across social platforms.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-25/news-interviews/31398664_1_billa-ajith-s-birthday-new-song|title=Billa 2 audio online! \u2013 Times of India|publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com|date=|accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioandmusic.com/content/editorial/news/sony-music-goes-viral-promote-tamil-movie-billa-2-songs|title=Sony Music goes viral to promote Tamil movie 'Billa 2' songs &#124; Editorial-News|publisher=Radioandmusic.com|date=14 January 2010|accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref> The Telugu version of the soundtrack was released on 5 June 2012 at the Taj Deccan in [[Hyderabad, India|Hyderabad]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/article/82681.html|title=David Billa audio released|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=5 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> The soundtrack received positive response from critics<ref>{{cite web|title=BILLA 2 MUSIC REVIEW|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-music-reviews/review-1/may-12-01/billa-2-music-review.html|accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Review: Billa 2 music is quite promising|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/review/south-review-billa-2-music-is-quite-promising/20120504.htm|accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref> and topped the charts.<ref>{{cite web|title=Billa 2 music sets charts on fire|url=http://www.123telugu.com/mnews/billa-2-music-sets-charts-on-fire.html|accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ajith Billa 2 Movie Grand Release in USA|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-08/news-interviews/32588285_1_grand-release-screens-makers|work=Times of India|accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Billa 2 trailer to hit online today|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jul-12-01/billa-2-ajith-02-07-12.html|accessdate=11 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Marketing==\n''Billa II'' underwent an extensive marketing spree before its release.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article3364380.ece|title=The don of summer|author=Nikhil Raghavan|date=28 April 2012|accessdate=14 July 2012|work=The Hindu|location=Chennai, India}}</ref> A first [[teaser poster]] displaying the new logo design was published in [[Diwali]] 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/ajith-s-billa-2-logo-design-unveiled-news-tamil-lk5nb5ibbif.html?ref=false|title=Ajith's Billa 2 logo design unveiled|publisher=Sify|date=1 November 2011|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> while the first posters depicting Ajith Kumar's look were released in January 2012 during the [[Pongal (festival)|Pongal]] festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-first-look-unveiled-news-tamil-mbpolSijdej.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 first look unveiled|publisher=Sify|date=16 January 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> From late February onwards, further posters featuring Ajith were unveiled,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/ajith-s-billa-2-latest-update-news-tamil-mc3jo1cgafh.html|title=Ajith's Billa- 2 latest update|publisher=Sify|date=29 February 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> with one poster in late March portraying a young Ajith carrying a kerosene can on a boat that led to speculations over the character's origin.<ref>{{cite web|author=Anupama Subramanian|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/young-ajith%E2%80%99s-first-look-billa-2-552|title=Young Ajith's first look from Billa 2|work=Deccan Chronicle|date=28 March 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> On 13 April 2012, a one-minute [[teaser trailer]] was uploaded to YouTube.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-15/news-interviews/31344917_1_billa-ajith-teaser|title=Billa 2 teaser sets records|work=The Times of India|date=15 April 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> The teaser garnered over 500,000 views within the first three days of its release, setting a new record for Tamil films.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-teaser-creates-a-sensation-news-tamil-meqk60eebhf.html|title=Billa 2 teaser creates a sensation|publisher=Sify|date=16 April 2012|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nAs part of the marketing, the makers planned to release a ''Billa 2'' calendar featuring the two lead actresses, Parvathy Omanakuttan and Bruna Abdulla; the stills were shot exclusively for the calendar in Goa.<ref>{{cite news|author=Lata Srinivasan|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-04-22/miss-india/31379326_1_billa-audio-release-parvathy-omanakuttan|title=Parvathy Omanakuttan sizzles in Billa 2 calendar|work=The Times of India|date=22 April 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> An event to launch the official theatrical trailer was planned to be held on 2 July at the [[Anna Centenary Library]] auditorium in [[Kotturpuram]], Chennai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/ajith-s-billa-2-to-have-a-new-trailer-launch-news-tamil-mg3iopecfih.html?scategory=tamil|title=Ajith's 'Billa 2' to have a new trailer launch|publisher=Sify|date=29 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> The entire cast and crew along with Russian dancers were expected to attend the function, which was to be telecast on television later.<ref name=\"indiatimes3\">{{cite news|author=Lata Srinivasan|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-03/news-interviews/32509437_1_trailer-ajith-venue|title=Billa II trailer launch cancelled; fans upset|work=The Times of India|date=3 July 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> The event was cancelled at short notice.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-trailer-launch-cancelled-news-tamil-mhcjXWidhdi.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 trailer launch cancelled|publisher=Sify|date=2 July 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> The trailer was however uploaded to YouTube the same day, gaining record views.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/billa-2-grand-trailer-launch-on-july-2/268433-71-180.html|title='Billa 2': Grand trailer launch on July 2|publisher=CNN-IBN|date=28 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-new-trailer-rocks-news-tamil-mhdku4gjejg.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 new trailer rocks!|publisher=Sify|date=3 July 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> Moreover, a promotional video featuring Ajith with composer Yuvan Shankar Raja was shot as well, but was not released either.<ref name=\"indiatimes3\"/>\n\n==Release==\nBilla 2 was released in 2500 theatres worldwide.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}} On first day Mayajaal Multiplex released Billa 2 in all screens and all shows \u2013 a total of 102 shows in 14 screens. \nThe overseas distribution rights were sold for 53&nbsp;million to the US-based company GK Media, the highest ever for an Ajith film.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\"/> In March 2012, The [[Sun TV (India)|Sun TV]] bought the satellite rights for a record price,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/79307.html|title=Sun bags Ajith's 'Billa 2' satellite rights!|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> with sources estimating the price at {{INR}}6&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|author=Prakash|url=http://entertainment.oneindia.in/tamil/news/2012/billa-2-satellite-rights-130312.html|title=Billa 2 satellite rights sold for Rs 6.25 cr|publisher=Oneindia.in|date=13 March 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> Three prominent production houses were reportedly trying to purchase the domestical theatrical rights then.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-satellite-rights-sold-news-tamil-mdnro2fccdh.html|title=Billa 2 satellite rights sold|publisher=Sify|date=13 March 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> [[Venu Ravichandran]]'s [[Aascar Films]] eventually acquired the theatrical distribution rights of Tamil Nadu for {{INR}}260&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|author=22 April 2012 By Anupama Subramanian DC chennai|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/kollywood/%E2%80%98billa-2-worth-shot%E2%80%99-877|title='Billa 2 is worst film ever in Ajith's career |work=Deccan Chronicle|date=22 April 2012|accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-records-rs-40-crore-sales-in-rights-news-tamil-meyjRKidiae.html|title=Billa 2 records Rs 3Crore sales in rights!|publisher=Sify.com|date=24 April 2012|accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref> All the distribution rights of the film, except the Kerala and Hindi dubbing rights had been sold at a record price of more than {{INR}}400&nbsp;million, making ''Billa II'' one of the top pre-release revenue generating films of all time in the Tamil film industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-ajith-starrer-billa-2-sold-for-record-price/20120424.htm|title=Ajith-starrer Billa 2 sold at record price \u2013 Rediff.com Movies|publisher=Rediff.com|date=24 April 2012|accessdate=28 April 2012}}</ref> In early May 2012, the Kerala release rights were finally sold to Sagara Entertainment and Money Tree Entertainment for {{INR}}8million, likewise a new record for an Ajith film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-kerala-rights-sold-news-malayalam-mfdkE1fcaig.html?scategory=tamil|title=Billa 2- Kerala rights sold|publisher=Sify|date=3 March 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> ''Billa II'' received an adult rating (\"A\" certificate) from the [[Central Board of Film Certification]], due to its \"high glamour quotient, violence and the mature content\".<ref>{{cite web|title='Billa 2' gets 'A'! Release date & certificate rating to change?|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/82896.html|work=Indiaglitz|accessdate=16 June 2012}}</ref> In the UK, the film was issued an [[15 (British Board of Film Classification)|15 certificate]] by the [[British Board of Film Classification]] with an advice that it contained \"very strong violence and revenge theme\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/AFF291235/|title=British Board of Film Classification|publisher=BBFC|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Billa II'' was initially planned to release on 13 April 2012, coinciding with [[Puthandu|Tamil New Year]], but the release was postponed to 1 May 2012, coinciding with Ajith Kumar's birthday,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/82273.html|title='Billa 2' likely to release on july 8|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=18 May 2012}}</ref> with the makers considering to bring forward the film by four days to release it on a Friday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/billa-iis-title-song-to-be-released-this-week/235197-8-68.html|title=Ajith's Billa II's title song to be released in March 2012|work= CNN-IBN|date=|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> However, the release became further delayed and was pushed to the second half of May 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-release-postponed-further-news-kollywood-mdkj7kfbedg.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 release postponed further|publisher=Sify|date=10 March 2012|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/79179.html|title='Billa 2' sees a delay in release?|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=|accessdate=28 March 2012}}</ref> After considering the first four Fridays in June 2012 for the film's release,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-re-recording-in-mumbai-news-tamil-mfvrmEjheeb.html?ref=false|title=Billa 2 re-recording in Mumbai?|publisher=Sify|date=21 March 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/ajith-s-billa-2-on-june-8-news-tamil-mfsh7Kgebfa.html?ref=false|title=Ajith's 'Billa- 2' on June 8?|publisher=Sify|date=18 March 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/the-biggies-are-coming-news-tamil-mgcmabddfjd.html?ref=false|title=The Biggies are coming!|publisher=Sify|date=2 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jun-12-03/billa-2-chakri-toleti-20-06-12.html|title=Billa 2 has unexpected twists: Chakri Toleti|publisher=behindwoods|date=20 June 2012|accessdate=20 June 2012}}</ref> the producer finally zeroed in on 13 July as the release date.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-26/news-interviews/32424299_1_wide-angle-creations-billa-aascar-films|title= Billa 2 from July 13|date=26 June 2012 | work=The Times of India}}</ref>\n\n''Billa 2'' was released across over 1,400 screens worldwide, making it one of the largest Tamil releases ever.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\"/> The film was released simultaneously in the four southern states, Tamil Nadu, Karnataka, Andhra Pradesh and Kerala as well as in North India and international markets.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\"/> In Tamil Nadu, it opened across 550 theatres,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sify.com/movies/billa-2-confirmed-for-july-13-news-tamil-mgyqOzhdiid.html?scategory=tamil|title=Billa 2 confirmed for July 13|publisher=Sify|date=24 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> while a [[dubbing (filmmaking)|dubbed]] Telugu version of the film released in Andhra Pradesh as ''David Billa''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/telugu/article/80871.html|title=Ajith's Billa2 will be dubbed into Telugu|publisher=IndiaGlitz|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> In Kerala, the Tamil version was screened and Karnataka saw the release of both the versions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/article/82857.html|title='Billa 2': Release plans|publisher=IndiaGlitz|date=13 June 2012|accessdate=13 July 2012}}</ref> The film was also released by Aanna Films in most of the major multiplexes in France with French subtitles;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindwoods.com/tamil-movie-news-1/jun-12-01/billa-2-ajith-05-06-12.html|title=Billa 2 goes to France|publisher=Behindwoods|date=5 June 2012|accessdate=5 June 2012}}</ref> in Malaysia, North India and the Gulf Nations, [[Malay language|Malay]], [[Hindi]] and [[Arabic]] subtitles were added to the film, respectively, while in other international markets, it was screened with English subtitles.<ref name=\"autogenerated3\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-06-06/news-interviews/32078091_1_chakri-toleti-tinsel-town-subtitles|title=Billa 2 in multiple languages|work=Times of India|date=9 June 2012|accessdate=9 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Reception===\nKarthik Subramanian of ''[[The Hindu]]'' said, \"Where the movie lacks in substance, it does try to score with technical aspects. The camerawork by R. D. Rajasekhar, background score by Yuvan Shankar Raja and editing by [[Suresh Urs]] are superlative for the most part\", and that the film \"does live up to the hype\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Karthik Subramanian |url=http://www.thehindu.com/arts/cinema/article3639256.ece |title=Arts / Cinema : Does 'Billa II' beckon? |work=The Hindu |date=14 July 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012 |location=Chennai, India}}</ref> [[MSN|MSN India]] said \"''Billa 2'' would be an interesting film for ajith fans&watchable film for general audience\"<ref name=MSN>{{cite web |author=Ians |url=http://entertainment.in.msn.com/southcinema/reviews/review-billa-2 |title=Review: 'Billa 2' \u2013 Reviews |publisher=MSN India Entertainment |date=16 July 2012 |accessdate=15 May 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002190033/http://entertainment.in.msn.com/southcinema/reviews/review-billa-2 |archive-date=2 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nMeena Iyer of ''[[The Times of India]]'' recommended it with a 3 star rating, \"If you're {{sic|a|hide=yes}} Ajith fan\u2014''Billa 2'' is a must. If you're an action aficionado, it's a treat. If you're neither, then don't bother.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/regional/tamil/movie-reviews/Billa-2/movie-review/14864866.cms |title=Billa 2 movie review: Wallpaper, Story, Trailer at Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date= |accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> Indiaglitz called it as a slick entertainer running for just 129 minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/tamil/review/12833.html |title=Billa II Tamil Movie Review \u2013 cinema preview stills gallery trailer video clips showtimes |publisher=IndiaGlitz |date=13 July 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> Prathibha Parameswaran of [[IBN Live]] said, \"If you liked ''[[Billa 2007|Billa]]'' and ''[[Mankatha]]'', and expected as much from the prequel, it falls well short of expectations.\" and further wrote, \"watch it only for Thala.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/review-watch-sluggish-billa-2-only-for-ajith/271114-71-178.html |title=Tamil Review: 'Billa 2' lacks pace, but watch it for Ajith if you must- Tamil Reviews- IBNLive |publisher=Ibnlive.in.com |date=13 July 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref> Anupama Subramanian of [[Deccan Chronicle]] rated the film 3 out of 5 stars and said, \"The film works to a great extent because of the sheer screen presence of a star called Ajith Kumar. After all, it is his film all the way!\"<ref name=DECCAN>{{cite news|author=Anupama Subramanian |url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/movie-reviews/billa-2-review-no-message-behind-violence-749 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120726114209/http://www.deccanchronicle.com/channels/showbiz/movie-reviews/billa-2-review-no-message-behind-violence-749 |archivedate=26 July 2012 |title=Billa 2 review: No message behind the violence |work=Deccan Chronicle |date=15 July 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Box office===\n\n====India====\nIn the domestic market, ''Billa II'' had a great opening with 95% occupancy in single screens and multiplexes. In the opening week, it grossed around {{INR}}4.79 crore at the Chennai box office and after 5 weeks, it amounted to {{INR}}7.79 crore after tax deduction. It grossed around 41 crore at Tamil Nadu, 2.4 crore at kerala, 2.1 crore at karnataka, 2 crore at andra and  1 crore at rest of India.<ref name=\"OPEN\">{{cite web|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/ajith-kumars-billa-2/1/208645.html |title=Ajith Kumar's Billa 2 continues to get thumpdown response at box office : Bollywood, News \u2013 India Today |publisher=Indiatoday.intoday.in |date=17 July 2012 |accessdate=9 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://behindwoods.com/tamil-movies/billa-2/billa-2-box-office-aug-12.html |title=Billa 2 box office collection |publisher=Behindwoods.com |date= |accessdate=15 May 2013}}</ref> The film did not get exemption from entertainment tax due to A certificate. It yielded {{INR}}7 crore or 10 per cent of the total entertainment tax revenue of the year for the exchequer.\n\n====Overseas====\nIn Malaysia, ''Billa II'' collected US$348,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/intl/malaysia/yearly/?yr=2012&p=.htm|title=2012 Malaysia Yearly Box Office Results|publisher=|accessdate=30 September 2016}}</ref> The film grossed $78,000 in the UK<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?page=&country=UK&wk=2012W29&id=_fBILLA201|title=Billa 2|publisher=|accessdate=30 September 2016}}</ref> and approximately $20,000 in Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/intl/?page=&country=AU&wk=2012W29&id=_fBILLA201|title=Billa 2|publisher=|accessdate=30 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=1891755}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|id=billa_2|title=Billa II}}\n\n{{Don film series|state=expanded}}\n{{Chakri Toleti}}\n{{Salim-Javed}}\n\n[[Category:Indian gangster films]]\n[[Category:2012 films]]\n[[Category:2010s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime action films]]\n[[Category:2010s crime thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s prequel films]]\n[[Category:Indian action thriller films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Puducherry]]\n[[Category:Films featuring an item number]]\n[[Category:Films about organised crime in India]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Goa]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Tbilisi]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Georgia (country)]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Yuvan Shankar Raja]]\n[[Category:2010s Tamil-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian crime action films]]\n[[Category:Indian crime thriller films]]\n", "name_user": "Munasabu", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billa_II"}
{"title_page": "The Music Man", "text_new": "{{About|the stage musical|the 1962 film adaptation|The Music Man (1962 film)|the 2003 made-for-television adaptation|The Music Man (2003 film)|other uses|Music Man (disambiguation){{!}}Music Man}}\n{{Infobox Musical\n| name        = \"The Music Man\"\n| image       = TheMusicManPoster.jpg\n| caption     = Original Broadway Poster\n| music       = [[Meredith Willson]]\n| lyrics      = Meredith Willson\n| book        = Meredith Willson <br> [[Franklin Lacey]]\n| productions = 1957 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] <br /> 1961 [[West End Theatre|West End]] <br /> 1980 Broadway revival <br /> 2000 Broadway revival market productions THAT HAVE OFFICIALLY OPENED. -->\n<!-- Please do not include production-specific (acting, directing, etc.) awards -->\n| awards      = [[Tony Award for Best Musical]] \n}}\n'''''The Music Man''''' is a [[musical theatre|musical]] with book, music, and lyrics by [[Meredith Willson]], based on a story by Willson and [[Franklin Lacey]]. The plot concerns [[confidence trick|con man]] Harold Hill, who poses as a boys' band organizer and leader and sells band instruments and uniforms to na\u00efve [[Midwestern United States|Midwestern]] townsfolk, promising to train the members of the new band. Harold is no musician, however, and plans to skip town without giving any music lessons. Prim librarian and piano teacher Marian sees through him, but when Harold helps her younger brother overcome his lisp and social awkwardness, Marian begins to fall in love. Harold risks being caught to win her.\n\nIn 1957, the show became a hit on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]], winning five [[Tony Award]]s, including Best Musical, and running for 1,375 performances.<ref name=Kenrick2010/> The [[cast album]] won the first [[Grammy Award for Best Musical Theater Album]] and spent 245 weeks on the Billboard charts. The show's success led to revivals, including a long-running 2000 Broadway revival, a popular [[The Music Man (1962 film)|1962 film adaptation]] and a 2003 [[The Music Man (2003 film)|television adaptation]]. It is frequently produced by both professional and amateur theater companies.<ref name=Kenrick2010>{{cite book|author=John Kenrick|title=Musical Theatre: A History| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n1DKBAAAQBAJ&pg=PT238|date=25 March 2010|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=978-1-4411-4811-7|page=238}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n[[Meredith Willson]] was inspired by his boyhood in [[Mason City, Iowa]], to write and compose his first musical, ''The Music Man''.<ref>Original 1962 Movie Soundtrack CD booklet</ref> Willson began developing this theme in his 1948 memoir, ''And There I Stood With My Piccolo.''<ref name=Suskin>Suskin, Steven. ''Opening Night on Broadway: A Critical Quotebook of the Golden Era of the Musical Theatre'', pp. 460-64. Schirmer Books, New York, 1990. {{ISBN|0-02-872625-1}}</ref> He first approached producers [[Cy Feuer]] and Ernest Martin for a television special, and then [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] producer [[Jesse L. Lasky]]. After these and other unsuccessful attempts, Willson invited [[Franklin Lacey]] to help him edit and simplify the libretto. At this time, Willson considered eliminating a long piece of dialogue about the serious trouble facing River City parents.  Willson realized it sounded like a lyric, and transformed it into the [[patter song]] \"[[Ya Got Trouble]]\".<ref>Bloom, Ken and Vlastnik, Frank. ''Broadway Musicals: The 101 Greatest Shows of all Time'', pp. 215-16. Black Dog & Leventhal Publishers, New York, 2004. {{ISBN|1-57912-390-2}}</ref> Willson wrote about his trials and tribulations in getting the show to Broadway in his book ''But He Doesn't Know the Territory''.<ref>Filchia, Peter. [http://www.playbill.com/article/stagestruck-by-peter-filichia-but-he-did-know-the-territory-willson-the-music-man-com-80116 \"Stagestruck by Peter Filichia: But He Did Know the Territory? Willson & ''The Music Man''], ''Playbill'', February 17, 1999, accessed February 5, 2019</ref>\n\nThe character Marian Paroo was inspired by Marian Seeley of [[Provo, Utah]], who met Willson during [[World War II]], when Seeley was a medical records librarian.<ref>\"A Pair of Marians\". ''[[American Libraries]]'', the journal of the [[American Library Association]], March 2005 issue, p. 12</ref> In the original production (and the film), the School Board was played by the 1950 International Quartet Champions of the [[Barbershop Harmony Society|Society for the Preservation and Encouragement of Barber Shop Quartet Singing in America]] (SPEBSQSA),<ref>Although SPEBSQSA retains its full name for legal purposes, it is now known by its decades-old official alternate name, [[Barbershop Harmony Society]].</ref> the [[Buffalo Bills (quartet)|Buffalo Bills]]. Robert Preston claimed that he got the role of Harold Hill despite his limited singing range because, when he went to audition, they were having the men sing \"Trouble\". The producers felt it would be the most difficult song to sing, but with his acting background, it was the easiest for Preston.{{Citation needed|date=March 2008}}\n\n==Productions==\n[[File:Joan Weldon-Forrest Tucker in The Music Man.jpg|thumb|Weldon and Tucker in the National Tour, 1960]]\n===Original Broadway production===\nAfter years of development, a change of producers, almost forty songs (twenty-two were cut), and more than forty drafts, the original [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production was produced by [[Kermit Bloomgarden]], directed by [[Morton DaCosta]] and choreographed by [[Onna White]].  It opened on December 19, 1957, at the [[Majestic Theatre (Broadway)|Majestic Theatre]].<ref>Filichia, Peter. ''Let's Put on a Musical!'' p. 52. VNU Business Media, 1993. {{ISBN|0-8230-8817-0}}</ref> It remained at the Majestic for nearly three years before transferring to [[The Broadway Theatre]] to complete its 1,375-performance run on April 15, 1961. The original cast included [[Robert Preston (actor)|Robert Preston]] (who reprised his role in the [[The Music Man (1962 film)|1962 screen adaptation]]) as Harold Hill, [[Barbara Cook]] as Marian, [[Eddie Hodges]] as Winthrop, [[Pert Kelton]] as Mrs. Paroo, [[Iggie Wolfington]] as Marcellus Washburn and [[David Burns (actor)|David Burns]] as Mayor Shinn. [[Eddie Albert]] and [[Bert Parks]] each replaced Preston as Hill later in the run, and [[Paul Ford]] was a replacement for Mayor Shinn, later reprising the role in the film version. [[Howard Bay (designer)|Howard Bay]] designed the sets. The musical won five [[Tony Award]]s, including Best Musical, winning in the same year that ''[[West Side Story (musical)|West Side Story]]'' was nominated for the award.  Preston, Cook and Burns also won.<ref>[http://www.playbillvault.com/Show/Detail/7849/The-Music-Man \"Playbill Vault: ''The Music Man''\"], Playbill Vault, accessed May 23, 2012</ref> [[Liza Redfield]] became the first woman to be the full-time conductor of a Broadway pit orchestra when she assumed the role of music director for the original production's final year of performances beginning in May 1960.<ref>[[Neil Genzlinger|Genzlinger,Neil]]. [https://www.nytimes.com/2018/12/28/obituaries/liza-redfield-dead.html?rref=collection%2Fsectioncollection%2Fobituaries&action=click&contentCollection=obituaries&region=rank&module=package&version=highlights&contentPlacement=5&pgtype=sectionfront \"Liza Redfield, Who Broke a Broadway Barrier, Is Dead at 94\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', December 28, 2018</ref> The long-running US national tour opened in 1958, starring [[Forrest Tucker]] as Hill and [[Joan Weldon]] as Marian.<ref name=Ovrtur>[http://www.ovrtur.com/show/120385/productions \"Productions\"], Ovrtur.com, accessed January 12, 2016</ref><ref>Hudson, Edward. [https://www.nytimes.com/1986/10/27/obituaries/forrest-tucker-67-is-dead-film-tv-and-stage-veteran.html \"Forrest Tucker, 67, Is Dead; Film, TV and Stage Veteran\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', October 27, 1986, accessed February 7, 2017</ref>\n\n===First Australia and UK productions===\nThe first Australian production ran from March 5, 1960, to July 30, 1960, at the [[Princess Theatre, Melbourne|Princess Theatre]] in Melbourne, and at the [[New Tivoli Theatre, Sydney|Tivoli Theatre]] in Sydney from December 13, 1960 to February 4, 1961.<ref>[https://www.ausstage.edu.au/pages/work/918 ''The Music Man''], AusStage.edu.au, accessed June 10, 2017</ref> The first UK production opened at [[Bristol Hippodrome]], transferring to London's [[West End theatre|West End]] at the [[Adelphi Theatre]] on March 16, 1961, starring [[Van Johnson]], Patricia Lambert, [[C. Denier Warren]], [[Ruth Kettlewell]] and [[Dennis Waterman]]. It ran for 395 performances at the Adelphi.<ref name=\"Ovrtur\" />\n\n===Subsequent productions===\nA two-week revival at [[New York City Center]] ran in June 1965, directed by [[Gus Schirmer, Jr.]] and starring [[Bert Parks]] as Harold Hill. [[Doro Merande]] and [[Sandy Duncan]] played, respectively, Eulalie and Zaneeta Shinn.<ref name=Ovrtur/> A three-week revival, directed and choreographed by [[Michael Kidd]], ran in June 1980, also at the New York City Center. The cast included [[Dick Van Dyke]] as Hill, [[Meg Bussert]] as Marian, [[Christian Slater]] as Winthrop, [[Carol Arthur]] as Mrs. Paroo, and Iggie Wolfington (who played Marcellus in the 1957 production) as Mayor Shinn.<ref name=Ovrtur/> In 1987, a Chinese translation of the musical was staged at [[Beijing]]'s Central Opera Theater.<ref>Gargan, Edward A. [https://www.nytimes.com/1987/04/19/theater/trouble-in-river-city-right-here-in-beijing.html?scp=13&sq=Music%20Man%20Beijing%20opera&st=cse&pagewanted=1/  \"Trouble in River City, Right Here in Beijing\"], ''The New York Times'', April 19, 1987, accessed May 23, 2012</ref> [[New York City Opera]] staged a revival from February to April 1988, directed by Arthur Masella and choreographed by [[Marcia Milgrom Dodge]], starring [[Bob Gunton]] as Hill, with [[Muriel Costa-Greenspon]] as Eulalie and [[James Billings]] as Marcellus.<ref name=Ovrtur/>\n\nAnother Broadway revival, directed and choreographed by [[Susan Stroman]], opened on April 27, 2000, at the [[Neil Simon Theatre]], where it ran for 699 performances and 22 previews. The cast included [[Craig Bierko]] (making his Broadway debut) as Hill and [[Rebecca Luker]] as Marian. [[Robert Sean Leonard]] and [[Eric McCormack]] portrayed Hill later in the run. In 2008, there was a revival at the [[Chichester Festival Theatre]], England, starring [[Brian Conley]] as Hill and [[Scarlett Strallen]] as Marian.<ref>Connor, Sheila. [http://www.britishtheatreguide.info/reviews/CFTmusicman-rev \"Review.'The Music Man'\"], Britishtheatreguide.info, accessed January 13, 2016</ref><ref>Billington, Michael. [https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2008/jul/05/theatre.reviews1 \"Theatre Review. 'The Music Man'\"], ''The Guardian'', 5 July 2008, accessed January 13, 2016</ref>\n\n===Planned Broadway revival===\nA Broadway revival is planned to begin previews on September 9, 2020, and open on October 15 at the [[Winter Garden Theatre]],<ref>McPhee, Ryan. [http://www.playbill.com/article/beetlejuice-to-close-at-broadways-winter-garden-as-the-music-man-revival-starring-hugh-jackman-and-sutton-foster-secures-theatre \"Beetlejuice to Close at Broadway's Winter Garden as ''The Music Man'' Revival, Starring Hugh Jackman and Sutton Foster, Secures Theatre\"], December 9, 2019</ref> starring [[Hugh Jackman]] as Hill and [[Sutton Foster]] as Marian, produced by [[Scott Rudin]] and directed by [[Jerry Zaks]] with choreography by [[Warren Carlyle]].<ref>Rooney, David. [https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/hugh-jackman-lead-broadway-revival-music-man-1194075 \"Hugh Jackman to Lead Broadway Revival of ''The Music Man'' (Exclusive)\"], ''The Hollywood Reporter'', March 13, 2019</ref> [[Jefferson Mays]] and [[Jayne Houdyshell]] have been cast to play Mayor and Mrs. Shinn, with [[Shuler Hensley]] as Marcellus and [[Marie Mullen]] as Mrs. Paroo.<ref>McPhee, Ryan. [http://www.playbill.com/article/jayne-houdyshell-jefferson-mays-more-join-hugh-jackman-and-sutton-foster-in-broadways-the-music-man \"Jayne Houdyshell, Jefferson Mays, More Join Hugh Jackman and Sutton Foster in Broadway's ''The Music Man''\"], ''Playbill'', September 5, 2019</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\n\n===Act I===\nIn the early summer of 1912, aboard a train leaving [[Rock Island, Illinois|Rock Island]], Illinois,<ref>Rock Island is the departure point in the script of the musical; in the film adaptation, the reference was changed to [[Brighton, Illinois]], the hometown of Willson's mother. See John C. Skipper, ''Meredith Willson: The Unsinkable Music Man'' (Savas Publishing, 2015), p. 200</ref> Charlie Cowell and other traveling salesmen debate whether innovations are making their profession more difficult. \"Professor\" Harold Hill is raised as one whose sales skills make him immune from such changes (\"Rock Island\"). Charlie says that Hill is a [[confidence trick|con man]] who promises to form boys marching bands then skips town after taking payments for instruments and uniforms. Upon the train's arrival in River City, Iowa, a passenger leaves the train with a suitcase labeled \"Professor Harold Hill\".\n\nAfter townspeople of River City describe their reserved, \"chip-on-the-shoulder attitude\" (\"[[Iowa Stubborn]]\"), Harold sees his old friend and [[shill]], Marcellus Washburn, who has \"gone legit\" and now lives in the town. Marcellus tells Harold that Marian Paroo, the librarian who gives piano lessons, is the only trained musician in town. He also informs Hill that a new [[pool table]] was just delivered to the town's local [[billiard parlor]], so to launch his scheme, Harold convinces River City parents of the \"trouble\" that can come from a pool table (\"[[Ya Got Trouble]]\"). Harold follows Marian home, attempting to flirt with her, but she ignores him. Marian gives a piano lesson to a little girl named Amaryllis while arguing with her widowed mother about her high \"standards where men are concerned\"; she mentions the man who followed her home (\"Piano Lesson/If You Don't Mind My Saying So\"). Marian's self-conscious 10-year-old brother Winthrop arrives home. Amaryllis, who secretly likes Winthrop but teases him about his lisp, asks Marian to whom she should say goodnight on the evening star, since she doesn't have a sweetheart. Marian tells her to just say goodnight to her \"someone\" (\"Goodnight, My Someone\").\n\nThe next day, Mayor Shinn and his overbearing wife Eulalie MacKecknie Shinn lead the festivities for [[Independence Day (United States)|Independence Day]] at the high school gym (\"[[Columbia, the Gem of the Ocean]]\") but are interrupted by a firecracker set off by troublemaker Tommy Djilas. Harold takes the stage and announces to the townspeople that he will prevent \"sin and corruption\" from the pool table by forming a boys' band (\"Ya Got Trouble [reprise]/[[Seventy-Six Trombones]]\"). Mayor Shinn, who owns the billiard parlor, tells the bickering school board to get Harold's credentials, but Harold gets them to sing as a [[Barbershop Quartet]] to distract them (\"Ice Cream/Sincere\"). Harold also sets up Zaneeta, the mayor's eldest daughter, with Tommy, and persuades Tommy to work as his assistant. After another rejection by Marian, Harold is determined to win her (\"The Sadder But Wiser Girl\"). The town ladies are very excited about the band and the ladies' dance committee that Harold plans to form. He mentions Marian, and they imply (falsely, it turns out) that she had an affair with a now-deceased miser, who willed the library building to the town but left all the books to Marian. They warn Harold that she advocates \"dirty books\" by \"[[Geoffrey Chaucer|Chaucer]], [[Fran\u00e7ois Rabelais|Rabelais]] and [[Honor\u00e9 de Balzac|Balzac]]\" (\"Pick-a-Little, Talk-a-Little\"). The school board arrives to review Harold's credentials, but he leads them in song and slips away (\"[[Goodnight, Ladies]]\").\n\nThe next day, Harold walks into the library to woo Marian in earnest (\"Marian the Librarian\"). For a moment, she forgets her decorum and dances with Harold and the teenagers. Harold kisses her; when she tries to slap him, she accidentally hits Tommy instead. With Tommy's help, Harold signs up all the boys in town to be in his band, including Winthrop. Mrs. Paroo likes Harold and tries to find out why Marian is not interested. Marian describes her ideal man (\"My White Knight\"). She sets out to give Mayor Shinn evidence against Harold that she found in the ''Indiana State Educational Journal'', but they are interrupted by the arrival of the [[History of Wells Fargo|Wells Fargo]] wagon, which delivers the band instruments (\"The Wells Fargo Wagon\"). When Winthrop forgets to be shy and self-conscious because he is so happy about his new [[cornet]], Marian begins to see Harold in a new light. She tears the incriminating page out of the Journal before giving the book to Mayor Shinn.\n\n===Act II===\nThe ladies rehearse their classical dance in the school gym while the school board practices their quartet (\"It's You\") for the [[ice cream social]]. Marcellus and the town's teenagers interrupt the ladies' practice, taking over the gym as they dance (\"[[Shipoopi]]\"). Harold grabs Marian to dance with her, and all the teenagers join in. Regarding Winthrop's cornet, Marian later questions Harold about his claim that \"you don't have to bother with the [[Musical note|note]]s\". He explains that this is what he calls \"The Think System\", and he arranges to call on Marian to discuss it. The town ladies ask Marian to join their dance committee, since she was \"so dear dancing the Shipoopi\" with Professor Hill (\"Pick-a-Little, Talk-a-Little\" [Reprise]). They have reversed their opinions about her books, and they eagerly tell her that \"the Professor told us to read those books, and we simply adored them all!\"\n\nThat night, the school board tries to collect Harold's credentials again, but he gets them to sing again and slips away (\"Lida Rose\"). Marian, meanwhile, is sitting on her front porch thinking of Harold (\"Will I Ever Tell You?\"). Winthrop returns home after spending time with Harold and tells Marian and Mrs. Paroo about Harold's hometown (\"Gary, Indiana\"). As Marian waits alone for Harold, traveling salesman Charlie Cowell enters with evidence against Harold, hoping to tell Mayor Shinn. He only has a few minutes before his train leaves, but stops to flirt with Marian. She delays him so he won't have time to deliver the evidence, eventually kissing him. As the train whistle blows, she pushes him away. Charlie angrily tells Marian that Harold has a girl in \"every county in Illinois, and he's taken it from every one of them&nbsp;&ndash; and that's 102 counties!\"\n\nHarold arrives, and after he reminds her of the untrue rumors he's heard about her, she convinces herself that Charlie invented everything he told her. They agree to meet at the footbridge, where Marian tells him the difference he's made in her life (\"[[Till There Was You]]\"). Marcellus interrupts and tells Harold that the uniforms have arrived. He urges Harold to take the money and run, but Harold refuses to leave, insisting, \"I've come up through the ranks... and I'm not resigning without my commission\". He returns to Marian, who tells him that she's known since three days after he arrived that he is a fraud. (Harold earlier claimed to have graduated from the Gary Conservatory in 1905, but Gary, Indiana, was not founded until 1906.) Because she loves him, she gives him the incriminating page out of the ''Indiana State Educational Journal''. She leaves, promising to see him later at the Sociable. With his schemes for the boys' band and Marian proceeding even better than planned, Harold confidently sings \"Seventy-Six Trombones\". As he overhears Marian singing \"Goodnight My Someone\", Harold suddenly realizes that he is in love with Marian; he and Marian sing a snatch of each other's songs.\n\nMeanwhile, Charlie Cowell, who has missed his train, arrives at the ice cream social and denounces Harold Hill as a fraud. The townspeople begin an agitated search for Harold. Winthrop is heartbroken and tells Harold that he wishes Harold never came to River City. But Marian tells Winthrop that she believes everything Harold ever said, for it did come true in the way every kid in town talked and acted that summer. She and Winthrop urge Harold to get away. He chooses to stay and tells Marian that he never really fell in love until he met her (\"Till There Was You\" [Reprise]). The constable then handcuffs Harold and leads him away.\n\nMayor Shinn leads a meeting in the high school gym to decide what to do with Harold, asking, \"Where's the band? Where's the band?\"  Marian defends Harold. Tommy enters as a drum major, followed by the kids in uniform with their instruments. Marian urges Harold to lead the River City Boys' Band in [[Beethoven]]'s [[Minuet WoO 10, No. 2 (Beethoven)|Minuet in G]]. Despite the boys' limited musical ability, the parents in the audience are nonetheless enraptured by the sight of their children playing music. Even Mayor Shinn is won over, and, as the townspeople cheer, Harold is released into Marian's arms (\"Finale\").\n\n==Music==\n\n===Musical numbers===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n; Act I                                                            \n* \"Rock Island\" \u2013 Charlie and Salesmen\n* \"[[Iowa Stubborn]]\" \u2013 Townspeople\n* \"[[Ya Got Trouble|(Ya Got) Trouble]]\" \u2013 Harold Hill and Townspeople\n* \"Piano Lesson\" \u2013 Marian, Mrs. Paroo and Amaryllis\n* \"Goodnight, My Someone\" \u2013 Marian\n* \"[[Seventy-Six Trombones]]\" \u2013 Harold, Boys and Girls\n* \"Sincere\" \u2013 Barbershop quartet (Olin, Oliver, Ewart, Jacey)\n* \"The Sadder-But-Wiser Girl\" \u2013 Harold and Marcellus\n* \"Pickalittle (Talk-a-Little)\" <!--the title is \"Pickalittle\", per the ibdb; Suskin & Green and other sources add the \"Talk-a-Little\" -->\u2013 Eulalie, Maud, Ethel, Alma, Mrs. Squires and Ladies of River City\n* \"[[Goodnight, Ladies]]\" \u2013 Quartet\n* \"Marian The Librarian\" \u2013 Harold, Boys and Girls\n* \"My White Knight\" \u2013 Marian\n* \"The Wells Fargo Wagon\" \u2013 Winthrop and Townspeople\n{{col-break}}\n\n; Act II\n* \"It's You\" \u2013 The Quartet, Eulalie, Maud, Ethel, Alma and Mrs. Squires\n* \"[[Shipoopi]]\" \u2013 Marcellus, Harold, Marian and townspeople\n* \"Pickalittle (Talk-a-Little)\" (reprise) \u2013 Eulalie, Maud, Ethel, Alma, Mrs. Squires and Ladies\n* \"Lida Rose\" \u2013 Quartet\n* \"Will I Ever Tell You\" \u2013 Marian\n* \"Gary, Indiana\" \u2013 Winthrop, Mrs. Paroo, Marian\n* \"It's You\" (reprise) \u2013 Townspeople, Boys and Girls\n* \"[[Till There Was You]]\" \u2013 Marian, Harold\n* \"Seventy-six Trombones/Goodnight, My Someone\" (reprise) \u2013 Harold and Marian\n* \"Till There Was You\" (reprise) \u2013 Harold\n* \"Finale\" \u2013 Company\n{{col-end}}\n\n''Notes:''<br>\nAs this musical concerns a [[marching band]], Willson's orchestration for several of the numbers includes band instruments.<ref>[http://www.mtishows.com/show_detail.asp?showid=000053 \"''The Music Man''\"], MTI Enterprises, accessed October 11, 2013</ref><ref>[http://guidetomusicaltheatre.com/shows_m/music_man.htm \"''The Music Man''\"], ''The Guide to Musical Theatre'', showing a reduced orchestra arrangement, accessed October 11, 2013</ref>\n\n\"Lida Rose\" and \"Will I Ever Tell You\", sung first separately and then simultaneously, are examples of Broadway counterpoint (songs with separate lyrics and separate melodies that harmonize and are designed to be sung together). Similarly, \"Pickalittle\" and \"Good Night Ladies\" are also sung first separately, and then in counterpoint.  Willson's counterpoint, along with two counterpoint song pairs from [[Irving Berlin]] musicals, are lampooned in the 1959 musical ''[[Little Mary Sunshine]]'', where ''three'' counterpoint songs are combined: \"Playing Croquet,\" \"Swinging\" and \"How Do You Do?.\"  \"Goodnight, My Someone\" is the same tune, in waltz time, as the march-tempo \"Seventy-six Trombones\".<ref>{{cite book|author=John C. Skipper|title=Meredith Willson: The Unsinkable Music Man|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SzB1CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA163|accessdate=5 April 2016|date=12 January 2015|publisher=Savas Publishing|isbn=978-1-882810-78-9|page=163}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1962 movie,<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/the-music-man-original-soundtrack-mw0000193178 \"'The Music Man' Original Soundtrack\"], AllMusic, retrieved June 22, 2019</ref> the 1980 and 2000 revivals,<ref>[https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/the-music-man-12495#Songs \" ''The Music Man'' Songs, Broadway 2000\"] ibdb.com, retrieved June 22, 2019</ref> and some amateur and regional productions, \"Gary, Indiana\" is sung in Act 1 by Harold (1962 movie) and Mrs. Paroo (between \"Marian the Librarian\" and \"My White Knight\"), with Winthrop singing a reprise of it in Act 2 (with Mrs. Paroo and Marian Paroo in 2000).{{citation needed|date=July 2015}}\n\n==Casts and characters==\n\n===Casts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:10; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:10%;\" | Character\n! style=\"width:10%;\" | Original Broadway Cast <br> <small>1957</small>\n! style=\"width:10%;\" | Original West End <br> <small>1961</small>\n! style=\"width:10%;\" | Broadway Revival <br> <small>2000</small>\n<!-- DO NOT ADD NEW CASTS UNTIL A NEW BROADWAY OR WEST END PRODUCTION OPENS -->\n|-\n! Prof. Harold Hill \n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Robert Preston (actor)|Robert Preston]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Van Johnson]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Craig Bierko]]\n|-\n! Marian Paroo\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Barbara Cook]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Patricia Lambert\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Rebecca Luker]]\n|-\n! Marcellus Washburn\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Iggie Wolfington]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Bernard Spear]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Max Casella]]\n|-\n! Mayor Shinn\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[David Burns (actor)|David Burns]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[C. Denier Warren]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Paul Benedict]]\n|-\n! Eulalie Shinn\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Helen Raymond]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Nan Munro\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Ruth Williamson\n|-\n! Mrs. Paroo\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Pert Kelton]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Ruth Kettlewell]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Katherine McGrath]]\n|-\n! Winthrop Paroo\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Eddie Hodges]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | [[Dennis Waterman]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" | Michael Phelan\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Main characters ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:90%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Character\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Description\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Professor Harold Hill\n| A [[Confidence trick|confidence]] man who pretends to be a traveling salesman\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Marian Paroo\n| The town librarian and part-time piano teacher\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Marcellus Washburn\n| Harold's old friend and former [[shill]], who now lives in River City\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Mayor George Shinn\n| A pompous local politician; suspicious of Hill\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Eulalie Mackecknie Shinn\n| The mayor's wife\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Mrs. Paroo\n| Marian's Irish mother\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Winthrop Paroo\n| Marian's shy, lisping brother\n|}\n\n===Secondary characters===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:90%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Character\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Description\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Original Broadway performer\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| The School Board (Barbershop Quartet)\n| Four bickering businessmen united by Hill (Olin Britt, Oliver Hix, Ewart Dunlop and Jacey Squires)\n| Bill Spangenberg, Wayne Ward, Al Shea and Vern Reed ([[Buffalo Bills (quartet)|The Buffalo Bills]])\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Pickalittle Ladies\n| Eulalie's four gossipy friends (Alma Hix, Mrs. Squires, Ethel Toffelmier and Maud Dunlop)\n| Adnia Rice, Martha Flynn, Peggy Mondo and Elaine Swann\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Tommy Djilas\n| A young man \"from the wrong side of town\"; secretly seeing Zaneeta Shinn\n| Danny Carroll\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Zaneeta Shinn\n| The mayor's oldest daughter; secretly seeing Tommy Djilas\n| Dusty Worrall\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Charlie Cowell\n| An anvil salesman who tries to expose Hill as a con man\n| [[Paul Reed (actor)|Paul Reed]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Constable Locke\n| The town sheriff\n| Carl Nicholas\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Amaryllis\n| Marian's young piano student\n| Marilyn Siegel\n|}\n\n==Setting and popular culture references==\nThe ''Music Man'' is set in the fictional town of River City, Iowa, in 1912. The town is based in large part on Willson's birthplace, [[Mason City, Iowa]], and many of the musical's characters are based on people that Willson observed in the town.{{Citation needed|date=May 2010}}. The \"river\" in River City is probably the [[Mississippi River]] near [[Davenport, Iowa]]: the Rock Island conductor's announcing \"River City, Iowa! Cigarettes illegal in this state\" implies crossing the Mississippi from [[Rock Island, Illinois]], into Iowa. The year 1912 was a time of relative innocence, as recalled in 1957 after two world wars, the [[Great Depression]] and the arrival of [[atomic weapons]].{{citation needed|date=May 2012}}\n\nThe musical includes numerous references to popular culture of the time. For example, in making his pitch, Harold Hill lists popular musicians and composers: [[Patrick Gilmore|Gilmore]], [[Patrick Conway|Pat Conway]], [[Giuseppe Creatore]], [[W.C. Handy]] and [[John Philip Sousa]].<ref>[http://www.doggedresearch.com/wilson/glossary.htm Wilson]. Doggedresearch.com</ref> Some of the cultural references are anachronistic: \"Trouble\" contains references to both ''[[Captain Billy's Whiz Bang]]'', a monthly humor magazine that did not begin publication until October 1919, and the nonalcoholic \"[[near-beer]]\" [[Bevo]], which was first brewed in 1916.<ref>[http://www.compedit.com/whiz_bang.htm \"From Scatology to Sociology: Captain Billy's Whiz Bang\"]. ''Studies in American Humor'', accessed May 18, 2010</ref><ref>Axelrod, Karen and Bruce Brumberg. [http://www.factorytour.com/tours/anheuser-busch-st-louis.cfm \"Anheuser-Busch Factory Tour in St. Louis, MO\"]. ''Watch it Made in the U.S.A.: Your Guide to Factory Tours'', Avalon Travel Publishing, Fourth Edition, {{ISBN|1-59880-000-0}}, accessed May 18, 2010</ref> In addition, [[Rafael M\u00e9ndez]] (referred to by Hill as \"O'Mendez,\" a great \"Irish\" trumpeter) was six years old in 1912.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1981/09/19/obituaries/rafael-mendez-75-musician-performed-for-heads-of-state.html \"Rafael Mendez, 75; Musician Performed for Heads of State\"], ''The New York Times'', September 19, 1981, p. 21</ref>\n\n==Recordings==\nThe first recording of \"[[Till There Was You]]\" was released before the original cast album version. Promotional copies of the 45 rpm single, Capitol P3847, were released on November 26, 1957, even before the Broadway production had premiered. Produced by [[Nelson Riddle]], it featured his orchestra and 17-year-old vocalist [[Sue Raney]].\n\nThe [[cast album|original cast recording]] was released by [[Capitol Records]] on January 20, 1958 in [[stereophonic]] & [[monaural]] versions and held the #1 spot on the [[Billboard 200|Billboard charts]] for twelve weeks, remaining on the charts for a total of 245 weeks. The [[cast album]] was awarded \"Best Original Cast Album\" at the first [[Grammy Awards]] ceremony in 1958 and was inducted in 1998 as a Grammy Hall of Fame Award winner.<ref>[http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/awards/hall-of-fame Official Grammy Awards site (The Grammy Foundation)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110122042616/http://www.grammy.org/recording-academy/awards/hall-of-fame |date=2011-01-22 }}, accessed July 4, 2012</ref>\n\nIn 1959, jazz composer and arranger [[Jimmy Giuffre]] released ''[[The Music Man (album)|Jimmy Giuffre and His Music Men Play The Music Man]]'', consisting of jazz arrangements of tunes from the musical.<ref>[http://www.discogs.com/Jimmy-Giuffre-And-His-Music-Men-The-Music-Man/release/1853037 \"''Jimmy Giuffre and His Music Men* \u2013 The Music Man''\"], Discogs, accessed July 6, 2015</ref>\n\n\"Till There Was You\" was covered by [[Anita Bryant]] in 1959 as a single for [[Carlton Records]], reaching #30 on the [[Billboard Hot 100]].<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/artist/279363/anita-bryant/chart?page=1&f=379 \"Chart History: Anita Bryant\"], Billboard.com, accessed January 11, 2015</ref> ln 1963, [[The Beatles]] covered \"Till There Was You\" on their second  LP ''[[With the Beatles]]'' (issued on ''[[Meet the Beatles!]]'' in the United States). Willson's widow later told ''The New York Times'' that his estate made more money from the royalties of the Beatles' recordings of \"Till There Was You\" than it did from the musical.<ref name=CommunityPlayers>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121028005813/http://thecommunityplayers.com/tcpshows/musicman12/TheCommunityPlayer2012.pdf \"The Music Man, On Stage, Screen \u2013 and LP\"], ''The Community Player'', May 2012, accessed February 24, 2017</ref>\n\n==Adaptations==\n{{Main|The Music Man (1962 film)}}\nThe film version, again starring Preston, with [[Shirley Jones]] as Marian, was released in 1962.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/33905/The-Music-Man/awards |title=NY Times: The Music Man |accessdate=2008-12-25|work=NY Times}}</ref>\n\n{{Main|The Music Man (2003 film)}}\nThe success of the 2000 stage revival prompted a [[The Music Man (2003 film)|2003 television movie]] starring [[Matthew Broderick]] as Hill and [[Kristin Chenoweth]] as Marian, with [[Victor Garber]], [[Debra Monk]], and [[Molly Shannon]] in supporting roles.\n\n==Reception==\nThough ''[[West Side Story (musical)|West Side Story]]'' had opened nearly three months earlier, ''The Music Man'' captured audiences, critics and five Tony Awards, including Best Musical. ''[[The New York Times]]'' theatre critic [[Brooks Atkinson]] wrote in his review \"If [[Mark Twain]] could have collaborated with [[Vachel Lindsay]], they might have devised a rhythmic lark like ''The Music Man'', which is as American as apple pie and a Fourth of July oration.... ''The Music Man'' is a marvelous show, rooted in wholesome and comic tradition.\"<ref>Atkinson, Brooks.  [http://theater2.nytimes.com/mem/theater/treview.html?html_title=&tols_title=THE%20MUSIC%20MAN%20(PLAY)&pdate=19571220&byline=By%20BROOKS%20ATKINSON&id=1077011428963 Theatre Review: of ''The Music Man'']. ''[[The New York Times]]'', December 20, 1957, accessed May 1, 2010</ref>\n\nWalter Kerr of the ''[[New York Herald Tribune|Herald Tribune]]'' glowingly described the opening scene of the musical: \"It's the beat that does it. The overture of ''The Music Man'' drives off with a couple of good, shrill whistles and a heave-ho blast from half the brass in the pit, with the heartier trombonists lurching to their feet in a blare of enthusiasm. The curtain sails up to disclose the most energetic engine on the Rock Island Railroad (circa 1912) hurtling across the proscenium with real smoke pouring out of its smokestack and real steam rolling along the rails\".<ref name=Suskin/> Kerr called Preston \"indefatigable: he's got zest and gusto and a great big grin for another slam-bang march tune\".<ref name=Suskin/> Robert Coleman of the ''[[New York Daily Mirror]]'' wrote that the producer \"made a 10-strike in landing Robert Preston for the title role\", stating that Preston \"paces the piece dynamically, acts ingratiatingly, sings as if he'd been doing it all his life, and offers steps that would score on the cards of dance judges\".<ref name=Suskin/>\n\nFrank Aston of the ''[[New York World-Telegram|New York World-Telegram and Sun]]'' declared \"It deserves to run at least a decade\", especially praising Barbara Cook's performance as Marian: \"If all our stack-tenders looked, sang, danced, and acted like Miss Barbara, this nation's book learning would be overwhelming\".<ref name=Suskin/> John Chapman of the ''[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]'' pronounced ''The Music Man'' \"one of the few great musical comedies of the last 26 years\", stating that ''[[Of Thee I Sing]]'' (1931) \"set a standard for fun and invention which has seldom been reached. Its equal arrived in 1950 \u2013 ''[[Guys and Dolls]]'' \u2013 and I would say that ''The Music Man'' ranks with these two\".<ref name=Suskin/> In the ''[[New York Journal American|Journal-American]]'', John McClain deemed the show \"a whopping hit. This salute by Meredith Willson to his native Iowa will make even ''[[Oklahoma!]]'' look to its laurels\".<ref name=Suskin/>\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{More citations needed section|date=April 2010}}\n''The Music Man'''s popularity has led to its being mentioned, quoted, parodied or pastiched in a number of media, including television, films and popular music.\n\n===Television===\n''The Music Man'' has been parodied in a number of TV shows, including ''[[The Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[Marge vs. the Monorail]]\", written by [[Conan O'Brien]]. At some point during the second Broadway revival, O'Brien was approached about playing the role of Harold Hill for a brief run, but he ultimately could not fit it into his schedule. He says, on the DVD commentary track for the aforementioned ''Simpsons'' episode, that it was the hardest choice he's ever had to make professionally, because ''The Music Man'' is one of his favorites. O'Brien did, however, as host of the [[58th Annual Primetime Emmy Awards|2006 Emmy Awards]], sing a parody version of \"Ya Got Trouble\" in his opening monologue targeting [[NBC]] and their slide in the ratings.\n\nThe television program ''[[Family Guy]]'' has parodied the musical at least three times. In the episode \"[[Brian Wallows and Peter's Swallows]]\", Lois chastises Brian's high standards in a spoof of \"Piano Lesson\". In another episode, \"[[Patriot Games (Family Guy)|Patriot Games]]\", Peter showboats after scoring a touchdown by leading a stadium full of people in a rendition of \"[[Shipoopi]]\", complete with choreography from the film. In Episode 22 of ''[[Boston Legal]]'', \"Men to Boys\", Alan Shore sings a parody of the song \"Trouble\" to convince patrons of a restaurant not to eat the salmon.  Several ''Music Man'' songs were used in ''[[Ally McBeal]]'', for example in the season 2 episode \"Sex, Lies and Politics\" in which lawyer [[John Cage (character)|John Cage]] spurs the jury into singing \"Ya Got Trouble\" with him.<ref>[http://allymcbeal.tktv.net/music2.html/ List of music by episode of Ally McBeal] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090226200924/http://allymcbeal.tktv.net/music2.html |date=2009-02-26 }}, accessed April 25, 2010</ref>  Season 2 Episode 15 (2012), \"The Super Speedy Cider Squeezy 6000\", of the TV show ''[[My Little Pony: Friendship Is Magic]]'', makes numerous allusions to ''The Music Man'', including a song based on \"Ya Got Trouble\".<ref>Schenkel, Katie. [http://cliqueclack.com/tv/2012/01/28/cartoonclack-my-little-pony-music-man/ \"Harold Hill comes to My Little Pony \u2013 CartoonClack\"], Cliqueclack.com, January 28, 2012</ref>\n\n[[MSNBC]]'s [[Keith Olbermann]] has numerous times referred to [[Fox News]] TV host [[Glenn Beck]] as \"Harold Hill\" on the air.<ref>[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/30109453 Transcript of April 7, 2009 ''Countdown with Keith Olbermann'' in which Olbermann refers to Glenn Beck as Harold Hill], NBC News accessed April 27, 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/29972795 Transcript of March 30, 2009 ''Countdown with Keith Olbermann'' (same)], NBC News, accessed April 30, 2010</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110714123757/http://rss.msnbc.msn.com/id/30766456/ns/msnbc_tv-countdown_with_keith_olbermann/ Transcript of May 13, 2009 ''Countdown with Keith Olbermann'' (same)], MSNBC, accessed April 30, 2010</ref>\n\n===Film===\nIn the 1960 film ''[[The Apartment]]'', [[Jack Lemmon]]'s character is given tickets to the show but is stood up at the Majestic Theatre. In ''[[Romy and Michele's High School Reunion]]'' (1997), Michele sings \"The Wells Fargo Wagon\". The next year, in ''[[The Wedding Singer]]'' (1998), Robbie teaches Rosie to sing \"'Til There Was You\" for her 50th wedding anniversary.\n\nThe 2006 [[mockumentary]]/[[documentary]] ''[[Pittsburgh (2006 film)|Pittsburgh]]'' centers on actor [[Jeff Goldblum]] as he attempts to secure a [[Permanent residence (United States)|green card]] for his Canadian actor/singer/dancer girlfriend, [[Catherine Wreford]], by appearing with her as the leads in a summer [[Regional theater in the United States|regional theatre]] production of ''The Music Man'' in Goldblum's hometown of [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]].\n\n===Music===\nThe political satire group, the [[Capitol Steps]], parodies numerous songs from musicals, including ''The Music Man''. To evoke turn of the 20th century [[Main Street USA]] at some of its theme parks around the world, [[Walt Disney Parks and Resorts]] uses songs from the show, including: \"[[76 Trombones]]\", \"[[Iowa Stubborn]]\", \"Wells Fargo Wagon\", and \"Lida Rose\".{{citation needed|date=October 2018}} [[Bill Hayes (actor)|BIll Hayes]] parodied \"Rock Island\" in a 1959 industrial musical ''Good News About Olds'' written by [[Max Hodge]], with Oldsmobile product terminology serving as the \"whatayatalk\".<ref>Ruel, Todd. [http://www.goneautos.com/Blog/files/Podcast_009_Florence_Henderson_Bill_Hayes.html \"Gone Autos Podcast #9: Florence Henderson & Bill Hayes-Let's Talk About a Rocket\"], GoneAutos.com, September 29, 2013, accessed October 27, 2018</ref>\n\nThe North Iowa Band Festival in [[Mason City, Iowa]], is a yearly event celebrating music with a special emphasis on marching bands. Willson returned several times to his home town of Mason City during the 1950s to participate in the event, including leading the \"Big Parade\", and the stars of the film version participated in the event in 1962.<ref>Skipper, John. [https://web.archive.org/web/20080525144645/http://nibandfest.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=20&Itemid=31 \"North Iowa Band Festival\"], nibandfest.com, May 25, 2008 (archived)</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n\n===Original Broadway production===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"95%\"\n|-\n! width=\"5%\"| Year\n! width=\"20%\"| Award Ceremony\n! width=\"45%\"| Category\n! width=\"20%\"| Nominee\n! width=\"10%\"| Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"10\" align=\"center\"| 1958\n| colspan=\"2\"| [[Theatre World Award]]\n| [[Eddie Hodges]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"10\"| [[Tony Award]]\n| colspan=\"2\"| [[Tony Award for Best Musical|Best Musical]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Leading Actor in a Musical|Best Performance by a Leading Actor in a Musical]]\n| [[Robert Preston (actor)|Robert Preston]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Featured Actress in a Musical|Best Performance by a Featured Actress in a Musical]]\n| [[Barbara Cook]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| [[Tony Award for Best Performance by a Featured Actor in a Musical|Best Performance by a Featured Actor in a Musical]]\n| [[David Burns (actor)|David Burns]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Iggie Wolfington]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Tony Award for Best Direction of a Musical|Best Direction of a Musical]]\n| [[Morton DaCosta]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Tony Award for Best Choreography|Best Choreography]]\n| [[Onna White]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[